name: Beeched Whale
description: This is a great problem first established by local hard-man, Jonathan Hogue, in 2016. Though this boulder problem is slightly "contrived," it's definitely worth the effort. Fun and stout!    Sit start on the right-most side of the boulder on a match-able incut crimp rail. Work your way left, climbing under the fallen tree and finishing in the middle of the block. Big moves for the finish required, and "beating the forearm pump," is the name of the game with "Beeched Whale," as it's quite long (Around 12-16 moves!).   Stand start directly under the finish and it goes at V1+, worth warming up on!*

name: Beeched Whale, (Left Arete).
description: The leftmost side of 'Beeched Whale,' follow the jugs all the way up. Fun and easy warm up for anyone! Like many problems of Acadia, it will most likely need to be cleaned.

name: Cowboy Junkies
description: Sit start on low arete climb to top-out

name: The flake will break
description: Sit start from the flake and crimp rail, feet out left. Big move right to a good triangular divot, then walk your feet right along the low crimp rail until you can lock off right and move your left hand from the flake to the upper crimp rail. Crux is probably finding feet from which to do the first move. The first move itself might be long for the small.  Nice movement. Walking right into the heel is especially satisfying.  The flake will indeed break, but so will everything.

name: Hyperbole
description: 3 moves, but man-o-man are those moves technical.     On the left side of the parking lot problem is "Hyperbole." It chipped in early 2015, making the grade much harder than originally thought.     Stand start on extremely thin, sharp, crimper edges, with glassy feet. Grab an almost non-existent left hand 3-finger crimp, also heinously sharp, get high feet and throw for the decent top out.     Originally thought of as V4, the starting holds and intermediate left hand crimp, chipped.

name: Hyperbole
description: Sit Start low on left side of boulder, climb up and right to top-out

name: Innocence Lost
description: Tall slab arete further in the boulder field past "Silence is the Questions". FA was done during winter with full snow coverage. The landing is not ideal. This thing is tall.

name: Kara
description: Start matched on an obvious jug under the roof. Make technical moves up the center of the boulder, V4. The alternate start on the left side and finishing in the same spot is V5.

name: Kara Right Exit
description: Start on Kara but traverse right across middle of face to top-out on arete.

name: Parking Lot Boulder
description: The right side of the main boulder in the parking lot, follow the obvious line of holds to a great top-out.

name: Parking Lot Left Arete
description: Start standing with the left hand on the arete and the right hand on whatever you can use. A few moves lead to an easy top out. Short, but a nice easier option.

name: Purity
description: SANDBAGGED: Definition: "deliberately underperform in a race or competition to gain an unfair advantage."    Amazing boulder problem up the hill from "Beeched Whale," this little gem is overhung at about 50 degrees and though short, it packs a major punch...     Feels way harder than V3/4 in our opinion.      Start matched on a decent side-pull, make a dynamic move to a weathered sloper out left, and choose from a shallow flake under-cling or shallow crimp rail to gain the awesome lip.    Big moves and relatively hard, this problem may be one of the best on the island (for the grade)! Very "heady," but well worth the effort! The feet are terrible down low, so use caution, (pads and spotters), as the landing is awful as well. FULL VALUE BOULDER PROBLEM!

name: Purity (Right Variation)
description: Start at the right side of the Purity boulder and traverse left to finish at the same spot as Purity for a much harder, 'sandbagged' variation.

name: Silence is the Question
description: Start low in the cave deep on the left side of the boulder. Make your way out right on sharp crimps and edges to the arete. Reach around the arete to minuscule incut crimps to a scary and committing top-out up the middle. Mantle and heel-hook to finish what feels exposed due to a stepped down landing.     The crux is keeping your feet and butt from dragging on the ground. This problem could be considered, 'sand-bagged.' Also, it chipped in early 2015, so it jumped a number grade.    Start directly on the arete and it's around V8.

name: Unknown
description: Just a guess on grade, I’m bad with that stuff. Sit start left hand on side pull crimp rail right hand low in crack on other side of the arete. Use some neat footwork to stab to crack pod on right side of arete then up to jugs and top out.

name: Unnamed
description: Start standing with your left hand on a sidepull at around 6 feet and your right hand on the arete at the same level. Pull on, bump the right hand higher on the arete and then deadpoint for the lip. A fun line on friendly holds. Better than 'Hyperbole' in my opinion...

name: Agador Spartacus
description: A nice line in the alcove with some thoughtful movements and just cool with your back to the ocean.  BETA: start in the lowest portion of the alcove in the center back.  start with hands wrapped over a dull knife edge.  set feet and lean back to hit a good block behind you.  let feet swing to the left and dig a toe in.  match hands on the block/bulge.  throw up for a decent ledge and match again.  find the ok crimp to bump up to a decent hold and then either top out or traverse right.

name: Salutations
description: Good jug start, then work up the slab to a layback finish.   V1 variation in red to the left.

name: Spiderpig
description: Start with matched undercling and move up the arête, then mantle and gain a slabby finish.

name: Telegraph
description: Half sit start under the small overhang, left hand gripping the undercling from Spiderpig, bring your right hand to the corner crack, and slide your left up the face crack to the telegraph hole. Keep on keeping on to a top out, and walk off right.

name: Hike in your flip flops
description: Seated start with hands in the lower cracks. Reach out with your right hand up and to the right and get your feet up to move out left towards the slab before topping out.

name: No Evil Under the Sun
description: Start very low on right undercling and left side pull with high left heel hook. Climb up and right out prow.

name: The Butterfield Line
description: This is the vertical line near the left end of the wall that follows a thin crack and a series of sloping holds.  Some of the holds can be a little wet, which can be an unpleasant surprise as you approach the top.  Pretty Exciting towards the top of it!    For what it is worth, my rating here is mostly a shot in the dark... It has been a while since I climbed this last.  I will update after my next visit to the problem.

name: The Traverse
description: Start from one end, finish at the other.  Stay around the middle height wise.  I usually start from the left end to get the hard stuff out of the way before I am too pumped.

name: Woodland Wordplay
description: Nice little mixed skill piece...rock quality is so-so, but depending on the rainfall, can get mossy or overgrown with lichen and can force some challenging foot placements throughout the year.  Crimps, smears, a little crack work, and two scoops of courage using the loose block when topping out.

name: Blunt Arete
description: Start low at lip of roof bulge and climb up blunt arete

name: Cave Problem
description: Start in low cave/hole. Climb out of low roof/cave to stance. The Crux is no dabbing on everything.

name: Center Line
description: Start on jug in back left of the cave climb obvious line out center of cave to finish on right front corner of roof. Drop-off. (Top-out has been done but is not recommend, very tall and very chossy, top-out will have an x rating and adds no difficulty)

name: Center right link-up
description: This is a link-up of the center line and the right line via the middle of Slick Willy.

name: Center Right link-up low
description: A different link-up of the center line and right lines via slick willy. This time you climb through the back of the cave on the starting holds of all the boulders. Finish out the right line.

name: Monkey Fingers (aka the left line)
description: Start on far left side of roof, climb straight out to a huge move to the finish hold.

name: Right Line
description: Start low on two good crimps at far right side of big roof. Climb up edge of roof and out right to jug. drop off or top out in the tall choss.

name: Slick Willy
description: start on good hold in back middle of roof, climb out and right to a jug. Drop-Off

name: Super Center Stand
description: Stand start on the right-hand edge and a left-hand pinch, do a large lurpy move to a pinch out of the roof, use a massive right drop-knee to navigate edges and use a high toe hook. Finish same as Center Line. The Large jug feature on center line is off.

name: Tug Boat
description: Sit start under low roof on two crimps, climb out blocky feature to top-out.

name: Tug Boat sit-extension
description: More of a traverse, but since it is all under a roof it doesn't feel traversy. Start lower and left of Tug Boat,  climb through Tug Boat and continue right to top-out. 25 feet of climbing.

name: Unnamed Arete Bulge
description: Start sitting under obvious steep arete, climb out the bulge and up to a jug, drop-off or top-out into the choss. (top-out has been done, but is not advised as it is very tall and very chossy)

name: Unnamed V8
description: Sit start under overhang to the left of the cave. pull on with under-clings and climb through a few hard moves to a jug. Drop-off

name: Monkey Pants (direct)
description: Rather than following the obvious jug haul on the left side, stand-start low on the right side with a decent under-cling. Make big moves to the vertical crack and follow the sharp, minuscule crimps, to the same top out as Monkey Pants(left).     Hard and intimidating line due to the ledge out right. Be mindful of a big swing and subsequent landing if you miss the top-out move to the horn, as it's BIG! Before sending it there were several falls that resulted in landing super far back and right of the boulder problem, nearly missing the pads. There are sharp tree stumps in the landing as well. Be cautious!

name: Monkey Pants (left).
description: The left side of the Highway 233 boulder.     Stand start on obvious jugs and work up high to a crimp rail that's possible to match, then throw out right to a sloping side pull on a horn (crux).     Top out delicately as this boulder problem is quite high, with a mantle far off the deck. THE FINISH IS DIRECTLY UP THE MIDDLE, BECAUSE IF YOU STAY ON THE LEFT SIDE ITS CHEATING AND ONLY V1- OR THEREABOUTS. I saw someone recently stay out left on the jugs and that is a different variation. Just a heads up for ethics sake. Finish RIGHT!    This was first established in 2016 by local all around-er, Jonathan Hogue.

name: Playing Hookie
description: On the right side of the boulder, sit start low on decent side-pulls at the obvious 'ledge.' Manage to get your feet on the ledge and, from here, make a big throw, (or REALLY technical move), up the corner to a sloping top out. Top out in the very middle of the proud line, maybe 20 feet off the ground at its apex.

name: Distractions
description: Start in the left corner of boulder with your feet right above the puddle. Traverse right 2 moves with the crux involving high right foot before reaching up. Good hand holds if you can find them before topping out.

name: Mojito Madness
description: Sit start under the left end of the long cave roof.  (See photo on opening page for Monument Cove.)  For full challenge, do not use any features to left for feet.  (Climber in the photo on Monument Cove opening page is doing an easier variation.)  Start with lower body fully under roof and feet only on back wall.  Throw for thin horizontal crack, swing out, and plant a foot on lip of roof.  Go for next-higher horizontal crack.  Straight up to top-out.

name: Right to Left Traverse
description: Start on good hands just left of cave...traverse ~50 feet to end using good hands in crack. Technical crux is moving around arete (no feet!). Practical crux is fighting the pump. V2 or 5.10.

name: Stuck In The Ocean
description: Start on the far right side of the over hang.  Start with a double undercling and boulder out the roof using a variety of tricks. Using the block that “suspends” the roof definitely drops the gade down quite a bit. Super fun and quite unique climbing on solid granite! Bump left hand out to a a crimpy side-pull. Re-adjust the feet and bump to a small right hand side-pull. Get a high right foot on the top of the start hold and big right hand to a jug. High left heel and left hand crosses to a slopper over top of the lip. Right hand crosses to the arete then left hand to a jug on the left lip. Cut the heel and cut feet with the right foot coming back on. Steady yourself then big left hand to a jug. Top out and dance.

name: Unnamed
description: Sit start on the crimps and follow the line in the picture. Not totally sure on the rating --- maybe a more experienced climber can edit.

name: ZigZag to the Stars
description: This Route was discovered by the Pemi-Baker Outdoor Leadership Academy and ascended by Chris Rose while exploring the Monument Cove boulder wall. Chris found this route by checking out horizontal crack systems that were close to the high tide mark. "ZigZag" offers several variations for multiple skill levels. The favorite is the sit start followed by hand jamming the crack. Bring your feet up and finish with powerful mantal moves onto the blocky and sometimes greasy granite. The ocean surf will provide the calm state of mind you need to push yourself mentally past the crux starting move.

name: Jake D by the Sea
description: Crux? pulling over the roof.   surprisingly good sequence of moves under then over the roof

name: Sailng, takes me away
description: sustained route of lie backs and gastons

name: Gold
description: Start under over hang and climb out to through crimps and slopers to top-out.

name: Back to Basics
description: The top out is the most challenging part of the climb, but is not much harder than the rest of the climb. Get feet high enough to reach the jug. Top out to the right.

name: Class Bookshelf
description: This traverse starts right below the easiest way to climb/scramble down into the school house. The traverse is a sit start at the left ledge and finishes by topping out in the middle of the two long walls.

name: Easy A
description: Climb the small sized crack on the face immediately right of teachers pet to the top out.

name: Extra Credit
description: Traverse starting near the entrance of the school house. Start in the center of the southern side and traverse left. Top out.

name: Naughty Corner
description: Use juggy edges in the dihedral to make your way up to top out on the lower ledge to the left

name: Quick Learner
description: Climb from horizontal crack to horizontal crack to top out above the start.

name: Remote Learning
description: Begin on the opening that is located on the 3rd crack in from the edge (sits below two layers of rock -- there are two. Start on the one to the right). Work you way up and left towards the cube, then traverse to the crack located to the left of "Easy A". Top out on the slabs sticking out of that crack. Crux is the section before you reach and pass "Easy A" (crimps).

name: Single File
description: Traverse the northern side of the wall from left to right starting on the crimps and top out right.

name: Teacher's Pet
description: Great hands, great feet. Pinchable chunks for rock in between a 1 foot crack. Most climbers should be able to reach the tops of the pinches and use them as jugs. Well spaced jugs with good feet for the top out.

name: Thinking Cap
description: Start on the crimp line to 1-2 more crimps to get you to the first horizontal crack line. Get feet up to reach up for the top or deadpoint.Top out.

name: Bobkittens
description: Start same as Prow left or Sharks Tooth left? names are unclear, campus to jug in seam and mantle the lip, great mantle practice.  One pad is all you need.

name: Center Crack Sit, Main Boulder
description: The sit to the crack/seam. Hard moves on really small pods lead to the stand, which is more hard moves on small pods. Cool looking line but it’s kind of sharp and odd climbing.

name: Center Crack Stand, Main Boulder
description: Stand start at obvious right hand crimp and left hand pod in crack. Make a few hard moves before reaching easier moves then the top out.

name: Dyno-Soar Right, Main Boulder
description: The right side of the main boulder, stand start at an obvious incut crimp and make a big move out right side to the lip. Traverse back left to top-out mantel.   Here is a short edit featuring this line and more. I've worked hard over the past few years establishing and repeating some of these stellar lines in Acadia National Park, making sure to document much of the climbing on video and paper. Please enjoy: youtube.com/watch?v=Z7N7YUA…

name: Dyno-Soar, Right Side, Main Boulder
description: Start on large in-cut hold on right side of face. Make a big but easy move to a pinch/crimp then go up from there. Sort of contrived, as there is an easier variation just right, but this is a nice problem.

name: Dynosoar Sit
description: Sit start on an obvious left hand crimp and a right hand Gaston, a weird lung/lock-off move gets you into the good edge.

name: Irish Goodbye
description: Climb the arete with really bad holds and big moves. I’ve not tried this but Keenan said it felt like hard 11 and it was a really good line. It looks cool anyway.

name: Its Never Pretty aka Grovel Time
description: This is the roof problem to the right of the obvious slab.     Sit start low and left on a small crimp edge. Make dynamic moves up and right, finishing directly up the arete on good holds.     The crux is groveling over the roof onto the arete off of terrible edges and slopers. If you're taller it makes it easier, but this little problem can be defeating.

name: Left Arete, Main Boulder
description: Sit start low on the leftmost side of the boulder. Work your way up the arete, slapping up the sloping edges and incut crimps to a tricky mantle.

name: Lip Traverse (Right) [aka "Prow"]
description: [NOTE: Apparently the same climb as "Prow" and or "Shark's Tooth right". RHall Admin.]  Coarse rock, stand start on right side of overhanging triangular boulder, and traverse the lip, topping out at the point.    The "Lip Traverse" (right), is a V4 stand start.   There's also a sit start on decent incut crimps, with a heinous heel hook at the beginning.   It is the consensus among locals that the sit start (lowest possible start on the right), definitely adds a number grade to this problem V5 to V5+.

name: Lip Traverse Left, Shark Tooth Boulder
description: Stand start with left hand edge and right hand undercling. Traverse right with funky moves and finish up at the jugs. This thing would be quite a bit easier if the tree wasn’t there, so some funky core tension has to be used or else you’ll just dab the tree. Rad climbing!

name: Lip Traverse Right, Shark Tooth Boulder
description: Sit start on large chalked hold. Climb out the arete/lip with good tension to cool pinches and a big move to jugs. Mantle. Super good problem!

name: Mammoth
description: The massive line on the highball boulder visibly to the left of the Canada Cliffs Main Boulder. This thing is tall and insanely proud. The landing is terrible as well, so come prepared. (30 ft. maybe?!)    The top out is terribly hard. Mantle for your life!     Also, make sure to scope it out and clean it before attempting, as many injuries from ground falls have been reported from this boulder. I myself landed, bouncing off the tree to the ground, and was lucky not to have broken my legs.

name: Nail-biter
description: Sit start low on the left side of the boulder. Start holds are the two slots at the beginning of the crack wide enough for fingers. Work your way a few moves along the crack to the arete, then straight up for an easy top out.

name: Old World Underground
description: On the back side of the boulder featuring, "Steal Once, Pay Twice."     Sit start very low on a razor sharp under-cling with your left hand, and decent right hand crimp/pinch sort of hold. Move up and right on obvious incut crimps, (all of which are quite sharp in nature), and finish directly up the arete on the rightmost side.      The start is hard for the grade. Stand start is maybe V0-, but due to the awkward sit start on terrible smears (and often times damp feet), it was decided to put a V3 grade on it which has been the general consensus since development.    Fun, short; packs a punch!

name: Out and Out
description: Hard face between Mammoth and Irish Goodbye. Start on a crimp rail and climb up with long moves on not so good holds.

name: Steal Once, Pay Twice
description: First established by Jonathan Hogue in 2016, this boulder problem was always on the local boulderers radar, but cleaning and prepping the problem took several days due to heavy liken and moss that impeded the line. After much work hanging in a harness for days on end, Jonathan put up the FA and named it "Steal Once, Pay Twice," a beautiful problem on incut crimps from start to finish!    Sit start with high hands on the obvious jugs. Delicately move up the middle of the boulder on incut crimps and decent feet. It's quite tall and the landing slopes downwards (stepped down), so crash-pads and spotters are recommended.    Here is a short edit featuring this line and more where we've established and repeated some of these stellar lines: youtube.com/watch?v=Z7N7YUA…

name: Synthetica
description: On the leftmost side of the "Steal Once, Pay Twice" boulder, this was first established by local, Jonathan Hogue.     An awkward start down low leads to better climbing up high towards the lip, though the grade is given for the lowest possible start. Start crimped on terrible starting holds and move up and left to a side-pull and a jug, then one big move to the lip (short and sweet), but fun none-the-less.

name: Triangular Boulder, Unknown Slab
description: Unknown slab up the hill from the main boulder. This is a very fun and well protected line, though quite heady due to a tree in part of the landing and it being a slab.    Here is a short video edit made for these areas and more:   youtube.com/watch?v=Z7N7YUA…    Thank you, enjoy your time in Acadia.

name: Unknown Slab, aka "The Blob"
description: Right around the corner from "The Prow," aka 'Lip Traverse Right,' aka 'Shark Tooth (right).'     Start all the way at the bottom of the sloping slab at left, making your way from left-to-right up the obvious line on the corner, topping-out in the middle. (There's a variation that starts directly in the middle and finishes at the same spot that goes at V2-).    Here is a short edit featuring this line and more. I've worked hard over the past few years establishing and repeating some of these stellar lines in Acadia National Park, making sure to document much of the climbing on video and paper. Please enjoy: youtube.com/watch?v=Z7N7YUA…

name: Warm Ups, Main Boulder
description: Around the left side of the main boulder are several V-Easy warm up boulder problems. Decent enough to warm up on and great for the novice climber looking to get a feel for Acadia National Park stone.     The back side of the Canada Cliffs Main Boulder has a couple V0- problems as well, the perfect warm up to check if the rock is dry and climbable, or for beginners, etc. Fun, easy, straight forward climbs with relatively safe landings as well.

name: Bander Snatch
description: On the far left of cliff, follow steep discontinuous crack to tree ledge.

name: Coda
description: Right facing dihedral with a finger crack on left wall. Gradually steepens to slightly overhung, finish up the juggy face after the pin. One of the best routes on Canada Cliff for sure!

name: Commander Salamander
description: Start in the middle of the wall below a finger crack. Climb the slippery face to gain crack.

name: Drunk Seaman
description: Left of House of Detention is this line that follows the line of weakness through two holes. Hard moves are encountered by the first bolt then sustained crimping after the rest. Cool route!

name: Garett's Arete
description: Start 5 feet left of the arete and climb the steep face. Move right to arete, using a short, finger crack to overcome the crux. Finish at tree ledge above.

name: Hombre De Acero
description: Climb the the cracks that line the face. Steep, technical moves on good locks and the occasional good foot will see you through. One of the best crack climbs I’ve ever done!

name: House of Detention
description: Begin at loose, left-arching flake to gain the 1st bolt. Move up and right to large overlap. Pull overlap and continue up steep face to top.

name: Jailbait
description: A vertical crimpy climb with the crux coming after the last bolt.

name: Man O' War
description: The business starts right off the ground. Thin, technical, and sustained climbing for 3 bolts. After the 3rd bolt enjoy easier climbing on fun and interesting jugs. Get a jam in the victory hand crack that awaits you near the end!

name: Mr. Ice Cream
description: This climb is part of an area the guidebook calls the "Outback Wall". Located left to the House of Detention wall, this area sees little traffic and as such is not the cleanest climbing on the island. Nevertheless, there are some fun, short climbs in this area and it's definitely worth exploring further.  For this route you'll climb up to a large-ish first ledge where you can throw in a double knee-bar rest if you're feeling extra. Then follow cracks and ledges up a slight corner to the top of the cliff. Crux is getting through the ten feet of narrow cracks following the first ledge; after that it's pretty straightforward climbing to the top out to the right of the small tree. Anchor off of the large tree set well back from the top of the route; consider bringing static rope to extend the anchor out over the lip or a rope rug to save your rope from wear running over the lip.

name: Mystery Arete
description: As in, It's a mystery why anybody ever bolted it. As the new guide book says, "A tolerable warmup."

name: Russian Revolution
description: Climb an obvious right facing corner finishing in a juggy roof (beware loose blocks). Climb right at the roof and make a move to the bolted anchor.

name: Seasons of Wither
description: Line of bolts in between Jailbait and House of Detention. Crimpy balancy climbing with hard moves near the top

name: Stiletto
description: Climb ledges to the base of a finger crack, jam the crack with the difficulties coming mid way. A sweet obscure crack that deserves more attention

name: Stonecutter's Bible
description: One of the few easy moderates worth doing.  Climb cracks in the corner (perfect foot and hand jams are possible) up into a chimney.  Top out at tree ledge.

name: They call me nasty
description: Stem, jam, and lay-back the detached pillar that forms a right-facing dihedral.  Surmount large block that sits atop the pillar.  Make delicate traverse right (crux, R) with gear at feet to dike with cracks.  Follow dike cracks to belay ledge with detached boulder.

name: Unforgiven
description: Begin just right of arete under small roof. Pull roof to climb face, staying to right of arete. Follow right facing corner to top.

name: Atlantis
description: Crimp your way up to better holds and cool moves which culminate in a sick lieback on finger locks! A truly rad route!

name: Unknown
description: Climb cracks with a few bouldery moves then some balancy moves. Good fun! Good warm up

name: Ballistic
description: Crimpy face climbing on good rock with fun movement. There is a pin but it has been recently replaced by a bolt a foot above.

name: Stratocaster
description: Spectacular arete that is the first route located on the left of the wall. Climb on good edges past 5 bolts. A  medium cam protects the finish.

name: Dragon Fish
description: Was project X3 in Jeff's book. The start is the crux. Bouldery moves on sea polished crimps go into radically steep fins and underclings. Continue bouldering out a body length horizontal roof on a stalactite tooth feature; very strange (V8ish?). After moving through the sea polished roof and statactite, climb through an amazing pocket covered face on a slightly overhanging wall to an another roof. Boulder through this roof into a technical corner. Hang on to the top. Absolutely amazing. No doubt one of the best 5.13's in Maine and the NE! Full value.  Warning: fix a line on Transatlantic, bring some jugs, know the surf report. Not affected by tide, but affected when the swell is pumping. Stick clip the first bolt or hang them on the way down.

name: The FishScale
description: Rappel in with a fixed line to a belay. Then climb the obvious and radically steep prow. Amazing boulder problem to start then endurance and tech to the top. Hands down one of the most amazing hard 5.12's in New England!!!    Was Project X4 in Jeff's Guide.    Warning: You need a low-tide or small surf. Fix a line and know how to jug before attempting. Slightly scary. Hard.

name: Maine Squeeze
description: An exposed step right off the hanging belay takes you to the first bolt. Fun face climbing through one more bolt and power into an undercling traverse. Get further and further from your gear as you round the arete and into a corner with three bolts. Follow this to the top and a two bolt anchor. Rad!

name: Thicker Than Water
description: The amazing crack that splits the sea polished overhanging shield and ends at huge trophy cup jug, climbers right of project X2 in the book, traverse climbers left to a bolted anchor. The gear looks decent.

name: Transatlantic
description: Pitch one: Climb out a roof with tech moves on. Cool features. There’s better gear than what appears from the ground. Pitch two: Start up a face, clipping three bolts, then move into a roof. Climb out the roof into an insecure corner to a jug. Wild moves out right lead to a pumpy finish on not so positive holds. Amazing exposure!! Such a killer pitch!

name: When Six Changes To Nine
description: Was project X1 in Jeff's book, finishes on corner climber's right of shown route in book.   Start in the obvious steep sea polished corner then when the corner ends cut left into a nice crack. When the crack ends, go right off a tufa fin onto more steep fins. Underclings and pinches lead to a final corner. Small cams in seams helpful. Scary. Don't fall off the final corner!! Use the same anchor as sedated

name: 24 Hour Crack
description: The awesome roof crack!

name: Bilge
description: Pluggin pieces with a background of crashing waves, what could be better?    The crux is probably in the first 10-15 feet, weather you traverse out left and back or just make the reach straight up for it.    A guidebook once told me this was about 5.7, but I did some 5.6's the following day at the South Wall which were significantly more challenging. pshhttt, grades...

name: Full Sail
description: Super fun route with lots of flakes to grab on as jugs. Here's the quote from Grant Simmon's guidebook: "An extraordinary moderate. Either start up the obvious groove that splits the cliff or traverse in from the left (easier climbing) aiming for a bolt shared with Rhythm Figure and Bilge. From the bolt climb up and right, passing the Sinbad anchor (optional belay), and continue straight up to another bolt. Finish slightly right on a gorgeous headwall (bolt). Single bolt and small cams for anchor (the first anchor left of the Bilge gully).

name: Head Arete
description: If you have only one day to climb at Acadia, you should head out to the Otter Cliffs.  But save an hour or two to head out to Great Head to do this incredible pitch.  In contrast to the other sections of the cliff that have committing apporaches, Head Arete has a simple walking approach.  It is somewhat tide dependent though, so pick a low tide window to head over or else the start will be wet.    At low tide, the climb starts just above waterline next to the sketchy traverse that accesses the middle part of the cliff.  Clip the high first bolt, and then make a sketchy mantle manuever to get established on the climb.  The cruxiest move comes at the 2nd bolt, where a powerful lieback gets you on to a beautiful headwall.  The next section is why this climb is so classic:  tricky, thoughtful, sustained 5.10 face climbing in a spectacular setting.  The bolts are never so far apart that you could get seriously hurt, but big whippers are possible.  A cam placement in this section helps with piece of mind.  The great climbing, coupled with the fact that your belayer is out of sight and there is nothing but ocean beneath your feet, is what makes this pitch so memorable.  The finish is harder than it looks, so think about it before committing.    One of the best pitches of trad face climbing anywhere.

name: High Noon
description: Was 12 "Hour Crack" in Jeff's Guide. Free climbed by Dave Sharratt.

name: Melba
description: According to the Butterfield guide book, back in 1915 there was an 18 ft. diameter stone tower that stood atop Great Head.  This tower was constructed by the tireless efforts of a donkey name Melba, who hauled in approximately 35 tons of cement and sand.  This route is named in honor of her.    Much like the donkey, this route is stout!    Pitch one starts below the alcove on the left side.  Climb into the alcove.  Once established, traverse right past a bolt to a stance and build a gear anchor.  You could also rappel down to this point from the top of the cliff.    There will two bolts on the roof above you; the left one is for Melba.  It's reachy to clip this bolt.  You can place a micro cam (blue alien) before committing to this reach.  With optimism, climb up over the roof (crux) and through the overhang making some wild moves in the process.  This felt very hard for the grade but is bolt protected.  Move up and left on easier, but non-trivial ground, following a crack system to the top and a 2 bolt anchor.

name: Old Soaker
description: Straight from Grant Simmon's guidebook;     "Share the common start with "Windward Roof" and "Melba", but heads straight up through the roof when those routes split left or right. Gymnastic moves and a meagerly protected corner take you to the ledge."

name: Sinbad
description: Climb up the big ledge thing (careful not to slip on wet rocks!) to gain the first bolt. Off some crimps and slopers, the crux might be gaining the opposing sidepull crimp things to make the second bolt. Some more steadily strenuous moves continue up the bulge, but thankfully there's a victory jug just at the top. Clip that last bolt, mantle up, and continue over easy run out terrain to reach rap the rap bolts in the black "V" groove above.

name: Windward Roof
description: What's fun?    Climbing by the ocean? Finding a way to mantel up an awkard corner using laybacks and/or heel hooks to get established in a corner under a huge roof (crux)?? Traversing left to pull around a big-ass roof that looks much more intimidating than it really is? Slab climbing up backward's facing holds? Turning around and seeing boats of tourist waving at the "Rock climbers, scaling sea cliffs to your right, as Acadia is also a popular spot fo.."    If that sounds fun, this climb might be.

name: Black watch
description: The left most route (facing the cliff) in the M.G alcove. Climb up to obvious groove, near the top of the groove step left onto the face. follow to top.

name: Corsair
description: From the middle of the starting ledge climb the steep finger crack, then straight up past 4 bolts to the top.

name: Highlander
description: From the right hand side of the belay ledge climb a short wall to a stance below a bolt. Climb left to another bolt, then up and left to another bolt. After that step left onto a right leaning ramp and climb up to ledge below the final head wall. Climb up the headwall (crux) to one more bolt and the top.

name: Maritime Nation
description: Start as for Morning Glory but instead of stepping up to the bolts continue up a corner with a finger crack. Make for the roof (2 bolts)pulling it on the left side. A groove leads to a two bolt anchor.

name: Morning Glory
description: From the belay ledge, climb a ramp untill it steepens and then traverse left to a small stance below a large left facing corner. at the third bolt in the corner move left to the arete

name: Trail of Dawn
description: Start as for Morning Glory. When Morning Glory starts to cut left up the corner, Trail of Dawn goes directly up the overhanging wall above and finishes directly between the Morning Glory and Maritime Nation Anchor at a natural gear anchor

name: The  Flake
description: Ascend a right facing crack up a steep wall, skirting the overhang to the left, or direct up through the overhang for a 5.9- variation.

name: Adair by the Sea
description: Steep face moves to a 10 foot finger to thin hand crack, face holds lead to top.

name: Black Crack
description: Fun timing with the tides leads to fantastic and varied climbing.  Liebacking, tricky problem solving through the roof, and crack climbing, or at least some stellar jams.

name: Cliff Traverse
description: Perfect during lower tides, this large traverse can be found towards the beginning of Otter Cliffs.  It is easily over 100 feet long and probably about 20 feet high.  You will weave in and out of large pockets and there is no shortage of holds; you have a ton of rock to work with

name: Crab Roll
description: This is a nice route in a classic Otter Cliffs location. Start from a nice ledge just a few feet above the crashing waves; wet shoes are a real possibility! The climb ascends an obvious crack using face, and jam moves. The crux is down low, the climb eases off as you get higher.

name: Drunken Sailor
description: Straight up the corner between The Great Chimney and Black Crack.

name: Easy Corner
description: Start up corner, traverse out under the overhang then work your way up the ramp/corner.    Climbable in the rain.

name: Engel Arete
description: Crux is a balancy hand move 15 feet off the ground.  Good mix of moves and exposure many feet above the waves.    Route is short but worth lapping a few times to work on technique.

name: Face of the Sailor
description: I believe this route used to be a named 5.11d, but cannot find it anywhere.  It has a beautifully overhanging, chunky, dynamic start and a wicked crimpy face to top, all separated by a flexy roof move.  "I climbed this with Steve-the chimney sweep in '97 and returned 10/2019 with my son & friend.  It did not look like it had been climbed since '97 and I did not see it listed on Mtn Project.  If anyone else has climbed this route and/or would like to edit my post, please feel free"

name: Gallery Arete
description: The blunt arete between The Great Chimney and Rock Lobster.

name: Guillemot Crack
description: On the left side of the Amphitheater if facing the water, right next to the Sea Stack, climb the corner and crack that stays just left of the chimney if facing the rock.

name: Guillotine
description: Follow the wide crack using faceholds and intermittent thin cracks to the upper dihedral crux.  After a funky move or two to get the lieback, move slightly left into the roof and finish with a fantastic overhanging traverse to the right.

name: High Tide Girdle Traverse
description: A good adventure bound to get some funny looks! This is a left to right girdle traverse that can be done anywhere from 6-10 pitches. The climb starts at the Escape Hatch and follows  generally easy blocky terrain within half to two-thirds height of the cliff  crawling around the sea stack (super cool)  and ending on a Dare By the Sea (5.10d). We found the most exciting part of the climb was from Razor Back to Drunken Sailor with options of traversing high through sharp questionable blocks, or low with minimal gear and ground fall potential.

name: In The Groove
description: Start up the obvious flake that borders Wonder Wall, enjoy the variety of moves that can be used to gain the top of this fun moderate flake.

name: Jamcrack
description: Start the same as Summer Camp Corner but continue straight up the vertical crack.

name: Overhanging Corner
description: Start up moderate corner and enjoy stemming, squeezing, and straigh on crack work. Don't forget to look around on either face, good holds abound.    Climbable even when wet (top-rope)

name: Overview of Otter Cliffs "Sub-Areas"
description: M.P. Currently Lists 85+ routes at Otter Cliffs. Current guidebooks break up this huge area (huge in terms of # of routes) into several sub-areas.     These sub areas are generally considered:   [Sea Cave]    (No routes at the moment entered)     [Plaque Wall]    Engel Arete  Jamcrack     [Mermaid Wall]    Greybeard  State of Maine     [Amphitheater Left]    Otter Point  Black Crack     [Amphitheater Right]    Submariner  Guillemont Crack     [Seastack]    The Great Chimney  Swing Time     [Yellow Wall]    Chockstone Chimney  Yellow Wall     [Guillotine Alcove]    Fishermans Folly  Crucifix     [Wonder Wall]    Easy Corner  In the Groove     [Adair Wall]    Starfish  Peak Performance

name: Peak Performance
description: Start 7 ft right of Adair by the Sea. Climb up to the small roof and step left into a short left facing corner to an overlap. Traverse right on a horizontal then trend left on jugs to top out.

name: Small Cove Problem
description: A great problem to warm up on and show off if others are watching.  It is pretty small, only about 4 simple moves and the rock is quite sharp and unforgiving.  The crux is a small dyno up to the top of the cliff, top-out after that.  All in all a real fun and easy problem

name: Sober Seaman
description: Same start as Drunken Sailor: climb the shallow corner, with a side-pull on the left face, between The Great Chimney and Black Crack (or what's left of it). But about 2/3 of the way up, at the overlap, veer left and diagonal to the top.  NOTE- See COMMENT by Eliot Coffey about the route description.  R Hall  ME Admin.

name: Yellow Wall
description: On the left side of the Guillotine Wall if facing the water. Climb the arrete from the bottom to the top (exit left of easier and better protected climbing at the top if need be).

name: 5.6 Wall
description: A great small face with fun climbing and excellent pro. Start on a step in a large crack and work your way up the face. There are a few possible lines, but the central one seems about 5.6. After topping out, you can build an anchor in a crack and boulder about 15' uphill.

name: Widow's Walk
description: Mantel a protruding triangular block. Move right and gain a finger crack on a sloped ledge. Mantel the ledge and walk the finger crack to a pillar. Climb the pillar for a dramatic finish and find an anchor crack among the boulders.

name: 5 Easy Pieces
description: 5 Easy Pieces is classic Jack Nicholson movie about a talented pianist frustrated with a life of mediocrity...oops, sorry.    This is a gorgeous route up the front face/left arête with 5 distinct bouldery cruxes, some of which may induce a heart flutter though the gear is good. As are the rests. This magnificent piece of granite wrastlin' is marred only by the fact that many of the high quality cruxes can be avoided by climbing around the corner to easier ground(The Book of Eli). That makes this an eliminate of sorts but so be it! It's a sensible eliminate that simply climbs an amazing face.    Climb to the alcove ledge of Legion of Decency but instead of mantling reach left into awesome left hand side-pulls. Climb thru a micro seem that leads to a good rest beneath a roof/arête. Resist the urge to climb around the corner onto the slab. Get gear and bust some rad moves to clear the lip and gain a tiny overlap/corner/roof. And a jug which gains access to a no hands ledge. From here, step right to the front face and another sweet set of moves to gain the next overlap/overhanging arête. Climb the arête to an awesome ledge.     The safest way to climb the final crux is to keep climbing rather than stopping to belay here. Leave the comfortable ledge being sure to place some solid pro. Mantle onto a small ledge on the arête's left side. Stick your neck out for some tiny gear in a horizontal, commit to the vertical face, place more gear, and decipher fun techy face moves to a welcome jug. Make one more set of moves to gain another sweet ledge, a great place to belay. The rest is a victory romp.

name: The Book of Eli
description: Climb the first 15 feet of The Weismuller Route, a mega classic though obscure 5.10 crack climb. When you grab a 2 foot tall monolith spike on that route move right using a side pull and sweet incut layback fingercrack.     Decipher a sweet and spicy boulder problem using side pulls and a sloper on the blunt arete. Or move left to an easier slab. From here, climb the gorgeous pink granite face above staying just left of the arete and sometimes using the arete.     When you gain the awesome triangular ledge step left into some nice cracks that lead to another ledge and a good optional belay. Finish up the moderate and gorgeous granite of The Weismuller Route.    Careful of loose rock in the upper crack. It's a work in progress.

name: Legion of Decency
description: Legion of Decency is a magnificent, instant mega classic, and an atypical crack climb of Acadia. Parts of this route may have been top roped by earlier explorers after climbing one of the nearby obscure, un-loved, burly, kickass climbs of the Parking Lot Buttress. The route has never seen a lead climber until recently, which is mind boggling because the route is rather jaw dropping when viewed from the ground. Though having a newly cleaned splitter crack system to send off on certainly contributes to its beauty.   A gorgeous right facing corner crack moderated by a splitter in-cut crack on the right leads to a clean slab with bomber finger sized gear in a sweet crack. A short headwall boulder problem with dueling side-pulls gains a beautiful alcove ledge and the beginning of the business.   From here, jam, side pull, and stem hard off the opposing wall, making sure to clip gear long as you have just embarked on a 50m pitch!   This is a wild, exposed, and super steep crack that would be much much harder if the stemming wall did not exist. That said, this route is definitely harder for climbers of minimal lank. Fully stemmed out, it feels amazing to be climbing such a wild pitch so securely!    There is a potential "death flake" before the crux but none of us have had to pull on it or place gear in it...  The crux comes as the wall steepens slightly , the left crack becomes more splitter, the right side-pulls become less positive, and the stem which gradually widens must be left behind in order to exit left onto the most incredible ledge in Acadia.   From the small triangular ledge which, looks (on a smaller scale) like it belongs on El Cap. Step right into a tough ringlock crux in a chewy, man-hand creating granite crack that splits the very edge of a vertical to slightly overhanging arete. On its own, the next 40 feet of climbing is one of Acadias purest cracks. But this climb is not over! from the top of the crack step left to a puckering face boulder problem, some scrambly stuff, and finish up the dueling cracks of the Weismuller Route on some of the best rock in the country.

name: The Road Not Taken
description: This is a variation that attacks the inviting looking seem/fin overhang at the buttress' mid height. Start on Legion of Decency. Climb to a spike/jug just before the "death flake." Place a .75 or equivalent cam and move left at a small roof with a side-pull and undercling. Climb on the arete and face just left of the crack to situate yourself beneath the imposing, overhanging, seam/fin. Place tiny cams and a tiny offset nut, heel hook, toe hook, knee scum, micro crimp underclang your way to finger locks and jugs of glory!

name: Weissmuller Route
description: At the base of the leaning buttress head up and left through a steep corner on the the face on the left. After a cruxy mantle, follow easy terrain to a ledge and belay. Second pitch follows corner to a roof, tricky moves right and up a easy crack to ledges and belay in the trees. Rappel anchor is climbers right. Two raps back to the ground.

name: Mr Clean
description: Start 20 feet right of whaleback, at the center of the big slab. Follow the weakness through the slab to the overlap, put some gear in and climb sweet cracks up the face just right of overlap. A really good route, classic movement and nice rock

name: Welcome to Pleasure Dome
description: Start same as Mr Clean, at overlap undercling out left and step up to a really nice handcrack in a slab. Another great route here.

name: Whaleback Crack
description: Follow ledges to the left of a Cedar tree then head right into the traversing crack. Follow jams and smears until a vertical crack is reached and jam that to the top.

name: Albatross
description: A high-quality route that is worth your while.      Make a steep move or two into the right-facing corner, and move left onto the ramp.  Climb the face above, then find the path of least resistance, trending rightwards, to the bolted anchors.

name: Balance Queen
description: Walking up from the car this is the first route you come to. It is the start of the "Lower Wall".     A short crack leads to face climbing past two bolts up a corner to a finger crack to a two bolt anchor equipped with rap rings.    careful of loose rock on the upper portion once you're past the bolts, a large rock flexes when a cam is placed behind it.

name: Band of Gypsys
description: This is a steep technical climb up the middle of the sea gypsy headwall (last pitch) It climbs from the 2 bolt anchor on the top of pitch one of Sea Gypsy. Clip the first bolt of Sea Gypsy and then climb straight up to some cam placements. Step up on to the steep face past 2 bolts to an overlap. From the overlap trend left into the crux and try to hold on to the top.

name: Bartleby -(Central Slab)
description: Climb a short, right facing corner to a roof, gain some handholds under the roof and pull around to the left.  Climb a left arching fingercrack up to fixed anchors.

name: Birch Ade   - (mid-cliff START)
description: Start straight up from the Gunklandia second (often first) pitch bolted anchor. Climb through some easy ledges to the short but sweet hand crack and into an easy offwidth section. Head out left on the flake and up the short left facing corner to the top.

name: Boys From Bangor
description: P1: Start on a  big mossy ledge and head up and left to the big corner then make an awkward mantle. Do a bit of jamming/laybacking with decent feet up the good corner then continue way right to a two bolt anchor. It would be a good idea to place a piece after exiting the crack just in case your second blows the finishing moves. 5.7   P2: Continue up and left on a bushy crack for 10ft, then head right through a small overlap shooting for yet another bushy crack. Finish up an obvious corner to another two bolt anchor.    Two single 60m rappels will get you back to the ledge.

name: Byzantine
description: Another high-quality Precipice route.    1. Make difficult, technical moves up the corner to the first block, then follow the cracks above to a two-bolt anchor.    2. We did not climb the second pitch -- if you have, hit the blue "Improve" button above.

name: Chicken of the Sea
description: Climb the face up to the hanging corner (which Trotsky follows), and break left up the steep, juggy flake ladder. Pull up on to the slab(the guidebook called this the crux, but I though the steep climbing was harder, if more secure)and follow the small, left facing corner to a ledge and a gear anchor. Alternatively, traverse right from the ledge and belay from the slings at the top of Trotsky's Corner.

name: Chitlin's Corner
description: A very long corner. This pitch is super classic even thought it has some preamble to it that isn't very fun. Start up the blocky finish, gain the rambling wavy corner and enjoy it to the top. Sometimes the last move to the anchor can be pretty wet.    The first time I was on this climb I was just learning how to trad climb and I placed well over 18 pieces of gear, the next time I was on it I placed 8.    The second pitch is a stiff and thin 5.10a that traverses under a roof.   [ Admin. NOTE: First pitch is a long nice 5.7 pitch that goes to a small ledge and anchor. R Hall, from a suggestion by R Birk]

name: Connecticut Cracks
description: The route follows a series of discontinuous finger cracks.    Delicate footwork marks the crux of the rotue as you traverse left to right between cracks.

name: Country Corner  - (mid-cliff START)
description: Originally submitted by Ron Birk, somehow without the required fields of DESCRIPTION and PROTECTION.     A mid-cliff START this pitch starts at the first belay of "Story of O" and climbs cracks to a belay ledge above. From that ledge the continuation is normally "Vacation Cracks 5.8" which joins P3 of "Story of O" to the rap anchor.

name: Crack Of Senility -(Central Slab)
description: Starts as a hand/fist sized crack that can be jammed and gets progressively larger as it goes up (i.e. you can practically get inside the thing).  After getting to a nice ledge walk up left to bolted anchor, but you may want to add a directional for your second first.  If you like offwidths you might enjoy this, otherwise you might hate it.

name: Dynamo Hum  - (mid-cliff START)
description: [NOTE: A mid-cliff START from the P1 belay of "Story of O". R. Hall, ME Admin.]    A steep left arching crack on the left side of the Fear of Flying Buttress. Climb past an old fixed piton into the widening crack. Belay on the tree covered ledge above.

name: Emigrant Crack  - (mid-cliff START)
description: Striking finger crack that splits the smooth face right of Gunklandia.  One must hang with the crack the entire way for full value.  Stepping left into Gunklandia at any point drops the grade to 5.9.    Descend by walking up and left from the top of the route (exposed class 2+) to the bolted rappel anchor atop Return to Forever.  2-Rappels with a 60m rope lead to the ground.

name: Fat Back Crack
description: High up on the wall left of Sea Gypsy Fat Back Crack is a great moderate route that see's little action because of its location. Get your jam on, stem and layback up the excellent corner to a two bolt anchor. Two 60M rappels will get you back to the ground.

name: Fat Gypsy
description: Starting at the two bolt anchor for the last pitch of Sea Gypsy, head up slightly left then straight up to a bolt. Embark on the seemingly blank slab to a thin crack heading up to a short steep section with another bolt. Mantle up then continue to finish on Fat Back Crack.

name: Fear of Flying
description: Start 20 feet right of Story of O, follow a grove into a slot then up to the roof. Pull out the roof on the left and into the crack above. Super fun!   Amazing finger crack off the 1st pitch ledge of The Story of O -Place gear at any point -Great movement -if only it were as long as Chitlins Corner :/

name: Fingertips on a Seascape  (mid-cliff START)
description: STARTS Mid-Ledge at the belay shared by "CT Cracks", "Old Town" and "Grendal".  Reach out of the left end of the ledge on top of Old Town and clip the first bolt. Make some fingery moves to pull onto the wall and climb up past two more bolts. Make an awkward mantle move above the third bolt then make a couple more moderate moves, ending at a two bolt anchor right below the Return to Forever corner.

name: From Russia With Love -(Central Slab)
description: Climb the crack in the corner. Exit left and climb the crack up left.

name: Gale Face
description: The Butterfield guidebook warns us to be careful getting to the first bolt. After climbing a bunch of easy ground one will be sufficiently high enough to hurt oneself permanently if they were to fall while performing the mandatory 5.9ish move to get the first bolt clipped. This might be a good time for the ol locking carabiner on the first bolt trick. Ed Webster bolted this route on lead. He is definitely The Man! Make thin, technical and committing moves past a drilled piton and another bolt to some much better holds in a suspect flake and go up. Get a bit of a rest, move right into a sea of smooth Feldspar Granite, gain a right angling corner (left wall overhanging) and make committing yet more moderate moves thru the corner making sure to look around for some key footholds. Another interesting flake, the one the gear lives in, allows one to mantle onto the upper slab. Hopefully the aspirant clipped all  of the gear long up to this point because the saga has merely begun. Set sail and get situated beneath the crux finger crack splitting the steep swell of Maniacal Depression. A committing high step gains a solid, bucketous, lock. " Arrrr batten down the hatches matie," cuz its about to get hard! This is one of the few routes I've  been on that goes from slab to vertical to overhanging and back to vertical in 15 feet. Find the sequence thru the series of shallow pods and jams as you walk the plank hanging your butt way out there laybacking the apex of this mounting swell. Get a stance, place some gear in the shin region, and surge up the last sequence. Try not to become Earth's largest land mammal, (The Beached Whale) mantling above small gear with the weight of the rope threatening to pull you out to sea. This is a much better way to access the upper crux of Maniacal Deprerssion.

name: Games Without Frontiers  - (mid-cliff START)
description: [ NOTE - A Mid-Cliff START on the left end of the "Fingers Ledge" at the belay shared by "2nd belay of Precipice Ledges (5.4) " and "Finger's on a Seascape". R Hall, ME Admin.]Follow three or so bolts up to the left of Return to Forever then launch into the thin seam. I’ve not tried it but the gear looks thin and hard to place.

name: Green Mt. Breakdown
description: P 1:  Start up Chitlins Corner.  After 50ft. move up right onto discontinuous cracks to a semi hanging belay ledge (gear).    P 2: Follow corner/ramp to a small roof.  Pull roof (crux) and continue up face to belay ledge (2 bolt anchors).

name: Grendal
description: Start right of Old Town, head up past a big boulder and eventually passing a tree and moving left on to a nice face. Finish on the Old Town ledge.

name: Gunklandia
description: Gunklandia is a local classic, with 3 fun pitches and a little bit of spice at the end. It starts a little down hill from old town.    The first two pitches are commonly combined into one and follow an easy corner system and crack to a spacious belay ledge with rap anchors. From here up and to the right takes you to a bomb bay chimney which puts the sting in the tail of this scorpion.     Have fun.   - - - - -- - - - - - - - - -     [Maine Admin. note: The "Direct" variation ( 15 ft of unprotected 5.9 on P1) probably should be listed here as only a variation, but it has it's own route listing. R Hall. If anyone has a photo of someone climbing it it would be greatly appreciated if you posted it.  I will make it the "lead" photo for the "Direct". ]

name: Gunklandia Direct Variation
description: The direct itself is a short (15 feet) set of unprotected face moves at 5.9 that ascend to and join the main GL crack at its first horizontal break.     It is not "some discontinuous finger cracks that lead up to GL proper" as previously described here -- that IS Gunklandia.    See COMMENT by Peter Lewis.  Most "old" climbs were, and still are, purposefully "sandbagged" as explained in the current guidebook.

name: High Plains Drifter
description: From Pressure Drop/Rusticator anchor, head straight up the slab following a seam/crack. At the head wall, clip a bolt and do a funky boulder problem with killer exposure then follow a hand crack to the trees. Belay off a tree and rap. Bring extra cord for rappel anchor.

name: High Wire
description: Shallow, left facing corner to start and then up cracks to top.to the left of Pipe Dreams.

name: Impalpable Cracks
description: Originally Climbed by Chris Gill and Ray Simpson on top rope. Slab, face, roofs, and heel hooks -- this climb has it all! Off the mid- cliff anchors for Story of, step up, clip a bolt, and traverse the slab to the arete and the face with black streaks. A sneaky nut placement protects the move to the next bolt. Fun  face climbing leads to a crux above the fourth bolt. There are two options here for the finish.The original top rope line climbs straight up to the ledge above, then traverses the ledge to the final crack.The other option, (the more fun and sustained one) is to head left after the fourth bolt and pull the roof, which is directly under the final crux crack to the top. After the fourth bolt all the protection is small and intricate.

name: Jaws
description: Awesome, pumpy, finger crack up the right hand wall of Chitlin's Corner!  Can be broken into two pitches, but link into one long pitch for full effect!

name: Juvenile
description: From Jeff Butterfield's Guide: A quality route. Climb up the yellow wall ten feet right of Small Crack Warning using a short, thin crack for gear. Move up and left past a somewhat hidden bolt to an awkward stance beneath a small roof. Clip a bolt over the roof, then pull over it into the crux, a flared corner with a bolt. Move up and left to reach good holds, then up and right to a 2 bolt anchor.

name: London Bridges
description: Climb the left facing, flared crack by using offwidth technique or laybacking the large flake.  Gain the Old Town ledge and belay from the fixed anchors there.

name: Lower Wall / Alcove / Staircase Break
description: Not a route but a place. This is the talus and vegetated area you come to walking uphill from the car after passing the last climb on Lower Wall (currently Albatross in the current guidebook)    For climbs in the Alcove area (Juvenile, High Wire, Pipe Dreams, Chicken of the Sea, and Trotsky) head up the talus but don't continue on the stone staircase.     For climbs on the Central Slabs ( Bartleby, Sweet Surrender, Crack of Senility, From Russia with Love, Mme. LeBois Plunge, Recollections of Pacifica, and Wafer Step) go up the talus and continue on up the stone staircase.     For other climbs on the Main Wall continue past on the main trail.

name: Main Wall / Alcove / Staircase Break
description: Not a route but the higher dividing line between the routes in the Alcove area (and the staircase leading to the Central Slabs) and the climbs on the main face.

name: Maniacal Depression
description: On the right side of the Precipice, just before you encounter the stairs is an obvious open book dihedral. The start is just left of an obvious short roof crack called Small Crack Warning (5.11d). Climb the dihedral (5.10) to its end and belay on the right. Traverse left to a very thin and flared finger crack. Optional belay here. Tricky small pro and a technical crux climbing the crack past a steep swell leads to easier climbing.

name: Michael's Pin  - (mid-cliff START)
description: Fun corner to finger crack.

name: Midnight Delight
description: Jam the corner. It’s dirty, fun and a good ole adventure! 2 pins and a fixed nut anchor.

name: Mme. LeBois' Troubled Lunge -(Central Slab)
description: Fun route with neat traversing to the left to keep the grade modest.    Step up on the ramp (could be slick...take care) and sink the fingers into the flake over the roof.  Place a bomber cam or two, maybe a nut, then pop the roof to a nice stance.  Step left.  Float up the easy section of Russian Revolution then again step left to avoid the finish of that route.  Milk the arête for some fun and stimulating finish moves which look hard but aren't too sassy.    A long sling on pro at the moves left will nearly eliminate rope drag.    The pin on the upper crack of Russian Revolution could be clipped if need be.  Long sling keeps the drag down here too.      There's a bit of a lack of gear on the upper arête prior to the top out so take care and get good gear prior to launch.    Great finish position on the final arête!

name: Old Town
description: Starts at a fun corner that requires an interesting high foot that will make you get into a fantastic layback that you'll stay in for the rest of this climb. make some fun moves until you mantle the ledge at the half-way point then protect high off the ledge and continue up the upper layback (crux) to the easy topout.   Matthew Fienup:    Truly classic laybacking and stemming at an accessible grade. Every bit as good as it looks.

name: The Philadelphia Story
description: Climb up the small right facing corner/crack system to a ledge.  At the ledge angle right and up through  an offwidth crack, and then move up and left to the anchor.

name: Pipe Dreams
description: Start left of the Trotsky Corner at a thin seam with pins. Climb up this seam until it ends and fire the shield above. Another brilliant Bob Parrott Route.

name: Pirates of Penzance
description: Boulder into the roof and do a few powerful moves to easy climbing above. This thing is stout! Definitely a good time!

name: Precipice Ledges
description: From the base of Chitlin's Corner, move up and right to a left facing corner behind a large tree. On the ledge above the corner, step a few feet right along the ledge, then climb another left facing corner to the Return To Forever belay ledge and a 2 bolt anchor.

name: Quiver
description: A route with little protection, start up a series of blocks to the left of Retlaw to the face. Go straight into easier terrain and the merge with Retlaw to a 2-bolt anchor.

name: The Ramp Traverse
description: This is a real moderate trad climb suitable for beginner leaders. The difficult sections are the start and about mid way up but very well protected.    Start at a right facing corner behind a clump of trees(birch if I remember correctly). Climb this vertical section to gain the ledge above to begin traversing left. Follow this ledge or 'Ramp' to the left twenty feet. Then climb up to gain the second ramp which may be the crux of the climb if it's not the beginning. Leader should be aware even though he/she is a good distance off the ground that the ledgey nature of this route means a 'ground fall' is closer than the ground. Finish the climb by continuing up and left.

name: Recollections of Pacifica -(Central Slab)
description: A excellent long finger crack!    This climb follows the plumb line that Wafer Step (5.5) joins at the half-point of this wall.    Enjoy moderate moves until you reach a point where the crack squeezes down and won't accept fingers, then pull the crux face moves and enjoy the easier ground above.

name: Retlaw
description: Climb up underneath the bush and move left to gain a crack.  Follow the crack up underneath a roof. Head under the roof's left side and then continue straight up to the anchor.

name: Return to Forever  - (mid-cliff START)
description: More classic stemming & laybacking!  A terrific linkup with Old Town.    From the Old Town ledge, climb straight up through an awkward V-shaped slot to reach the clean, left-facing corner.  Stem and layback your way to the top.

name: Rusticator
description: Climb onto the pedestal, clip a bolt, then do a stiff boulder problem to access the upper finger crack. Climb straight up to a two bolt belay. Rap with a single 60m rope.

name: Scaramouche
description: Start on anchors above old town ledge, head left into face climbing with little to no pro (5.9R) then move into the dihedral. Thin pro and thin locks will see you through. The book calls this .10d, felt really hard for the grade but it’s stellar climbing!

name: Scaramouche Arete  - (mid-cliff START)
description: Technical/Balance/Thin

name: Sea Gypsy
description: A fun and varied route that pulls through an awesome, obvious roof crack you can see from the ground. The second pitch is a bit spicy but I don't think it's R-rated like the guidebook indicates.    Pitch 1:(5.8 50 ft.) Climb the corner on the right side of the buttress to the two bolt anchor      Pitch 2: (5.8 PG-13/R 70 ft.) Make insecure slabby face moves off the anchor (5.8 crux)to reach a bolt about fifteen feet up. This gets a 5.8R in the guidebook cause if you blow the crux you're going to take a factor two fall on the anchor. After the first bolt continue up easier and slightly run-out climbing right then left up a ramp to a two bolt anchor. (You could probably run this pitch together with pitch one, then you wouldn't have the crux right over the anchor.)    Pitch 3 (5.9+ 90ft.) Climb up under the first, smaller roof, clipping a piece of cord attached to a piton in a small corner over the lip. Pull up into the corner then climb right and then back left till you are under the roof crack. Plug in a #1 or #2 then pull out the roof on jams and crimps on the face on the left. Savor the exposure then climb to the two bolt anchor at the top.    Descent: 2 single rope rappels

name: Selfless Bastard
description: Sick route up the dueling cracks above Connecticut cracks. Follow cracks and features forever. Rad!

name: Side Street
description: Left facing corner to roof to face climbing past two bolts and the occasional gear placement. Be careful moving around the flake after the bolts.

name: Small Crack Warning
description: Start up a slabby face, clip a pin(possible back up) and work into the roof. Move around the roof and into the tight corner. Finish up at the Maniacal Depression anchor.

name: Southern Fried Chute
description: This climb follows the right side of Sea Gypsy buttress and can be used as an alternate start for that route. Start up large blocks to access the right-facing corner, then jam the crack and pull (gently) on the wedged flakes and blocks in the corner. Belay at the bloated station above or link into p2 of Sea Gypsy.

name: Space Between
description: Climb the first 130 ft of Chitlin's Corner to the bolts.  Then climb up and right on tricky moves off Chitlin's Corner bolts to a rest.  Then follow a thin crack up and left into the top of Chitlins Corner.  High feet, good crimps and shallow jams will get you through the long crux.  More sustained than Selfless or Maniacal.

name: The Staircase
description: Not a route, this is the granite staircase that leads up to the climbs on the Central Slab.     It also divides the "Upper/Main Wall" from the "Lower Wall" routes.

name: Standard Route
description: Enjoyable climbing on the second pitch more than makes up for the bad first pitch and it's weird body positions an gear.    P1: Start up the route from just behind the boulder and make awkward moves up to a pin, clip it and make a traverse move right (crux) place a piece and grovel into the chimney. Pull the flaring chimney and setup an anchor, either use the horn backed up or the crack.    P2: Stem, Layback, or straight on your way up the short WIDE chimney, it is very classic and unforgettable. clip the pin at the top and traverse 20' right to a rap station and belay up your second.    2 60m ropes reach the ground.

name: Star Face Mole
description: This is an independent line just climbers left of Recollections of Pacifica. It begins in a small right facing corner and climbs up to a cool three finger slot. Move left here and clip the bolt. After the bolt is a balancy crux on small feet. Follow easier terrain and good gear to a tricky finish on a left arching slightly flared (at bottom)crack to a two bolt anchor.  Re FA, comment by Grant Simmons:"Originally done by Kurt Winkler before the placement of the bolt.  He utilized a small thread as pro in that section. "  [R Hall  ME, Admin.]

name: Story of O
description: Pitch one takes you up a little gully to a slabby section.  Belay at a comfortable stance.  Pitch two goes up a tremendously fun left facing dihedral.  Great stemming and jamming with excellent pro.  Belay at the top of this feature.  Pitch three heads up steep hand cracks.  Veer left at the top of the cracks to find the anchor.  You can descend with one 60 meter rope by doing two rappels.  There is another bolted anchor directly below.

name: Sweet Surrender -(Central Slab)
description: This climb is on the Central Slabs; after passing the end of the Lower Wall, go up the talus and Staircase and continue right.    Start as for Bartleby, but at the roof go right. Climb straight up to a tree ledge and a fixed anchor.

name: Swept Away
description: Start up London Bridges to a horizontal under two bolts. Make tricky moves with poor feet on tiny crimps to a hard second clip, then just keep it together  while getting further and further above the second bolt...

name: The Tempest
description: Head up the same start as Fear of Flying, then continue straight up over the small roof. Good face climbing on mostly positive holds leads to a bolt, mantle and climb the slab to glory. Belay on top of the same ledge as the last pitch of Story of O.

name: Trotsky
description: The crux is in the first 20 feet -- thin moves with small gear for pro.  Reach a corner (with relief) and continue on easier ground to a belay on a ledge.  Exciting and fun.  5.7 is an "island rating," otherwise known as sandbag.  Some say this feels as hard as 5.9.

name: Vacation Cracks  - (mid-cliff START)
description: [NOTE: A mid-cliff START from the ledge belay shared by the top of: "Country Corner (5.7)", "Dynamo Hum (5.10d)", and "Eclipse (5.11c R)", and P1 of "Fear of Flying (5.10 a)".  R. Hall  ME Admin.]  Climb a series of cracks on the steep face above and slightly right of the big tree atop fear of flying buttress. [...at it's top it joins with P3 of "Story of O" and heads left to the rap anchors. R Hall ME Admin.]

name: Wafer Step -(Central Slab)
description: A great 5.5 climb in a very scenic location.  Scramble to the top of a detached block.  Jam the steep, vertical crack to a stance.  From here the angle lays back and you follow the beautiful left arching crack until it joins a vertical crack (the top of Recollections of Pacifica).  Belay from the two bolt anchor.  Rappel with one rope.

name: The Wet Lithuanian
description: You must climb pitch one of Green Mountain Breakdown to get to this route.  From the GMB belay ledge, go up the ramp to the roof.  Exit the roof left to make delicate moves to traverse to the face.  Follow the obvious crack that diagonals left up the face toward Chitlin's Corner.

name: The Lower Slab
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Ancient Via Ferrata
description: This "route" (which is not in the current guidebook) was recommended to me by a world-traveled climber as a "don't miss". While most technical climbers could easily solo it, an uncaught slip would certainly be fatal. It is most interestingly climbed with a short rope and about 5-6 long "alpine draws". (We used a 50M 8mm doubled over for 80ft, which seemed about right). Unlike maintained Via Ferratas, there are no cables to clip into along the way and the steel rods that do exist are suspect due to age.  START- See "Location" for approach. To get to the start of the Via Ferrata continue only another 40-50 ft beyond where the path reaches the Upper Slabs, and then go straight up on talus to the base of a open-book corner of black rock with two iron (steel?) "L-beams" overhead [photo], only one of which is still connected on the right side.  P1 - EITHER climb the black corner (5.0 - 5.2) and then exit right by going up between the L-beams [photo],...OR, scramble up the grassy buttress and balance ACROSS the L-Beams! (I have no idea how to rate this!) 30 ft.  P2 - P3 - P4 - P5 [Short "pitches"] etc. Follow the "yellow brick road" (well, actually the brown, rusted iron road) on a long, rising diagonal to the right, placing protection for the follower(s) after any tricky moves. After the last, short 3-4 ft horizontal ladder (there's only one this small) look to continue right for a while, but then cut back left to more open rock (fewer bushes) to the summit.  Descent - Follow the south hiking trail (towards Jordan Pond) off the summit for about 75-100 yds, and then you can cut back to hiker's left and get onto the talus and back to the base of the Ferrata and Upper Slabs. [As part of your approach to the climb, you might consider walking up to this point (it's only about 150-200 ft beyond Upper Slabs) before you do the climb so as to be able to recognize it.]

name: Escape Hatch
description: I thought this pretty "old school" 5.5, but used that rating since it came from the current guidebook (Grant Simmons, 2014) whose ratings are supposed to be "the grades that the climbing community has settled on." However, even the guidebook calls the climb "stout" !     P1 - Climb the Upper Slabs, usually accomplished on the lead via the large right facing corner at the left edge of the upper slabs, perhaps stepping out onto the face near the top, bolted anchor. 50 ft  5.3-5.4    P2 - Move left and climb the front of the low angled buttress of Gargoyle. Step up into the corner just below the Gargoyle crack (protect, with a long sling) and then I stepped down* and right to the steep wall on the right.  Up this on good holds to the final move, have a small wire nut to protect. 70-80 ft  I thought about 5.6+; my shorter companion (* who stayed low) thought 5.7.     Rap off double bolt anchor

name: Faust
description: Head up left from the upper slab anchor and follow  left crack system to the crux bulge. Get in gear before committing to awesome moves on crimps and a few good edges then to a tricky top out.

name: Gargoyle
description: From the bolt anchor atop the Upper Slab, angle left across a grassy ledge to reach an obvious buttress. Either climb out onto the buttress immediately and follow it up (5.6) or follow the right-facing corner to a tree before traversing left onto the buttress (5.5).    Head for some chockstones in a broken down section, and climb over them. Pass a small bulge, backing up a questionable fixed pin. Keep right and head for the fist-sized crack above, using it to pull over the crux bulge near the top (5.8). Belay from a gear anchor on the comfortable ledge.

name: Moraviana
description: A very moderate two pitch climb, with the crux being towards the top of the last pitch.     Moraviana starts to the right up the upper slab, and quickly enters a left facing corner. There's some vegetation in the crack which makes getting protection tricky. Easy moves past the corner lead to old rusted bolts for a belay.     The second pitch begins with a long scramble up fourth class terrain before you reach a nice vertical section, with some fun moves.     It's an easy climb, and easy to protect. The location is great late in the day, with a beautiful sunset.    I loved this climb, it's off the path enough that you get away from the mobs at the precipice and otter cliffs.

name: Off-Width Chimney
description: Climbs the obvious chimney on the right side of the upper face.

name: Upper Slab Routes
