description: Under MtProject guidelines you can't call the climbs on the Upper Slab Top Rope climbs (to be a TR you have to be able to set it up without technical climbing), but essentially this is what they are. I used the 5.4 rating for the access climb, but the climbs themselves are more interesting. (One could use the Via Ferrata route for even easier access.)     Once one leads up the right-facing corner on the left of the Upper Slab (5.3-5.4, perhaps stepping right onto the slab at the top for easiest climbing) the slab's 3 or 4 climbs can be TR'd with a single rope off double bolt anchors and/or the old Via Ferrata hardware, backed up.     Line 1 - About 10 ft right of the corner approx 5.5-5.6     Line 2 - Bit further right - about 5.6-5.7     Line 3 - further right yet, some small cracks about 5.7-5.8, some "straight up" variation(s) may be 5.9

name: Bullwinkle
description: Start up blocky steps to a very short  finger crack, then up to a big ledge with trees. Climb the right-facing corner above (awkward to start, and with inobvious gear) until it's possible to traverse out left (further than you think) and mantel up on the ledge. Continue up fairly easily (bolt) to below the overhanging headwall, then move up right (improbable-looking, but not difficult) to a stance. Up and left (fixed knifeblade) onto the prow, and then up to the anchor.

name: Dale's Variation
description: Start as for Natasha, but immediately step right, using the parallel crack system on the right and the juggy holds between the cracks. Fun moves on big holds. At the top, step left to the anchor of Natasha.

name: Fearless Leader
description: Follow a right-facing corner up the right side of the big block, somewhat loose at first, to a bulge. Pull up (crux) onto the slab below the roof, then step left and follow the left-facing corner to a ledge with a two-bolt anchor.

name: Natasha
description: This climb follows a left-facing corner with a nice but thin crack. Hardest down low, easy above.

name: Rocky
description: Climb the short right-facing corner to a very awkward move left onto flakes. Up easier ground, then step right on the slab under the roof. Pull the roof, get established on a stance to the right, then make a few awkward moves up to a ledge and well-hidden anchor.

name: 500 Pound Flakeout
description: The central hand/finger crack, tough placements.

name: Armistice (on separate face)
description: This is a fun, short finger and hand crack. It is quite well protected once you get past the easy starting slab. Unfortunately, due to being shaded by a large pine, it's perennially in need of cleaning.

name: The Bolt Ladder
description: You can start below the ledge and make this climb a 80ft or start off the main ledge and have it only be 60.

name: Brown Eye
description: Straight up the center of the wall. Usually topropped

name: Chalk on the Wild Side
description: The obvious sustained thin crack near the left end; because its difficult to project and very serious at the crux its usually topropped

name: Clash of the Tendons
description: At the left end of the Verticals, this is a very thin face climb

name: Diagonal Crack
description: An obvious feature, this awkward and sustained right leaning crack is rough an tough to protect. At the top there is rounded crack on the left 5.10 or one can leave the crack early and head straight up 5.11

name: Marty the Toad
description: Sustained slabby face climbing with some better holds close to the top.

name: Under the gun
description: This paragraph is taken from Rock and Ice in the Camden Hills By Ben Townsend: Follow an arete at the extreme left end of the crag to the Clash of the Tendons anchor. It is advisable to uses a directional when toproping this climb

name: After Seven
description: A really fun and interesting climb. Easy rock leads to a small roof. Pull through the roof and climb a series of cracks. An interesting mantle gets you to the top.

name: Bob's Route / Porno Bob's Route
description: Admin's NOTE: Apparently this is the same route as "Porno Bob's" route. R Hall 9/7/16  Fun, enjoyable climb. Follow Dirty slanting cracks up the wall to a puzzling pull into an alcove (crux). THen head up and left to a bolt. Continue straight up to a two bolt anchor.

name: Independence Day
description: Thin crack follows left edge of slab.

name: Porno Bob's / Bob's Route
description: Perfect finger jams up and right and then back left to the anchor.  Bolt at the crux.

name: The Raw and the Cooked
description: Diagonal up and left to overhang, step left to slab past two bolts to anchor.

name: The Becky-Joy Route
description: Step up over a small overhand just off the ground, then follow an obvious crack system to oak trees on a big ledge. (This section by itself makes a nice short 5.4 climb.) Step right and climb the headwall past a bolt (crux) to good holds on the left, and pull onto a big ledge. The bolted anchor is a bit up and right, behind the tree. One-rope rappel.

name: Broken Elevator (a/k/a Robert's Fall)
description: Follow the left-leaning crack system and move left to a stance below a bulge. Protect with micro nuts, pull the bulge, and head up left to a good horizontal below an overhang. Pull the overhang and step left, then back right into an alcove with a bolted intermediate rap anchor. (Possible belay here.) Straight up through the next bulge, then more easily up and left to Broadway. Two-bolt belay anchor on the left (same as for Poison Ivy or Good Omens).  A mentally challenging pitch with route-finding and inobvious gear.

name: Buffy
description: This route is broken by a big ledge in the middle, and it's slow to dry. However, it also has some sections of good climbing.     Climb up the left (smaller) of the two flares on the short slab. Up and a bit left on the big sloping ledge to the headwall, and climb the obvious flake-crack on its right end to a big ledge. The anchor is far back on the ledge, behind the oak tree.

name: Bugaboo
description: 1. Start as for Joe's Route, then climb the rib between the two left-leaning corners, heading for a V-groove just below the anchor. 5.7, 90'    2. Up and a bit left through the quartz band (easy, but not much gear for a while), then straight up to either of the Continental Cracks finishes. 5.6, 90'

name: Charlotte's Crack
description: Find the thin seem that heads to a ledge with a tree 40 feet up from the base. Traverse left up thin holds and pro, or follow the crack to the big ledge (broadway). From anchors walk left to the start of a big crack, go to the top.

name: Clamdigger Crack
description: The bottom is unattractive but cleans up above the roof with some fun easy pockets, easy to protect.     At the top, the right hand ramp finish has a large sticker bush, quite possibly a raspberry or gooseberry bush, which makes that finish a bit prickly.  The left hand finish avoids this bush.    From Rock and Ice Climbs in the Camden Hills, Townsend Rees 2010:   "Easy rock leads to a small overhang.  Above, follow a left-leaning crack to the left edge of the face, then climb up the wide crack to an anchor on Broadway.  Alternatively, finish by climbing left out of the wide crack, directly to the Pandora Freeway anchor.  (90')"

name: Continental Cracks
description: Climb the initial slab past two bolts (crux) to reach the base of the cracks. Optional gear belay at a small stance up and left (3" cam helpful). Follow either of the two cracks, which are about the same difficulty, to an alcove, then either stem up on the left, or pull up steep holds on the right, to a crack system leading to the top.

name: Desperado
description: Easy climbing to a horizontal crack; then fun moves following two bolts for the second half of the climb.  Wrap bolts are in the alcove.

name: Equinox
description: A fun moderate outing, with fairly good protection by Camden standards. Climb up a short slab near the left end of the big roof. make your way around the left side of the roof until it is possible to step right onto the slab above the roof. follow cracks up to a large peapod. Pull through the peapod (crux), and continue up a series of cracks until you come to a chain anchor. Their is a second pitch to this climb but its not worth doing (4rd class scramble).

name: Floral Morals
description: Stem up the corner (crux) to the hemlock tree. Step left and follow an obvious crack system up and left to the bolted anchor at the top of the Old Spice slab.

name: Fourth of July (mid-cliff START)
description: 5 feet right of the Poison Ivy anchor on Broadway, a couple face moves leads to a thin finger crack that fades in and out. When the crack fades out climb to a bolt, then straight up the face to some pockets where gear can be found. Climb a short vertical section to two rusty but beefy bolts.

name: Ghost Town
description: Face climb past a low bolt (crux) up between the two blocks, then up and a bit right to a prominent square-cut hole below a roof. Pass the roof on the right, then climb easily up the blocky crack to a nice ledge and the anchor.

name: Goat Yoga
description: P. 1 Mostly bolt-protected, but not quite sport climbing. Pull up onto the opening slab, clip a bolt, and move up to a nice ledge below the overhanging headwall (gear in a great horizontal just above the ledge). Climb the steep headwall on mostly big holds past two bolts (optional thin cam placement between the bolts), emerging on a big sloping ledge. Scramble up to the base of the next headwall, placing gear if desired. Step a bit left and climb over unlikely-looking bulges past two bolts. A short finger crack leads to a final bolt just below the nice belay ledge. (This pitch can be toproped by scrambling down and right from the start of Joe's Route to the anchor.) 5.9+, 90'  P. 2 Straight up the bulge above the anchor, then easy slabs to a headwall with a right-leaning crack. Up this, then easy slabs to a nice ledge with a bolted anchor. 5.6, 110'  P. 3 Straight up easy slabs (sparse but solid gear in pockets) to a distinctive square-cut block. Protect, then step left and climb up more slabs to an alcove. Climb the left ridge of the alcove to the big ledge. Bolted anchor 15' left of the big pine tree of Joe's Route. 5.3, 115'  Walk off right, rappel (one 70m rope), or take Witchy Woman or Tritium Witch to the top.

name: Good Omens
description: Climb delicately up the shallow V-groove to the bolt, with tricky protection. Continue straight up, stepping left at a small overlap. At the bushy ledge, pull through a bulge (crux) and continue up to Broadway and the Poison Ivy anchor.

name: Harmonic Convergence
description: Find a small crack below a very small grassy ledge and a slightly overhanging bulge and climb it!  Watch out for the loose triangular rock at the at the grassy ledge.  The bulge is a tricky pull; once you have passed it move left and then straight on for the first bolt you see.  At the top of the climb there is a small horizontally angling crack that takes some small gear that protects the final moves well.  From here move right to the small evergreen bush and on to Broadway ledge.

name: Hidden Attraction
description: After an awkward starting move to a good stance, climb straight up past a short thin crack to gain the top of the vertical wall, then traverse diagonally right and exit at a short dihedral. Nice belay ledge with a two-bolt anchor (same as Obscure Object). Rappel.

name: Hollywood Waltz
description: P. 1: Climb easily up the crack and corner system to a bulge. Pull the bulge on the right, move back left, then up to a short hand crack. At its top, move left and climb the face to a good ledge and belay from gear. (Alternatively, follow a ramp up right to the bolted anchor of Standard Route.)  P. 2: Step right from the belay and climb a short, thin finger crack, then wander up easy face to a ledge below a bulge. Step up left, then back right and head straight up the narrow clean face past horizontals to Broadway (oak tree and bolted anchor).

name: Hotel California
description: 1. Up the short dirty slab to an overlap, pull over to a short left-leaning wide crack, then step up right to a thin crack system that stays just right of the outside corner. 5.6, 115', two-bolt anchor. (Done by itself, this is one of the nicer moderate pitches at the crag.)    2. Move the belay up to above the bushy oak tree. Climb the obvious vertical crack system on the short vertical wall (tricky gear at the start). Bolted anchor on the left. 5.9+, 40'.    3. Cross the ledge and follow an obvious very steep corner and crack system to the top. 5.10b, 50'.

name: Jack-in-the-Pulpit
description: Climb easily up the initial slab past a bolt to a ledge below a bulge with a yellow birch tree on the left. Step right and clear the bulge with a not-very-obvious mantel (easier for taller climbers). Continue up the easy crack system to the tree.

name: Joker
description: 1. Scramble easily up the chimney to a short finger crack on the left wall. Climb the left wall, passing a bolt, to a ledge. Step right and climb a short friction slab past another bolt; diagonal up right to a stance with a gear anchor. (5.8, 60') (To do this pitch by itself, stay left of the second bolt and go to the big pine tree on Charlotte's Crack.)  2. Step right and climb the overhanging headwall past two bolts. Follow a crack system more or less straight up the slab above, pulling a short headwall on the left to reach Broadway. Belay at the bolted anchor of Charlotte's Crack. (5.9+, 70')  If doing this route in one pitch, use long runners on the lower part to alleviate rope drag.

name: Obscure Object of Desire
description: A Short, steep, and thin face climb. A right leaning crack leads to a steep face with good pockets (hard to find) and descent edges. The crux comes up high, you will seem insecure, but all of the holds are solid.

name: Old Spice
description: A fun, moderate climb, but be aware of the long run outs. Climb up the middle of a narrow slab to a spacious ledge at a two bolt chain anchor. The climbing is straightforward for the most part, but gear placements are hard to find.

name: Old Spud
description: The very shallow corner on the arete between the Old Spice slab and the steeper Old Stud wall.  Tricky gear. Can TR with shared anchor with Old Spice.

name: Old Stud
description: A harder start to old spice. A short, steep slab with three bolts. Join old spice after 25'. The hard section is quite safe, but this route shares the runout 5.6 upper section of old spice.

name: Pandora
description: This good climb requires trad gear, you'd be looking at some hairy runouts otherwise!    (P1) Scramble up the ramp in the small gully to the tricky slab that angles left.  The business starts right away at the first bolt, follow the three bolts up (10a to 10c) and through to some grassy steps to a small stance and build your belay there.    (P2) Traverse to the right onto the slab to the first bolt, and follow the bolts to the anchor!

name: Pandora Freeway (mid-cliff START)
description: Follow the crack system past a horizontal to a sloping ledge, pull an overhang, then move up and left to a big horizontal. Step left and climb a slabby scoop to another overlap (crux) and then up to the Pandora anchor. Rappel back to the Clamdigger anchor with one rope.

name: Poison Ivy
description: Climb a fun flaring corner to many horizontals. Choose your own adventure through generally good rock to the big Broadway Ledge. A two bolt anchor awaits you.

name: Queen Charlotte
description: This climb begins on the ground 15 feet right of Charlotte's Crack. Follow the arete (left of big dirty gully) 15 feet up to a small overhang. Pull the business and continue on easier ground to the big ledge with a pine tree with chains.    A fun alternative first pitch to Charlotte's Crack

name: Skidmarks (mid-cliff START)
description: Step up immediately left of the bolted anchor (top of Poison Ivy, bottom of Fourth of July) and wander upward and slightly left, eventually reaching a crack system just below the top. There is a very well-concealed anchor at the bushy ledge, with a good stance.  A great toprope and a very committing lead, left unbolted by local consensus. The technical crux is before the first good gear. On lead, first head for a slot on the right for a #1 Camalot or equivalent, then back left to another slot for a #0.4 (double ropes are nice here); up a moderate but unprotected ramp to a horizontal, then step left and follow a subtle thin crack system up and a bit right to big holds and good gear. There are many places where falling would be a bad idea.

name: Slow Children (mid-cliff START)
description: Add this to the climb "Poison Ivy" (on the lower wall) and you get a 2-pitch, four-star 5.4-5.5.     START- In the "gap" in the mid-cliff ledge Broadway, about 10 ft left of the double bolt anchors of "Poison Ivy".     P1- Climb the crack above the "gap" for about 30 ft, then hand traverse left to another crack system and up to the top and a 2-bolt anchor.

name: Spawn
description: 1. Gain a short left-facing corner. At its top, step back right and climb a short slab to a grassy ledge. Follow the obvious crack left and up to a big step across, then go up to a bolted anchor on the left. 5.7, 90'  2. Step back right and follow a vegetated crack to an overlap split by a finger crack. Pull through the overlap (crux) to a horizontal, where it's possible to clip a bolt (actually part of a different route -- use a very long runner). Work right, then up a slab with tricky gear to the anchor. 5.7+, 90'  Rappel twice with one rope.

name: Spider (mid-cliff START)
description: Climbs a face then up cracks to finish just to the left of Clothesline.  Crux is the lower face. Originally rated 5.7, with bolted protection on the crux moves.  Well, one is a bolt, the most important one.  The other two are ancient pitons. Don't lean back on those! Good gear above.

name: Standard Route
description: An easy climb with thoughtful and somewhat spaced gear. Climb two short left-facing corners, followed by a couple of small overhangs and lots of fun, featured rock, to reach a big sloping ledge and the anchor. Rappel, or head up and a bit left to link with Hollywood Waltz.

name: Summertime Blues
description: Mantel a short initial corner, cross a grassy ledge, and climb the main dihedral to the bulge (this part is all shared with Throne of the Mountain King). Head left up the slab under the bulge, then up easy slabs to the big ledge and the tree.

name: Tangled Up in Blue (mid-cliff START)
description: Pull up out of the right side of the alcove onto a short slab, then step back left to a crack system. Follow the crack until it fades out, then step left to a short section of thin face climbing (5.8, bolt) that leads to a good ledge. Pull up a steep right-facing corner (crux) onto the headwall, then straight up to the top.

name: Templeton's Crack (mid-cliff START)
description: Climb easily up the vegetated crack to a ledge, step right onto the face, and follow the faint crack system (tricky gear, small Tricams critical) to a horizontal. Runout face climbing (crux) leads to another good horizontal and gear. Wander up the face above, finishing up the headwall just left of Charlotte's Crack; belay and rappel from the Charlotte's anchor. An excellent, sustained pitch with challenging protection.

name: Throne of the Mountain King
description: Mantel a short initial corner and cross a grassy ledge to the base of the main dihedral. Up the corner, then work right and pull the bulge to an alcove with a bolted anchor. There's another anchor about 40' further, at the base of the next headwall, which allows easy rappel access, but if you toprope off the upper anchor you are guaranteed a lot of rope drag.

name: Together Through Life
description: Climb straight up past obvious horizontals to the right edge of a large flake, then more or less straight up to the anchor (easier on the left).   The stance at the anchor is cramped, so it's preferable to lower off.

name: Toontown (mid-cliff START)
description: Climb up to a bolt, then work left and up (crux) to a good horizontal. Slightly runout face climbing leads to a second bolt, and then a nice ledge. Trend a bit left, then straight up the headwall to the top and a three-bolt anchor.

name: Tritium Witch (mid-cliff START)
description: Climb more or less straight up the face to a short finger crack and a bolt. Above, an enjoyable crack system leads to a short headwall just below the top.    An easier start follows the large diagonal crack system from the pine tree, joining the regular route at a small vegetated ledge.

name: Velvet Underground
description: Climb the mossy slab on good holds (poorly protected, but very easy) to a ledge. Get solid gear, then climb small left-facing flakes to a high bolt. Tiptoe left to reach big holds, then power up and right to a nice ledge with a two-bolt anchor.

name: The Web (mid-cliff START)
description: From the top of pitch 1 of Charlotte's crack (Broadway Ledge) follow a right trending crack system. Pass a bolt on the left (belonging to Toontown) climbing the face to the arete. Continue upwards on the arete and face to a two bolt belay.

name: Wherever You Go, There You Are
description: Climb easily to the top of the pillar, which can be slung for protection. Step up and arrange gear, move left and up to good holds, then hand-traverse vigorously back right (crux), clipping a bolt along the way. Another move or two leads to the ledge and an anchor on the right. Fun moves on mostly good rock, though the top-out can be dirty.

name: White Streak
description: Sustained, notably runout face climbing, mostly in the 5.7-5.8 range with a couple of short 5.9 moves. Get solid gear in the thin horizontal above the second bolt to protect a very long runout to the next horizontal. The technical crux is near the top, with solid gear in the horizontal at your feet.

name: Witchy Woman (mid-cliff START)
description: Follow the wide crack until it ends at a horizontal, then climb straight up a short slab to reach a diagonal ramp. Step left a few feet, then climb straight up to a tiny overlap. Pull the overlap (crux) and follow big holds, stepping left to finish up the middle of the face. The route seems improbable from below in several spots, but hidden holds and pockets make it both easy and well protected.

name: Young Stud
description: Traverse right to gain an incipient crack, then climb up past tricky gear (crux) to gain the easy crack. Belay from the Old Spice anchor (two bolts with rings).

name: "Four Grey Bolts"
description: Moderate climbing past three grey bolts leads to a difficult crux arete (right of the fourth bolt) fo the finish.

name: 3 stooges
description: start 30 feet left of cracked up in a small left facing cornor

name: birds eye (aka- FB)
description: fun climbing up to a crux at 2/3 height. can seem a little harder the first time u try it!

name: borderline
description: climb the left side of double overhanging side of the arete, super technical

name: The Corner Store
description: Follow the thin crack that starts behind the ash tree, but don't use the tree for "aid" in the first few moves. The crack continues up the corner through a couple of bulges. From the juniper bush, continue up the face (with a crack for pro) on the right side. Ascend a slab to an oak and pine tree. Finish up a short finger/hand crack in a dihedral, which goes to the top of the cliff. To descend, go right into a gully, and then follow the gully down to the bottom of the cliff.

name: cracked up
description: follow a thin seam 4' right of the arete until second bolt, then step left  and follow the arete up.

name: Curly's Corner
description: This is an alternative finish to the "Four Gray Bolts" route. Clip the third gray bolt with a longish sling and then go leftward to ascend the obvious corner. Clip the (shiny) bolt in the corner and continue up and around the roof that contains a fist crack. Finish at the Three Stooges anchor.

name: Disturbed
description: climb the left facing cornor past a crux about midway!

name: Dyno-U-Mite
description: climb an often wet start to ledges(10+ ish), then angle up right to base of a short dihedral couple ok holds and crappy stems leave u staring at big jug up left(crux), so Dyno-u -mite!5-8 climbing leads u to the anchors!

name: Element Zero
description: About 15' right of Glory Hole and 30' left of Squiddler on the Roof, at a short overhanging left-facing corner. The finish is the right face of a prominent jutting prow above.

name: funny farm
description: fun little easy slab route.

name: Glory Hole
description: Super fun route, look for the glory hole hidden deep in back of horizontal above the 5th bolt to make the next move just a little easier!

name: Hooked
description: crux is pulling out onto face off ledge above slacker.

name: Loud Room
description: The route uses the same line of bolts as Quiet Room. Climb up the face to the right of the bolts, reaching left to clip them.

name: Moe's Woes
description: This is a direct start to the "Four Gray Bolts" route. A couple of meters to the right of the gray bolts, climb up a line of 3 shiny bolts to gain the bottom of the narrow arete. You can finish by climbing the arete of the "Four Gray Bolts" route.

name: O-C-D
description: layback up and on to a big flake. then face climb straight up past a low bolt left of a big flake- straight up a wondering face past two bolts to a small ramp on right( original trad line) then two more bolts of crux climbing to high anchor in the roof.   originally a trad line to the right - but the direct start was much cleaner and better climbing-

name: Quiet Room
description: super fun with some techy moves getting to the 2cd bolt.

name: simple gifts
description: fun route with a crux at the anchors!    climb up right on to the flake then clip anchors.

name: slacker
description: great little step bouldery route, this thing will give u a great flash pump.

name: The squeeze
description: Route between -glory hole and fb-(birds eye)

name: squidler on the roof
description: climb up to a ledge under the 4' roof. palm and limbo ur way out to reach holds at the lip(harder if ur short)then hold on tight when your feet cut!

name: straitjacket
description: climbs much easier than it appears from the bottom,,,

name: sun spot
description: a fun route -

name: Trad Man's Delight
description: A fun trad lead.    Start at the bottom of the crack and angle up and left to the top.    We found this crack full of moss, dirt and lichen (in an unclimbable state).  We cleaned it all up and then climbed it (summer 2012), so now it is ready to go.    We don't know if anyone had already climbed the crack back in the distant past. If anyone has information, please post.

name: voluntary madness
description: be ready to work right off the ground! You will traverse right at  5th bolt  for 12d and continue back up left to high anchor. direct finish  13c or d.

name: Crescent Moon
description: Follow steep flakes out right, then straight up, bearing left along a short diagonal crack near the top.

name: Desperately Seeking Sheena
description: Follow the obvious wide crack, stemming across the chimney against the pillar as much as possible (much easier for tall people). Continue past the Revolution anchors to the ledge and anchor above Where the Vultures Go.

name: Early Bird
description: A very puzzling start (bolt) leads to easier climbing. Don't miss the cam placement in the very back of the large horizontal crack above the crux.

name: Exile on Maine Street
description: Climb up on the right to avoid the big roof, then work left across the slab on diagonal cracks to a short right-facing corner. Pull up onto a ledge (crux), clip a bolt, then continue to the top of the pillar.

name: Holy Chloronosis Trad Man
description: Follow the painfully sharp finger crack, taking advantage of every opportunity to stem off the pillar. This climb tends to be quite dirty.

name: The Portal
description: Follow steep cracks up and over the chockstones to emerge in daylight, then follow a blocky crack and corner system on the main wall. Watch for loose rock.

name: Purple Haze
description: Start up a short, left-leaning corner, then move right into a steep flared corner with a thin finger crack on its left. At the top of the corner, step up left past a bolt, then pull the left end of the overhang. The start is mossy and takes a while to dry.

name: Revolution
description: After a short step move to get started, the climb mostly consists of delicate stemming between the main wall and the outside corner of the pillar.

name: Sky King
description: Climb the center of the featured slab.

name: Sunshine Sue
description: Circumvent the big roof to its right, then climb straight up the slab past horizontal cracks and one protection bolt.

name: Where the Vultures Go
description: Start with an awkward balance move (tiny cams) to a ledge with a sizeable detached block (stable enough to climb past, but not to place gear behind), then straight up past the bolts (crux). It's also possible to use either arete, which drops the grade a bit.

name: Trailing Arbutus
description: Climb the slab to the left of Everdrip encountering two bolts. Traverse left at second bolt and under roof. Exit around left end of roof at wide crack. Finishes at bolted rap station just above roof. The pine at the top of Everdrip just beyond the bolted rap station has a chain but is in rough shape with slightly lifted roots.

name: Alpine Spring
description: Climb a short slab to a ledge (same start as Beautiful Garbage). Continue straight up the face, finishing up the steep right-facing corner with an overhang at the top to an anchor (shared with Beautiful Garbage).

name: Beautiful Garbage
description: Climb up a short slab to a small ledge (same start as Alpine Spring). Follow the steep crack on the left through the overhang above, then step right past a small tree to an anchor shared with Alpine Spring.

name: Common Ground
description: Step up onto very featured horizontal ledges, then climb more or less straight up the steep wall on good holds. At the top, step right to the anchor (shared with Madam Butterfly).

name: Cowboy Bebop
description: Pull up through the steep starting section on good rock. At the second bolt, step left onto a sloping ledge, another bolt, and a short vertical crack. The smooth headwall above, passing a horizontal crack, is the crux; mantel onto a nice ledge with an anchor.

name: The Crozier
description: Starting on the right, pull up onto the slab and mantel onto a ledge. Climb up past the horizontal onto a steep headwall, and follow good holds straight up to the anchor.

name: Firecracker
description: Straight up the crack system to an anchor.

name: Jerry's Corner
description: Pull up into the steep left-facing corner and layback to a small overhang, then step right and reach a pocket on the right face. Climb up past a wide horizontal onto an awkward ramp below a large overhang. Pull through the big overhang to an anchor.

name: The Kuller
description: This is a very good route, similar to Million Muppet March but on mostly trad gear. It was named in memory of the late Jeff Kuller, longtime director of parks and recreation for the Town of Camden.     Follow a short crack system up through overhanging rock past a horizontal, then continue straight up the slab above, passing a bolt, to an anchor.

name: Madam Butterfly
description: Climb the shallow right-facing corner, then pull over onto the face on the left above an overhang and continue to the anchor (shared with Common Ground). A committing lead.

name: The Million Muppet March
description: Start up a thin vertical crack system (optional gear placements), then climb straight up through an overhanging bulge on big holds. Continue up a slab (more optional gear placements) to an anchor set in the overhang at the top of the cliff. Probably the best route on the Guide's Wall.

name: Mos Eisley
description: Move up the short right-leaning crack, then step left onto the face of the buttress and follow a wandering line of least resistance up to a very puzzling steep exit on the left. The anchor is a few feet up and right on a slab. "A wretched hive of scum and villainy," according to Obi-Wan Kenobi, but the quality of the climbing is much better than the appearance would suggest.

name: The Real Folk Blues
description: Pull up through the overhanging start on good holds. At the second bolt, undercling and jam up and right, following the obvious flake, to an anchor.

name: Scarecrow
description: Follow the crack to the grassy ledge and an anchor (shared with Tin Man, the left crack). An easy, well-protected lead.

name: Sparkler
description: Follow the right-leaning crack, then step right to an anchor (shared with Firecracker). Awkward, reachy, and hard to protect well. The obvious flake lodged in the crack wiggles but doesn't seem to want to come out.

name: Tin Man
description: Step up a short outside corner (crux, easily avoided by stepping in from the right) to a short left-facing corner below an overhang. Follow the left of two parallel cracks up to the grassy ledge and an anchor (shared with Scarecrow, the right crack).

name: Treasure Island
description: Follow the featured, left-facing corner up past several ledges to an anchor. This is an enjoyable easy lead with good protection.

name: Downhill Arete
description: Sit start: climb the arete.

name: Downhill Face
description: Stand start: the downhill face of the boulder. Find some crimps a couple moves off the deck to take you up. Arete to the right is V0.

name: Grab the Jug!
description: On the backside of the Buried Treasure boulder. Sit start; as for the arete, but move up and left for a throw to a large, flat hold.

name: Jug Band
description: Backside of Buried Treasure. Sit Start; from crimps, slap to jugs.

name: Mantel Illness
description: Stand start; the left side of the downhill face of the boulder. A fun, balencey problem.

name: The Reward
description: Sit start: a left to right traverse of the wall, from the bottom left, moving thru the fin, finishing up on the vertical rail, just shy of the right arete.

name: Sunken Arete
description: Sit start: left hand on the undercling, then climb the right arete of the bloc.

name: Timpani
description: Sit start: right hand on the undercling, climb the middle of the wall, using a large undercut fin.  Stand start from crimp is V3.

name: Tomato Soup
description: Sit Start; the left arête adjacent to the Tombstone.

name: War Cry
description: Stand start: from the fin, pull over to the right.

name: All Feet
description: Sit start; from crimps, climb leftwards on the footholds of the previous route.

name: Country Mile
description: Stand start; the blunt arête to the left. Climb on its right side. Step up a steep ramp, with a long move to a good hold.

name: Crack Fiend
description: Stand start; the crack in the alley makes for an adventure few boulderers will search out.

name: Diagonal Crack
description: Stand start; the diagonal crack is something of a trad route.

name: High Foot Challenge
description: Sit start; immediately behind the Pompadour there is an undercut arête. Sit start with left hand in the break, right on the arête, and a very high right foot. A couple dynamic slaps gains the top.

name: Lightning Crack
description: Stand start; the diagonal crack to the left with laybacks or fist jams.

name: Weak Hips
description: Stand start; the left side of the blunt arête is a rock-over testpiece. Hidden holds might help.

name: Barney's Rumble
description: Sit Start; On the hidden side, just left of Eli's Crack. Move up crimps to gain the arete to top out. Dangerous landing, make sure your spotter is on point!

name: Bongo Slab
description: Climb the hollow sounding slab on the left up to the seam. Traverse left around the arete for the finish. Take on the suspended boulder above, for an added adventure.

name: Broken Slab
description: Around to the left. The low angle slab split horizontally.

name: Dump Truck
description: Escape a meat cleaver arete in the back of the cave and somehow swing around the roof to an airy finish up the suspended boulder. A kneebar may assist you, somewhere along the way.

name: Eli's Crack
description: The overhanging crack on the hidden, backside of the formation. Terrible landing.

name: Flintstone Arete: Project
description: The arete on the left of the slab, starting in the cave. Finish up the suspended boulder. Shitty landing. Rating only a guess.

name: Suspended Animation: Project
description: Stand start; up the ramp on the right, use the same starting 'spike' hold as for Yabba Dabba Doo. Move out left for a big reach across the suspended boulder to a meaty sidepull. Campus up to gain the suspended boulder with your feet to an airy finish.

name: Yabba Dabba Doo!
description: Stand start; up the ramp on right and move up and left, climbing the weakness of the suspended boulder.

name: Barometric Pressure: Project
description: Climb the left arête, then take the head wall on the right. A beautiful line. Difficulty rating only a guess.

name: The Crack
description: Sit start; the awesome crack from the jammed block, topping out on the right. Project: Continue left up the headwall above the crack. A fantastic line!

name: Crimp Slap
description: Hanging start on an obvious crimp at the right end of the wall, lunge to the lip and pull over on the left.

name: Mike's Hairbrain Scheme: Project
description: Hanging start in the crack. Escape the crack on tiny crimps on the left, ties into "You are Here" or "Barometric Pressure" finish.

name: Mini Mantle
description: Sit start; mantle the center of the lip on the squat bloc to the right of the main wall.

name: Pineapple Cake
description: Sit start; a left to right lip traverse.

name: Pointy Hat
description: Sit start; immediately right of the wall, the small bloc with a half height break.

name: Scrubbing Ladder
description: The slab around the left side of the wall

name: Small Cave Crack
description: Sit start; round to the left, there is a small cave. Use the crack for hands, and the prop bloc at the back for feet.

name: You Are Here
description: Stand start; slaps and heel hooks up the left arête until it’s possible to pull round left on to the slab.

name: Campus Portal
description: Stand start; The hanging prow to the left leans rightward to join the previous route.

name: Cornered: Project
description: An nice looking, often wet inside corner of the Hidden Wall's right end. Nothing established yet, open to interpretation.

name: Double Stack
description: Stand start; the undercut groove to the left, a stack of pads may help those with inflexible hips! Sit start underneath in the cave?

name: Needle in a Haystack: Project
description: Stand start; the blank-looking wall to the right of Rainbow has some sharp crimps. difficulty rating only a guess.

name: Paper Wings
description: Stand start; Crimps up the often wet wall, just right of Double Stack.

name: Rainbow in the Dark
description: Stand start; the central line on huge flakes is brilliant.

name: Telling the Trees
description: Low start; round the nose to the left, from an obvious low jug, slap up the right arête to a tricky mantle.

name: Uphill Both Ways: Project
description: Telling the Trees start; keep traversing up left along the gully. Difficulty rating only a guess.

name: Wandering Youth
description: Stand start; the right arête. An eliminate variation avoids the arête for V3.

name: The Cache
description: Sit start: the small, low bloc to the right of the wall. From a prop block at the back of the roof, span to the lip and mantle out.

name: Escape Pod
description: Stand Start: the steep slab between the dihedral and the arete. Pull the small roof on the left for the top out.

name: Freddy
description: Stand start: the crack to the right of the dihedral.

name: Ruby Duby
description: Stand start: the dihedral. Commonly climbed from the low hold on the right. Pull around the small roof for an exciting top out.

name: Snatch Trap
description: The groove on the right of the wall itself.

name: Stair Master
description: The arete directly above the stone steps.

name: Around the Horn
description: Uphill side. Stand start; the right arête.

name: Crocodile Long Mouth
description: Sit start; just to the right is a snout-like bloc. From the large flat hold, wrestle your way on top.

name: Left Arete
description: Uphill side. Sit or stand start; the left arête of the bloc.

name: Mullet Wall
description: Stand start; gain the half height break, and make insecure moves up the left arête to a thank-god jug. Sit start available for the completionist.

name: Pompadour
description: Uphill side. Sit start; the central line is a classic. Climb to the break, then take crimps and tiny footholds to reach a distant jug.

name: Sideburns
description: Stand start; the right arête above a dubious landing.

name: Crystal Method
description: Stand Start; the middle of the wall, using the quartz stripe.

name: Tombstone Left
description: Stand start; the left side of the bloc, incorporating the arete.

name: Tombstone Right
description: Stand start; right side of the bloc, incorporating the arete

name: Every Second Counts
description: Face climb to a ledge (no pro), then follow a wide crack and an open corner on the right side of the buttress to a mantel out left onto the easy slab. Up and right again to a short right-facing corner below the headwall. Climb the headwall (crux, bolt) and emerge on a large flat ledge with an anchor at the back.

name: Extension Ladder (mid-cliff start)
description: [NOTE, R Hall Admin.: The "extension" of Fireman's Ladder. From the top of Fireman's Ladder make a....    ....Awkward step across the chasm, then up finger crack to bush and finish on slab with quartz veins to oak tree.

name: Fireman's Ladder
description: Boulder problems interspersed with ledges.  Crux may well be the start.  Awkward but fun.

name: Natural History
description: Fun bouldery chimney moves to a disco ledge, then a few feet of beautiful finger crack to the oak tree.

name: November
description: Nice thin face climb.

name: Over the hill
description: Located on far left side of the Ramparts. [Admin's NOTE: "Over the Hill" and the next climb, "Sassy" are located on a steep wall just to the left of the ice climb "Bixler's Way", and up-and-LEFT of the "Fireman's Ladder" Area, closer to the Right Cataract Area than Ramparts. R Hall 9/7/16]    Climb the center line of the wall past a low steep section to a small roof, then big pulls up less steep rock to top.

name: Sassy or sally  aka sos
description: This route is on the right side of wall where Over the Hill is located.   For Sally you climb up the line but can stem into the corner beside you,  Sassy is in the 5.11 range and just climbs the route without stemming into the corner.     [Admin's NOTE: "Over the Hill" and the next climb, "Sassy" are located on a steep wall just to the left of the ice climb "Bixler's Way", and up-and-LEFT of the "Fireman's Ladder" Area, closer to the Right Cataract Area than Ramparts. R Hall 9/7/16]

name: Anniversary Climb
description: Boulder up to the big ledge (or scramble up from its right end), then climb the short arching crack. Pull up onto the arete (crux) and follow it past horizontals to a bolted lower-off anchor.

name: Arete
description: Start to the right of the easy slab below the right headwall, near a big tree a short way up the cliff.     Technical climbing goes up and left out the exposed slab and up the striking arete. Fun tippy toey, climbing.

name: Ariel
description: Climb to the right of Dream Weaver. Great line up overhanging wall. Gained by climbing the lower part of Dream Weaver and then tending right out overhanging face. Great 11D. Crux at start and at last move.

name: Caliban (mid-cliff START)
description: Fun but funky climbing- right knee bars (pad) helpful from last bolt to anchor!

name: The Coast of Bohemia
description: From the big ledge, climb the shallow right-facing corner to a bulge (crux) and pull up onto the slab above. Move up and right, using a right-leaning crack, to the Prospero anchor.

name: Dream Weaver
description: Every goes very smoothly till you get to the ledge. Once at the ledge you can either go left up the arete or head straight up. I feel that the climb was originally intended to go straight up but I wasn't able to figure out the moves. If you go left towards the arete. I feel that you knock the climb down a letter grade and a number grade to a 10a/b. The crux this way is very pumpy and a fall could result in a dangerous swing into the ledge.

name: Fireman's Ladder Area
description: The climbs in the Fireman's ladder area are at the far left end of Rampart Cliff and are currently listed in a separate AREA Fireman's Ladder Area of Camden Hills    To get to the Fireman's Ladder area from the Rampart Cliff, follow the cliff down to climber's left, then continue down through a somewhat scrappy gully (careful of rockfall), then continue left.  To get from Fireman's Ladder (Area) to the Ramparts' left wall follow right along the cliff base to a steep gully.  Up this 40-50 ft to the base of the left end of the Ramparts.

name: Out of Gas
description: Climb the easy corner to the oak tree, step right, then more or less straight up a continuous crack system to a roof. Bolted anchor at the ledge above the roof.

name: Prospero
description: This climb is trick up to the 2nd bolt everything after that goes very smooth.

name: Puissance
description: Climb the slab (Reincarnation, 5.9-) to the ledge, then take the brilliant steep headwall. Formerly an aid route now free. When you fall off the first move of the headwall, be sure to lower down and climb the slab again (crux).

name: Reconnaissance
description: A right-to-left linkup that joins the crux portions of Resonance, Renascence, and Ariel.

name: Renascence
description: Crux at bottom of route then sustained climbing to the top. My favorite at the crag.

name: Renasonance (Link Up)
description: Just another link up, start Renascence, Make sure you extend the 2nd bolt then head right below roof finishing resonance.

name: Resonance
description: Farthest right climb on overhanging wall. A bit contrived but still decent climbing.Maybe a bit harder now than when it went up. I have broken a hold or 2. SORRY!!!

name: second april
description: super fun route with a short crux @ 2cd bold moving left thru slopers. then finishing up the top face of tilted arc.   If its feeling to hard look for a couple knee bars.

name: Tense Mossworks
description: This is a crack that starts just to the left of Dream Weaver.  It has been cleaned and makes for a nice trad lead (when dry).    The crack ends at the ledge below the crux of Dream Weaver, so the logical finish would be to continue up to the DW anchor.    This crack can be easily seen (left of the climber) in the "photo of Josh" posted with Dream Weaver.

name: Tilted Arc
description: Bolts not replaced. Route goes on gear, although a bit spicy! Could definitely be an ankle breaker.Very cool but awkward climbing up overhanging flared groove, then a super awesome but weird and scary move to gain a lip. Then big throw to to small incut protected by a bolt. Originally rated 12b. Hold on face is Much smaller now. Still 12a.

name: Treerock
description: Up the easy corner past the oak tree, then up cracks and traverse right to pull onto the belay ledge with a bolted anchor (shared with Out of Gas).

name: Wingspan
description: a short but very pumpy route!   crux comes in middle of the route past a (wingspan) move,

name: body count
description: climbs the center zebra striped wall past a low crux.

name: Hot Corner
description: Ascend easy terrain to access the obvious right facing corner. Place small gear at the bottom of the corner and climb up the face right of the corner, passing two bolts. Place gear above the second bolt and continue climbing up the corner to reach the third bolt. Continue up and right to the top.

name: Irony
description: a little spicey if ur new to the grade, but bolts are where u need them.

name: itchie balls
description: climb the steep powerful and crimpy face.

name: ladder line
description: climbs a large right facing flake to a 4' roof.

name: liken lichen
description: climb a dirty face 20' to a steep face up small arete.

name: red hot
description: climb the thin diagonal crack on the far left of cliff.

name: sister city
description: climbs the grove 15 feet left of the undertaker cornor, long moves up vertical face, moving left to overhanging face/ arete to top.

name: spazeman
description: climb up a grove of center right of the warm up wall. past shallow flake to face. this is the route directly above where the trail meets the cliff

name: Straight Outta Camden
description: Step out right from the birch tree and follow the crack as it diagonals up above a slab. Where the crack turns vertical, pull the small overhang and continue up a short, steep corner to the anchor.

name: streamline
description: face climb straight up brown face to steep roof.

name: undertaker
description: climb the right facing cornor through a low roof working up right to center of large roof.

name: Wallflower
description: Climb the left-leaning crack, then the right-leaning crack above. A short section of face climbing leads to the belay ledge.

name: wrong turn clyde
description: short little face normally toproped

name: Central Crack
description: The thin, steep crack just left of Running Free.  The route can be done as a clean-aid practice climb at A2.  Free ascents to date have involved preplaced clean gear.

name: Exasperator
description: This somewhat hidden climb goes up a wide crack in a left-facing corner past a birch tree to a square-cut overhang with a roof crack. Above, go right around another roof. It is also possible to step left to avoid the crux roof, which is more intimidating than actually difficult. (100') Extra pieces to 4" (at least) for the corner.

name: Glass factory
description: +)  A few yards right of the big outside corner that defines this section of the cliff, a short flare leads up to a ledge with a small tree.  Above, follow a left-facing (somewhat mossy) dihedral to an anchor.  (70)  Despite the dirty appearance, this is a fun, well-protected route with cool moves and features.  The  original route continued up dirt and loose blocks to the tree ledge; if you insist on having this experience, drop the star and add an X to the rating.

name: Groovey Grubworm
description: A few yards left is a steep, wide crack with a large spike of rock wedged in it at the start. Hand and fist jamming leads to chimneying past chockstones. From an alcove, climb a short slab on the right (crux, 2 bolts), turn the roof, and follow a fist crack up the headwall to a fixed anchor. Rappel with one rope. Take a full rack, including extra gear to 4. (80')

name: Jumpstart
description: Climb the low-angle arete on the right side of the formation to the right side of the big roof. Pull up onto the slab above and follow thin cracks left until you can exit onto easy ground. Belay from the big spruce tree (same as Twisted Schister), possibly using a directional.

name: Kudzu Corner
description: a steep, flared dihedral with several bolts and fixed pins. Start up a short overhanging wall to gain a ledge and the base of the corner, which leads up to a hard move around right (crux) and easier climbing up cracks and flakes to a thin crack in the headwall (140'). There is a fixed anchor in a hidden alcove at the top.

name: Millenium Falcon
description: The climb starts directly where you will approach the cliff up the talus field. Start up a dihedral to some thin cracks onto a right-facing crack and the crux followed by a two-bolt belay on a small ledge. (P2) Start up and right, clip a pin and bolt then trend straight up to two corners and some blocky terrain on the left. I climb the central corner directly to the tree, where you will find a webbing anchor/rappel point. With a 60M rope you can do the whole thing in one very long pitch. A 70M adds a sense of security.

name: Odin
description: Pull the obvious overhang (crux), then follow a much easier corner, crack system, and outside edge straight up to the anchor, which is next to a small spruce tree.

name: Running Free
description: Just left of Play Misty is this wildly positioned and well protected route. Take a light rack (up to a #2 Camalot or equivalent) and many quickdraws. The first pitch (crux) climbs an obvious crack, thin at first, past two bolts and three fixed pins to a 2-bolt belay. The second pitch follows a finger crack right to a slab, then climbs straight up past three bolts to a small ledge (optional belay; same as Play Misty). From here, work right past four bolts up a steep headwall to flakes and a short hand crack.

name: Twisted Schister
description: Between Jumpstart and Exasperator is a very impressive triangular roof. Start as for Jumpstart but step left, making a tricky move up a crack to an easy slab, then up to an alcove with a loose block. Undercling out left to a good stance, then exit the big roof out an arm sized crack. Well protected with large gear.

name: Agony of Defeat
description: Bouldery moves off the ground lead to sustained 5.10 face climbing up the narrow bleached streak passing six well spaced bolts to anchor.

name: Black Beauty
description: Begin at base of ramp leading to left facing flakes.  Climb through the flakes and finish the route passing eight bolts to an anchor.  Medium sized gear needed for the start.

name: The Black Chick Route
description: Start a step higher along the 4th class ramp, face climbing up the wide brown stain past 7 bolts to the anchor.  Medium gear.

name: Buteo and the Beast
description: This route begins 150' right of the Death Ramp and just right of some stacked blocks.  Fairly sustained 5.7 climbing but well protected.  Start partway up the Black Beauty ramp.  Face climb up brown face past 3 bolts to ledge then continue over varied face and flakes climbing past 7 more bolts to anchor.  A .5 tri-cam make this climb very safe.

name: Chick McNugget
description: Start on left side of 4th class gully at base of short right facing ramp.  Climb the vertical face past 2 bolts to a spruce tree.  Descend ramp.

name: Circling Vultures
description: Begin twenty feet right of Vertical Sketchmaster and climb easily through a shallow scoop to a bolt at twenty feet.  Pass 5 more bolts to anchor.

name: Death Ramp
description: Take the left angling access ramp to the top of the cliff if you desire.  An early route judging by the vintage pins found near the top.

name: Dusty Hamster
description: Directly above the base of the wooded ramp is a dark finger crack at mid height.  1: Wander up the face then up the thin finger crack splitting a face above a tree ledge.  2: Move left up the 5.4 face (no pro) to top.

name: Ebony and Ivory
description: Climb the unprotected right leaning 4th class ramp until just before it turns vertical.  Take the left trending bolted line past five bolts and some flakes to the anchor.

name: I'm a Frayed Knot
description: Climb a diagonalling line past horizontal cracks towards a broad white streak that is left of a birch tree.

name: Line of Cold Shuts  1
description: Up face following shallow arete.  More face climbing leads to the right past two overlaps and eventually reaches the anchors at 175'.  Nine cold shuts.

name: Line of Cold Shuts  2
description: Difficult moves off the ground lead to a line of cold shuts up to flakes then continue through the brown streak.  Seven cold shuts lead to an anchor at 80'.  Stop here or continue past more bolts to a higher anchor.

name: Mike Had to Go Home
description: The left-most route on the cliff.  Several horizontal breaks.

name: Natural Mystic
description: Start at the very left end of the wooded ramp and make an awkward mantle onto a shelf eight feet up then face climb past bolts to anchor.

name: Scraps
description: To the right of the ramp is a lowered angled face capped with some interesting corners and an overhang.  Take any route to the base of the left-most right-facing dihedral.  Up the corner then move right into a wide down-facing slot.  Finish out the cracks and left to the top.

name: Tiers for Walter
description: A new route not in the Clifton Guidebook.    Just to the right of Natural Mystic, closest to the tree adjacent to the cliff is where you'll find Tiers for Walter, easily identified by its two close initial bolts.    The moves by the first bolts is the first crux, with a second one coming 2/3rds of the way up.    Classic Clifton crystal pinching at it's finest. Can only be climbed with a 60 meter or longer rope.

name: Variety Pack
description: Follow an aesthetic right facing corner system to a small roof.  Make cruxy moves over roof to flakes.  Continue on face past bolt to rappel anchor.

name: Vertical Sketchmaster
description: A fine route suffering from encroachment on both sides.  Layback the series of vertical left-facing flakes to a bolt.  Move past another bolt to a ramp, run it out slightly over moderate ground to another bolt then move straight up through the crux bulge to easier ground and the anchor.  Six bolts, bring small to medium tri-cams and SLCD's.  Try not to clip the Circling Vultures anchors befor the third bolt or stop there for a nice 5.8 pitch.  Rappel with one rope to cold shuts or bring a second rope.

name: Dazed and Confused
description: Great runout slab climbing!  Start from the same stack of blocks as Overnight Sensation.  From the stacked boulders, scramble up a small slab, and out to a 20ft long crack.    Follow the crack up and exit left, aiming for the second treeledge.  Pull over a white bulge and take a deep breath.  Pitch 2: From the middle of the tree ledge, climb up the face, clipping one bolt and top out at bolt anchors.

name: Leading Colors
description: Climb the low overhang which becomes My Time.  Once established on face, follow line of bolts straight up clean slab.  The crux is pulling the bulge near the last bolt.  After last bolt, aim up and right to finish at the Vacationland anchors.  Rap with two ropes.

name: The Maine Line
description: A clean white slab leads to an obvious bulge where technical crimping gets you thru the crux.

name: My Time
description: A Clifton classic!  Make time for My Time - especially for the new leader, a really fun climb.    P1: Follow the ramp up the corner to its top and more right to a left facing flake.  This part is a little run out but just remember, its only 5.5  Layback the flake to a ledge then traverse straight right around bulge (crux) to a pin belay.    P2: Move out to the right following the dike on Ben's Balls (remember to protect your second).  Just before the pine tree, step up left past a bolt to a two bolt anchor on a ramp.    P3:  Move slightly left up to pin then trend up and right past three more bolts to a chained bolt anchor.  Third class up and left to summit, walk off to trail on the right or rappel with two ropes.    This route has a lot of potential for practicing rescue techniques due to a solid belay ledge (pitch 2) with a bomber anchor.  Have fun on this one, its awesome.

name: Overnite Sensation
description: One of the best climbs of its grade in Clifton.  Classic face climbing on superb rock.    Pitch 1:  Start on the flat, grassy ledge shared with Dazed and Confused moving up and right just below the bushes to gain a crack on the right. Climb crack or face on the right to bolt anchors (50')    Pitch 2:  Sustained climbing straight up the knobby, white face past 5 bolts and a Tri-cam placement.  Move left through the brown streaks to a two bolt anchor (140').  Rappel the route or 4th class to the summit.

name: Snake and Bake
description: Climb slab left of the corner of Ben's Balls passing several bolts through crux. Protection available in flakes and cracks, but avoid snake. Climb straight up to bolted anchor.

name: Vacationland
description: High quality slab climb on clean solid rock.  Start as you would for My Time, but break left after 25 ft.  Use knobs to gain the first bolt of Vacationland on the face.  Follow five bolts to rap anchor.  Rap with two ropes, or do optional less classic second pitch.  Rappel with two ropes.

name: Janitor in a Drum
description: Follow appealing mostly vertical cracks up to topout.  It took a lot of work to clean this route; it would be great for this route to get more traffic and stay clean!

name: Opening Day
description: This route opens with a few tricky moves that lead to a nice flake.  Continue up flake and belay from trees.

name: Lyback
description: Climb a large right facing dihedral/off width.  Make strenuous layback moves, which are punctuated with no hands rests.  Good gear placements may be found at the rests.  At the top of the dihedral, make somewhat technical moves up and left onto the top of the buttress.  It may feel much harder than 5.8 when climbing the route for the first time.

name: Son of a Birch
description: This striking crack is found on the right side of the buttress.    It begins with a over hanging left leaning crack, that becomes a right trending finger crack once you've hucked the overhang.    Takes gear like a champ, and is super fun.

name: Airline
description: There's a bolted climb right next to Bivy Route that has some fun moves? Really? This one was slightly furry but is now cleaning up again. A tough start leads to a section of large holds above. The last section, just past the last bolt, holds a slopey crux. Once you pull through, you can stand up on the ledge and ponder what you intend to do...  You can clip the anchors for Crankenstein and lower down (this is not the original route, let's call it Shortline), or you can plug some cams and follow the crack out the roof out left. Once you reach the notch, head on up to the anchor and hope the rope is long enough to get you back to the ground.

name: All Seriousness Aside
description: You know you wanna touch those huge jugs. Work your way up to the roof, then pull through on huge holds with a hard move coming onto the face above. From here, continue up the black face on small holds past several bolts.

name: Alley Fox
description: This route starts on Alleyway and continues up instead. Aim for the single bolt. It's a bit more of a natural and aesthetic line, because it runs straight up. The climbing is mostly <5.7 with a 5.8 crux move.

name: Alleyway
description: The path of least resistance moving left on angular hold and a ramp then straight up and right to a ledge.

name: Amber Waves of Grain
description: One of the first sport routes to take on the steep main face from the bottom up. Follow a slab up past two bolts to the start of walk on th emile side on wheaties ledge. Continue up the s-shaped stripe to a belay at horizontals. COntinue up past the crux bulge and several more bolts to an anchor.

name: Another Bolted Face Climb
description: Sustained delicate moves over small crimpy holds.  Although not a pure slab climb, the angle is less than vertical.  The climb is a little bit dirty at the end.

name: Apple Jam
description: Finger/Hand crack

name: Attitude Adjuster
description: Climb a ten foot, right-facing flake then make a long reach to a finger jam over the room.  Just when you think it's over, balance straight up face to join Alleyway.  Another popular testpiece.

name: Bivy Route
description: Starts 20' right of Punks in the Gunks, below the largest point of the above roof.  Start up a bulge (1st crux) perhaps getting a spot until you clip the first bolt.  Then up low angle climbing with positive holds.  Come up to a small roof (second crux) - pull it on the right on positive holds.  Continue up to a prominent ledge (last tricky part) that's big enough for a bivy!    This route is great and well-protected, do it!

name: Blaze of Glory
description: Climb up vertical rock on mostly positive holds.  This route is unique due to the absence of the usual Clifton crystal pinching.  The dike futures offer an array of jugs, side pulls, and a few pockets.  The crux comes about mid way up the climb where you need to place a cam in a horizontal and make a move up to a nice side pull/jug.

name: Bloody Phalanges
description: Face climb

name: Chinese Water Torture Direct
description: Move right from start of Stevie's Spanking up thin moves to below a roof.  Traverse right on horizontals.  Variation: continue right up corner.  Both routes were originally protected with a pin.

name: Climb Out or Ground Out
description: Scary face climb

name: Corner Line
description: Easy moves up big blocks then a moderate left facing corner. Tops off onto a ledge to the right.

name: Crankcase
description: An easy finger crack leads into crimpy and reachy face moves. Two bolts protect the face climbing which tops out at a ledge with a beefy two bolt anchor.

name: Crankenstein
description: The old guidebook says that this route likes to spit you off. It's techy, delicate, powerful, and actually quite fun. It starts with a low angle scramble up to the ledge, then figure out a sequence through the tiny holds and tiny feet up the vertical wall and over the first bulge. The first jug on the route comes at 2/3rd height and is followed by a little boulder problem to get over the next bulge. Big moves between big holds will get you to the anchor. Don't blow the last move or you'll have to go through it all again for the send!

name: Delirious
description: A classic line, although rarely repeated due to major runouts with groundfall potential and 1/4" bolts placed on hooks on the initial on-sight ascent. This route climbs the dark face 20' to the right of wheaties. The first bolt is located 30+ feet up. Climb to a comfortable ledge, then continue into a left facing dihedral.

name: Dirty Meat
description: Tackle the shallow, right facing dihedral and straight up the face above. The moves are not exactly obvious which makes it a little bit of fun although it could use a cleaning.

name: Down Under
description: Essentially a bolted boulder problem. Climb the weird, short corner and exit onto the crystal slab. Balance and crimp strength are your friends. Top it out.

name: Eagle Direct
description: A variation to the first pitch of Where Eagles Dare or a great single pitch on its own. Follow bolts directly up the thin face to the finger crack. Plug some small gear and climb the crack to the anchor.

name: The Eagle Has Landed
description: The most direct line on the cliff. This route climbs the distinct white  bleached streak 25 feet to the right of wheaties, 5 ft to the righ tof a large dropoff. Climb the steep face to the first band of horizontals. More crystal pinching through the middle tierpast ledge to faint arete and anchors.

name: The Eagle's Gift
description: An awesome route with thin slab/face climbing plus a small roof.   Start up a slab trending slightly left past bolts and some small ledges to base of roof.  Pull over the roof to an alcove and move right to an airy bolt anchor around corner.  165' of rope will just get you back to the ground.

name: Easy Stuff
description: This is the distinct dihedral corner topped by a large block to the far left (while looking at the wall) of the "Practice Wall."  Follow the finger crack up the back of the dihedral until you reach the block at the top.  Then work the horizontal crack to the left until you are out from under the roof.

name: Eavesy Stuff
description: Traverse to the right from Easy Stuff past bolts.

name: Element 115
description: A difficult line requiring many top ropes. Climb a slab at ground level, until you junction with walk on the mild side at a ledge. Continue up a shallow curving arete on the left. Their is an uncompleted second pitch.

name: Entrance Exam
description: Right Facing corner/bulge system on the entrance wall.  Some tricky moves, a big reach or two, and thin footwork throughout.  Much of the difficulty is finding the holds and realizing the moves.  The rest of the difficulty is dealing with small/sharp crimps and awkward stances.

name: Flake to Nowhere
description: First 5.12 at Clifton.

name: Foxy Lady
description: blocky climbing with finicky gear. Bit dirty when we climbed it. Not the best lead for a 5.7 climber due to finicky gear down low.

name: Happy Face
description: An obvious, inviting slab with four bolts.  Originally a top rope route or solo, this is now a safe and appealing lead at a moderate grade.  Rappel from tree.  A broken hold raised the grade a notch.

name: Hard Stuff
description: Looks can be deceiving. The top half of this climb is a juggy crack, while the bottom is a harmless looking corner/face. Getting off the ground and making any upward movement is tricky but may involve some slopers, crimps, and/or heel hooks. The crack is so thin at the bottom it is barely usable. Once you get to the left hand sidepull, you can make a huge move up into the good holds, plug some gear and finish it up.

name: Help
description: Short slab to blocky climbing followed by crack running through a dihedral at the upper portion of the climb. A little stemming in the dihedral or laybacking keeps the upper portion interesting. One of the better pitches on the practice wall, IMO. Good lead for the 5.7 leader as it takes great gear

name: Highlander
description: up 5.7 slab past 2 bolts to horizontals on blocky holds past small overhang crux to 2 bolt belay   up flakes to classic face climbing on blunt arete crux to another 2 bolt belay

name: Jack the Dripper
description: Boulder to a finger crack.

name: Longitudinal Wave
description: Recomended. Thin Cristal pinching leads to a classic mantle over a bulge. THe bulge distinguished this climb from surrounding climbs.

name: Maine Bound Memorial Route
description: Most 3rd class

name: No Rest for the Wicked
description: The steep face just to the right of Wheaties (the distinct layback crack). The climb just keeps on going. Climb past of total of 7 bolts.

name: The Only Frontier
description: hand/fist crack

name: Pried and Joy
description: Start at crack just right of ledges.  Awkward moves up the crack to ledge with giant block.  Continue up on large holds past horizontals and a bolt.

name: Punks in the Gunks
description: Unique for clifton, this route offers positive holds and pumpy climbing through the largest roof at the cliff. P1 passes through a couple "bivy ledges" aiming for a right facing flake with a bolt. After the flake, look left for a bolted belay on a large blocky ledge. P2 Take on the daunting diamond shaped roof, by traversing right past fixed gear and some bolts.

name: Rainy Day Deliverance
description: Straight up the headwall.

name: Reckless Abandon
description: Overheard as I rack up for this climb: "That thing is so thin!" Is it a steep slab or a less than vertical face climb? You be the judge. Crimp and technique your way past 4 bolts to the anchor. Somewhere in there are a few good holds and some fun moves. The toughest moves come between the first two bolts and just before the last bolt. Pitching off just before the anchor is heartbreaking.

name: Root of Choice
description: Climb up the right facing corner, which forms the right end of the 5.10 Ledge.  A nice route when dry, however this route often wet.    This is the best way to access the 5.10 Ledge even when its damp.

name: Route Awakening
description: A good way to access the Toilet Bowl feature - not to be missed.    Start right of Cereal Killer on a clean slab below a small roof.  Climb the slab on ledges trending right to below the roof.  Go around the right side of the roof and up the face following a groove.  Follow the bolt line (10b) or stay slightly right (easier) up to a ledge with a bolt anchor.

name: Sales Pitch
description: A short, bouldery route that requires some strong fingers. Start up easy terrain with a crack for hands and slabby feet until you reach the first bolt. Head straight up using a short crack on the right, then some crimps, followed by a slopey seam. The crux comes at the top. Once you've figured out how to get there, topping out is easy.   A quick way to set up a toprope is to run a lap on the bolted first pitch of Crossover.

name: Scrappy Face
description: A fun, short boulder problem of a route. It could be bouldered with a lot of pads. Start directly beneath the bolts and climb straight up on decent crimps.

name: Short Stuff
description: Originally a boulder problem

name: Slice of the Gunks
description: A fine moderate trad route.  Pull through horizontal cracks on  clean vertical rock for 30ft.  Pull the crux at the end of the vertical section (5.8), and follow easy low angle rock up to anchors.

name: Standard Route AKA Open Book
description: Short slabby section to a ledge into a dihedral, step right and continue straight up to a new looking two bolt anchor with chains and rap rings.

name: Stevie's Spanking
description: PG retrobolted face climb

name: Talus Scout
description: A short, powerful route on a boulder on the southern approach trail.  Moves from left to right, and then right up the face of this boulder.  Some of the moves may be a little bit easier if you are tall.

name: The Tax Is Too Steep
description: This route starts on a 15 sq. ft. platform (roughly) to the right of "Texas Two Step".  Right off the deck you'll find a nice grippy (and sharp) start into a nice friction section, which will lead you to the crux. You'll find more sharp quartzite crystals and crimpers at the crux (located over half to 3/4 way to the top). This portion of "The Tax Is Too Steep" will leave you balancing on the tip of your toes and praying for a 'thank God hold' to magically appear before you cut loose. The route ends/tops out on the edge of "Catwalk" ledge. "Catwalk" ledge runs the distance from directly above "Texas Two Step", continuing several yards past "The Tax Is Too Steep".    All in all its a very good climb to warm up to and work on your balance. From what I gather you can start this route below the 15 sq. ft. platform where "Texas Two Step" instead of taking the ledge staircase that leads to "The Tax Is Too Steep".

name: Texas Two Step
description: Follow a finger crack to a tree ledge then move past several bolts to anchor.  Originally done with one bolt and tricky stopper placements.

name: Upside down staircase
description: Pumpy climbing on polished granite. Steep for a 5.8 trad climb.

name: Walk on the Mild Side
description: Classic. Follow the right traversing line of bolts from the far right end of wheaties ledge. Follow the bolted traverse out right to a pleasent ledge, move right until anchors. Continue up a steep face past an assortment of bolts, to a dike. Continue up the dike to a two bolt anchor.

name: Wave Guide
description: Months of top-roping led to the F.A of this crystal pinching marathon. Run it out from ground level, or start at the far right end of wheaties ledge. Climb the steep bleached face past five bolts to a two bolt anchor.

name: What's In a Name?
description: Diagonals right past 3 bolts (2 hangers have been removed) to trees.

name: Wheaties
description: Another classic!  Layback an obvious left-facing flake to a face passing several bolts to ledge.  Belay here or continue forty feet to a bolt anchor.  The original second pitch (Breakfast of Champions, 5.9+) is now easily combined with the lower section by continuing straight up the face past bolts to a new anchor below the room on the Cross-over ledge.  The original route had only one bolt on the face above the initial flake.

name: Where Eagles Dare
description: The best 5.10 in Clifton.    P1: Start up the left side of a blank face to horizontal with hidden piton, traverse right and up the finger crack to a ledge. Continue past a bolt to crossover ledge. P2: Follow out right and up to a gear belay at horizontals. P3: Traverse left onto the face and climb up the exposed face past three bolts to a bolt anchor, or top out.

name: Witch Wonder
description: An awesome classic two pitch crack climb that you'll want to do over and over.    For the first pitch you can either climb the bolted chunky monkey arête of Highlander (5.7) or slither up the dirty dihedral and slamming through a slot chimney (5.9)    For the second pitch follow the crack up and through a squeeze chimney that's quite a squeeze, on the scale of something like being born. Getting into the chimney's the crux. Then follow the easy crack the rest of the way up to the anchor bolts @ the top. (5.7)    It's a fun climb, with beautiful views. Bring some friends for a party because the belay ledge between the two pitches is huge!

name: Big Brother
description: Follow a series of underclings, with each one becoming a little harder than the last until moving up a technical face. Cop a rest at a large hold then finish up another technical but easier face to lower offs.

name: Heavy Weather Scaling
description: This is a link-up that provides the line of least resistance to the top of the Sundog Wall. Start on After the Gold Rush, go up and left to a ramp. Follow the ramp/ledge leftward, and eventually go straight up (crux) to finish on Bear Necessities.

name: High Noon
description: Start in bushes below a beautiful water stained slab. Tricky climbing up the face leads to a roof feature. Climb past this to a pumpy traverse then a rest. Tricky and reachy moves lead to the chains.

name: Lumiere
description: Follow three bolts to a fixed pin in a horizontal crack. Continue following bolts up and slightly left to the top.

name: Melt Dog
description: Start on Meltdown, clipping the first two(second with 24” runner) then climb bolts three and four of Sunnyside Up, finally moving left along a horizontal crack into Sundog below its last bolt. A .5-.75 sized piece protects the runout from Sunnyside Up into Sundog. Best warm up or just a good route in general.

name: Meltdown
description: Follow bolts to a small roof and continue above the roof on small crimps (crux).

name: Sundog
description: Start below an overlap, climb up to an undercling and an impossibly long reach(height dependent). From here, head right then back left, pull a small roof and head straight up on big moves to the anchors.

name: Sunnyside up
description: Great route, it lies on the Sundog wall. It's the second route from the last on the right side. The crimpy crux is within the first two bolts. After that pull a small roof and sustained crimpy climbing follows to the anchors.

name: Zebra
description: Two cruxes with quality but easier climbing in between. The guide mentions only one short stuff crux, but I found there to be two hard sections leading me to believe a hold may have broken on this. Follow a sharp crimpy face on black streaks to a roof, pull the roof to a rest and a deceptive and crimpy crux to the last bolt. One last lock off leads to anchors. Needs new LOs.

name: B3 Bomber
description: The crux is within the last few moves of the route. It requires an reachy shallow underline on unsecure feet. The route starts by walking on a right angling ledge to the first bolt and then straight up into a right facing corner. You can layback the corner or skip the layback for a harder variation.

name: Can't Count to Five
