description: Three boulder problems, each separated by a good rest. However, they can be a tad run out as the name of the route refers to not having enough bolts to equip it properly. Fun nonetheless. Start right of the tree and beneath the first bolt. There are holds out right to get up to it. Continue straight up to a tricky crux at the very end. The last boulder problem is the hardest, but at least the fall is clean!

name: The Guardian
description: CLimb through a shallow overhang with flakes and cracks past two bolts. Pullover the arete and scamper up easier slabs to the pine tree anchor.

name: Male Lesbian
description: Male Lesbian is a very bouldery route with three distinct cruxes separated by good rests. The start moves are the first crux as you tackle the technical bulge to get established on the wall. Move up the slab to a hard face sequence and then get ready for the big moves on good holds to finish it up. Fun, well protected, and tough.

name: Maple Run
description: Start on the right facing juggy flake. Mantle on ledge and carefully walk few feet to the right. Do pumpy moves to bouldery buldge. Pull the buldge and move right and up to anchor.    The first route done on this wall and for a long time was the only route on this wall.

name: Maple Syrup
description: Climb directly below anchors for Maple Run. 6 Bolts to Cold Shut anchor. Crux is after the second bolt and continues through sustained holds for two bolts. Appears as a TR only route in Tierny's guide book but has since been bolted.

name: The Mean Sister
description: Hard for its grade with some speculation that the route is actually 12a. Clip first bolt, then a v2/3 boulder problem to good resting jug. From there go leftwards towards arete using layback and then to compression moves, v4+ boulder problem. From there mantle onto slab, run it out next bolt. Then easier climbing but with exposure to holds under roof. Do big moves, pull roof and then crux mantle.     Bring at least a 60m rope to lower to the ground from the anchor. You can use 50m rope also but you will have to top out and then walk down.

name: The Perfect Time
description: Bouldery route. Technical moves off the ground leading to a hands free stance. From there sustained overhanging moves. Leads to very powerful ending moves after last bolt and before anchor.

name: Vertical Toad
description: Very techy, bouldery and tough. Starting in the middle of the crag, climb up to and mantle onto a small ledge to reach the first bolt, then traverse the crack up and right to reach a jug and the second bolt. Climb straight up with difficulty using some small crimps and an undercling, clip the 3rd bolt mid-crux and pull a couple more hard moves to reach a rest in the underclings. A few big moves on decent holds will get you to a topout and the anchors.

name: Babysitter's Route
description: A decent route that climbs a techy face. Start on the right side of the wall with the arete and face and climb straight up on crimps and crystals with a jug or two tossed in. Probably better as a toprope unless the original bolts get replaced!

name: Under The Weather
description: A short but pumpy and overhanging route. Start on edges, move up to a rail, then into jugs for a few moves. Work your way through some crimps and a gaston and you'll be at the lip in no time. Topout or lower off.

name: Broken Mirror
description: Gymnastic climbing out the overhang to a powerful crux up the short corner. Start up the corner/crack and figure out how to get to the good jug on the face. Now commit to the climb and swing your feet left. Tricky moves on pinches, sidepulls, crimps will get you to a good rest stance and fun climbing on better holds will get you back to Riders on the Storm to finish up to the anchor.

name: Easter Island
description: Steep technical face climbing up a white streak with cool square cut holds. The crux is in the vertical section when the holds get small. Bold sport climbing, can be made safer by adding a trad piece after second bolt. The start is easy but do not fall.

name: Mirror Image
description: Fun climbing up the flake turns into somewhat scary but much easier climbing at the top. Climb the flake to reach the bolt at the crux and navigate rightward with a jug and a few small holds. Once through the crux, the difficulty eases considerably, but you'll want some small pieces to protect you as you climb the face above. Finish straight up to the 2-bolt anchor.

name: Riders On the Storm
description: Start by pulling on the huge flake in the diheral leading a bolt. The first moves can be protected by a big cam. Clip that bolt or proceed left to second bolt. The first bolt is not part of this route. If you clip it then unclip it after clipping second bolt to avoid rope drag. After second bolt, proceed straight up.     Clip the anchors, have a seat and enjoy a great view.

name: Storm Trooper
description: Technical, vertical face climbing with a couple of short cruxes. Start up the corner until you're directly beneath the bolt line, or climb Riders on the Storm to the first bolt and then follow the bolts straight up. Using a decent hold in the seam, work up the clean face on tiny holds to reach a bad rest on slopers, then make some tricky moves to better holds. Fun climbing on better holds to the anchor.

name: Tooth Fairy
description: Pumpy moves up a corner system that doesn't climb like anything else in the area. The holds are mostly large but the problem is figuring out how to use them. Scramble down from the alcove to reach the first bolt and have your belayer scramble down as well or else you'll suffer from rope drag. Follow some jugs and the corner crack up to the top of the pillar (sling the pillar if you want) and rest up before launching into the downward and right facing corner. Is it a layback? Gaston? Undercling? Figure it out. There is a hidden jug just past the bolt and brings you to the end of the crux. One more trick move lets you stand atop the jug and then up easier ground to the top.

name: Black Tide
description: Fun face/slab climbing up the center of the main wall. What was once an X-rated trad climb is now a well bolted sport climb! Traverse out left to reach a belay anchor at the base of Craig's Crack. Climb over the bulge to gain the slab, then follow the brown streak straight up. When it gets steeper, technique your way through the crux, then finish up to the anchor.  For a 2nd pitch, bring trad gear & continue into the alcove above and exit via one of the cracks.

name: Cool Jerk
description: While this is a 3 pitch climb, most people will only do the 1st pitch. Climb up the large crack that looks like a flake but sure doesn't climb like one. You'll find yourself at some large blocks and you can clip a bolt. Move straight up the face onto the ledge, then traverse left to the short corner. Figure out the corner, maybe with the help of a mono crack, then clip the bolt anchor.  If you wish to continue, climb up over the bulge, then move right to the base of the off-width on the upper wall. Finish up cracks to the top.

name: Cool Jim
description: This is a link up of Cool Jerk into Jim Dandy that eliminates most of the wandering nature of Jim Dandy while still keeping the crux. Start up Cool Jerk and climb the crack to reach the bolt above the blocks. Climb up and right into the flared corner of Jim Dandy, passing another bolt before getting to the fun. Finish it up to the bolt anchor.

name: Craig's Crack
description: Mega classic route. Great slab climbing leads to a crack/corner and a bolt anchor on a ledge. Perfect to cruise on a hot summer day. There is a slight runout on the short slab between the two cracks.  For a 2nd Pitch, finish up the face to the roof, then either finish on the Dike Route out left or follow the wide crack.

name: D.C.
description: A nice little warmup or first lead on the right side of the Main Wall and also a great way to access the climbs on the Upper Wall. Easy climbing follows a line of bolts up the stairstep face before reaching the crux. Weave left then right through the bulges/ledges and then up to the bolt anchor.  A 2nd and 3rd pitch may be done by heading up left to join Cool Jerk at the start of the offwidth, then climb the offwidth to the face above.

name: Direct Helix (Betty Boop)
description: A well bolted moderate on the right side of the Main Wall. Start up over varied terrain to reach the clean face above. Crimp and balance to the anchor.  While fun on it's own, this route also provides easy access to Double Helix and Hand Jam above.

name: Don't Let the Man Bring You Down
description: A fun addition to the cliff. Start up the wide crack/flake to reach the first bolt on the black streak. Step right above the bolt and crimp & balance your way up the face to reach a ledge, a mantle, and then a rest. Continue up the black streak with a shallow dihedral/dike feature on the left side and the crimpy face on the right. Climb over a small bulge near the top and you'll find yourself at the anchor.

name: Eight is Enough
description: Fun face climbing that is unfortunately too dangerous to enjoy in it's current state. Start at the left side of the main wall near Spring Fever and just right of the trees. Scramble up a small rock or climb the short dihedral and traverse left to the dike. Follow the dike up to the ledge, then reach a high bolt. Pull the crux bulge and aim for the next bolt and then for the anchor.  The old guide claims there were 3 bolts, however I could only find two. The hardwear is due for an upgrade and should have 5 bolts plus the anchor.

name: Jerky Jim
description: This is a link up of Jim Dandy into the finish of Cool Jerk that creates a gem of a climb that heads directly up the buttress. Start up the discontinuous cracks on Jim Dandy to reach the blocks and the bolt. Climb straight up past the bolt to gain the ledge. Clip another bolt and finish up the short corner to reach the bolt anchor.

name: Jim Dandy
description: A fun stretch of climbing. Follow discontinuous cracks up the buttress to the large blocks up high. Clip a bolt on the left, get up on the ledge, then traverse right to another bolt. Finish up the flaring corner above to reach the bolt anchor.

name: The Man Got You Down
description: Super thin, technical climbing leads to more featured rock with a bunch of fun moves. Start up easier terrain and head towards the first bolt. Clip in and enjoy the crux on small feet and smaller hands to reach a decent crimp. Continue up the more abundant holds past a few bolts and then start plugging gear when the bolts run out. Shares the same anchor as Don't Let the Man Bring You Down, or continue further to the Midnight Rambler anchor. Rappel or lower.

name: Midnight Rambler
description: This corner/crack system is worthwhile and fun. The old guide referred to it as dirty, but it appears to have cleaned up over time. Follow the crack and corner straight up with good gear and a variety of moves before reaching the bolt anchor. Rappel with a 60m rope.  From here, you can continue with a 2nd pitch to reach the base of the off-width, and then a 3rd pitch of climbing the off-width and stepping left onto the face above. Most people are content with the first pitch.

name: Peggy Lane
description: Follow the obvious low angled corner at the left end up (sometimes through bushes and trees) to a small vertical section that brings you to the top.

name: Spring Fever (aka Risky Business)
description: There's an anchor up there! In what seems like the middle of the face, the shiny bolts beg you to come visit. Begin beneath the lone bolt and work your way up the brown streak, staying mostly left. Past the bolt, you'll find a few cam placements on a small ledge, then head towards the obvious flake. Once there, it's not far to the ledge and the anchor.  If you need a 2nd pitch, continue up the Dike Route on the left.

name: Twist & Shout
description: This route tackles the right side of the center face between Spring Fever and Craig's Crack. Head up the ramp to the right and then climb straight up. There is a small flaring crack and a hollow flake and eventually you'll be on the ledge and sharing the bolt anchor of Craig's Crack.  Best to toprope this one after leading one of the other climbs.  For a 2nd pitch, finish on the Dike Route, or continue straight up and pull the roof at a jug.

name: Elf Toes
description: Climb the brown streak on the left side of the slab on the Mountaineer's Wall.  Follow the brown streak up to a ledge (rest) then continue up past more bolts to reach the anchor.  This is a delicate sustained route that only gets harder the farther up you go.  Make to single rope rappels or use two ropes to rap.

name: Movin'To Montana
description: Pitch 1: Locate a large corner system with a distinctive triangular roof hanging out over it.  Begin by climbing up easy ground on crumbling rock and traverse left under an off width crack to gain the bottom of the large right facing corner.  Follow the corner up and belay on large hand sized gear below a chimney.      Pitch 2: Climbing the chimney using nice cracks and face holds.  Belay on gear.  Rap from trees or walk off.

name: Agro Shagg
description: High first bolt, but a good jug to clip off of (albeit, a high foot, so a bit sketch; bring a stick clip if you must). I shoot out right to a side pull on Looney Toons; being only a few feet to the right, this doesn't seem off route, but makes Agro a bit of a squeeze job. Another couple moves brings you the other direction and back again to the crux: a big slanting pinch that you can barely fit both hands on; man-handle this a bit and go big with style to a crimp, or if you're a complete bamf, go further around right to the jug utilizing a poor sloper as an intermediate. Rest. Do some magic to the real bomber side pull rest, then get ready for the finger crack next to the last bolt (a good 30' below the anchor). If you can't finagle your fat paws into this tiny crack, do some more magic and high stepping to get into the next section of adventure climbing. Then begins the great unknown overgrown chossfest with hidden jugs (probably hard 10). If you're prepared, you've got a couple of small nuts (to match the big ones that have gotten you this far) and/or a #1 for a few choice placements to keep you safe, as well as some mithril to ward off the trolls and giant spiders that guard the anchors. Good luck; you're gonna need it.

name: Block Buster
description: Easy climbing leads to interesting moves past 3 bolts onto the low-angle slab above. Stop here at a 2 bolt anchor to make it 5.9, or continue for a pumpy burn up an overhanging crack/seam past 3 more bolts.

name: Cell Block D
description: start up the first couple bolts of Two Shaved Heads then make a big iron cross left into a really cool traverse sequence. finish up with a couple bouldery moves and dead points. the holds aren't typical shagg, but thats what makes this route unique and deserves more travel.

name: Continental Divide
description: Scramble up to the belay anchors of Ritual. Follow the crack and flake system past a few bolts up and right to the top of the cliff.

name: Cut Split and Delivered
description: Climb the right facing flake for 20 feet to the first bolt then face moves lead to the anchors.

name: Death to the Queen
description: Another route that breaks through the huge roof above the Standard Route crack. This is the middle route starting off the "Bird's Perch" ledge. Belay from anchors on the left side of the ledge. Follow the shallow dihedral and finger crack past tenuous moves to the huge roof. Wild climbing out the roof leads to a fun dihedral and the top of the cliff.

name: Deja Voodoo
description: Ascends the interesting white face on the far right end of Shagg.

name: Diesel
description: Start up short shagg then continue straight up to anchors of great escape, up the slightly overhanging beautiful granite face with the tiny crimps. VERY BOULDERY!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!  From Nathan Kimble: A variation of this route was first climbed by David Graham call Diesel Bob. Dave was kind enough to stay off my project until I completed it.

name: Diesel Bob
description: A tough link-up. Climbs the lower crux of What About Bob into the crux of Diesel.

name: Fat Bastard
description: What do you call a fat lady jacked-up on Ginseng?  Fat Bastard!  This is just another link-up that is too classic not to be mentioned.  If Ginseng is not long, pumpy, or classic enough for you, keep going up and right from the Ginseng anchor to the top of Fat Lady via fun, exposed, pumpy climbing to enjoy one of the best lines on the cliff.

name: Fat Pig
description: Start up ginsing then before crux head striaght up headwall to fist set of anchors. There is also a direct start that is harder and bumps up the grade a tiny bit to solid B. It is seldom if ever done.

name: Freedom Variation
description: Variation start to the Great Escape. Finger crack and stemming to the first bolt of Great Escape.

name: Fuzzy Rhino Slippers
description: Technical face climing on semi-chossy rock. It is unlike many of the other steep climbs at Shagg.The crux is at the first bolt. More technical climbing and the use of the right arete get you to the chains. When you are at the top enjoy the beautiful view of the pond and the western Maine mountains!

name: Ginseng Route
description: Ginseng is perhaps the best route at Shagg. It's pretty much the perfect endurance test (for the Northeast). Start off a pile of boulders left of the obvious right-angling weakness of The Great Escape (10d).    The first half of the route climbs up a beautiful pane of Shagg's trademark fine-grained granite. Unlike granite elsewhere in the area, this rock forms into perfect horizontal slots that make for good, if a bit slopey, handholds. A few taxing moves take you to a break. This is where the cliff changes to schist and the angle kicks back even more.     The schist is a bit reminiscent of the rock at Orange Crush at Rumney and offers interesting big flake/sidepull features. Like all good endurance routes, a tough move guards the anchors.

name: The Great Escape
description: The Great Escape climbs the obvious right-angling fault up the center of the cliff. It's amazing that a route of this grade climbs up this steep wall, as much harder routes exist both to the left and the right of The Great Escape.    This route is pretty much the perfect warmup. It's close to the harder routes and has good holds but maintains a steep angle throughout it's length. However, if you're here just to tick this route, I'd also say that this is worth the trip to the crag.     It's a bit runout to the first bolt. If you have an extra-super long stick, you could stick clip it, maybe. Start off the pile of boulders and begin climbing up and right. Follow the big holds to some tricky moves right below the chains.

name: Grimas De Oro
description: Climb the beautiful arete on the backside of this  boulder from a sit start. Great tensiony moves! FA/SA 2004.

name: It Ain't Pretty Being Easy
description: This route is like a little piece of Rumney transplanted about 100 miles east. It Ain't Pretty climbs up a sinuous line of ill-defined corners on the far left end of the cliff. This is the schist part of the crag. The cool granite starts a bit to the right. As with most shisty climbs, this route offers strange climbing on a daunting array of corners, blocks, and ledges. As for the crux, I'd say it was more sustained than cruxy. I just felt off-balance the whole way.

name: Kick to the Teeth
description: Bouldery! Hard moves off the ground to a stance. More tough climbing leads to the the chains.

name: Late for Dinner
description: One of Shagg's easier offerings, the route offers a bit of face climbing, a mantle, and a small roof move.

name: The Long and Short of It
description: Not the most popular route at Shagg, at first glance the route appears uninspiring yet the climbing is interesting and varied. Starts out at the base of It Ain't Pretty and immediately moves left requiring big moves on good crimps and sidepulls. An exciting sequence spits you out on  a rest ledge above half-way.  Finish straight up and right with a few difficult moves to gain the top.

name: Looney Tunes
description: The first 30 or so feet of this climb is what it's all about. Steep reachy side pulls lead up and left to a cool knob. The crux requires some tricky foot intensive beta with the knob while reaching way out right to a big  rail, suck it in hold the swing and mantle it out.  Try to catch a breath and climb the second half, good thing it's probably easy 10 from here.

name: Loopy Noodle Butt Conspiracy
description: Begins from chain anchors on the left side of the "Brid's Perch" ledge. Thin climbing past 3 bolts lead to the huge roof above. Crazy campus moves out left lead to a cool stemming finish and the top of the cliff.

name: Meltdown
description: Meltdown climbs the heavily chalked line on the right, shorter side of the cliff. It's the next route right of Shaggin Wagon.  This route is like a steeper version of Venus at Rumney. It's all about power-endurance. Thin holds just seem to keep coming and success depends on your ability to manage the pump. If you sit back and envision the perfect sport route, then you are probably thinking about Meltdown.

name: Nice Tooth
description: Start up Ginsing.After the crux at flake traverse left 10 feet into the crux of tightrope. Finish at anchors for tightrope.

name: Patches the Clown
description: A great route often overlooked because of a lack of bolts on the first 40 feet of climbing. Climbs the Standard Route crack to a move up and right to reach the first bolt (5.5). Fun well protected climbing leads through smooth rock to a finishing crux mantle to reach the anchors. Used to access the "Bird's Perch" ledge and the climbs that start from there.

name: Pushes Little Daisies
description: Fantastic, relentless, exposed face climbing up greenish rock to the top of the cliff!

name: The Raging Bull
description: This is an amazing bouldering problem located at the base of the ridge before the hike up from the pond to the Crag. Bushwack to the right before the hike up and you will find a white granite overhanging roof. Start on the corner where the roof meets the base of the wall, fire up to the overhanging arete, then to a small hold on the face of the overhang. From here slap and move into position to throw for the outer edge of the roof for a wild finish! FA/SA 2004.

name: Recombinant DNA
description: Difficult face moves off the ground get you past the first 3 bolts and a run-out to a 2 bolt anchor. Continue up easy terrain past 2 more bolts to crux moves in the white rock band to a ledge and anchors.  Harder for short people.

name: Rhino Flake
description: An interesting jaunt up the flake/crack system. Usually done as a solo but can be gear protected.

name: The Ritual
description: Rumney-esque route at Shagg Crag

name: Rough Rhino
description: Fun but sharp face climbing brings you up along the edge of the arete to the top of the boulder. Just about the easiest line at Shagg.  Originally done with only one bolt protecting a thin move near the bottom.

name: Screw It
description: One of the few great endurance routes at Shagg, and one of 4 that start on The Great Escape. To reduce rope drag, skip the clip on the flake of Shagg It, or bring a full length sling. This makes the next section (where the gray rock meets the schist) a bit creepy, albeit safe with a good belay. There are a couple of hard moves before a good hold can be acquired to clip off of after this section. After rounding the corner, finish by climbing into Shagg Zag by either down climbing a bit and unclipping to reduce drag again, or merely skip it and prepare for a ride if the juice isn't there to make it through this endurance crux. All in all, a great newer route that needs to see more traffic, and could use another brushing or two. Thanks Jim Ewing for putting this up. Two stars for the complexity of the lead.

name: Shagg It
description: Start up great Escape then bust straight up and left out the proudest line of the cliff.

name: Shagg Zag
description: Great climb! A little scarier than it is hard. Technical I think by Shagg standards. Climb the start of Great Escape, then instead of "escaping" to Great Escapes" anchors (hence the name) continue straight up then veer left through techy and exposed moves to the crux. Fun Climbing! The "ORIGINAL" line BTW.  [NOTE: Name changed to "Shagg Zag" 5/27/20 to conform with original name and current guidebooks.  R Hall ME Admin. ]

name: Shaggadelic
description: Start in underclings into a low thug crux to 1st bolt- then some easier climbing to a dyno ( or dead point if you are tall)  at 4th bolt - following that a difficult boulder problem -v7 isn -leads to jugs followed by a few easier thin moves into a glory easy finish! a little runout to chains adds some spice, but remains safe.

name: Shaggin Wagon
description: If you came to the crag looking to tick 5.12, Shaggin Wagon is the route for you. This is not to say that the route is easy for the grade--far from it. Shaggin Wagon is all of 12a; however, success depends more on being tall than being strong.    The crux is at the bottom after which it's all about hanging on. If you are tall, the first move shouldn't be much of a problem. Expect a deadpoint to a pretty good hold.  If you are short...well, I'm tall, so your struggles are alien to me.     The difficulties continue up a cool undercling/layback feature. Good foot work is key. Pumpy edges follow to the anchors. I've heard people call this route 12c, though they were all pretty short.

name: Short Bob
description: A fun, easier alternative to What About Bob.  Avoids the nasty crux at the bottom of What About Bob then bails to anchors before the upper difficulties.

name: Short Shagg
description: This mini-route climbs up a left-facing flake just to the right of The Great Escape. There's not much routefinding or beta indecision here: just climb the flake to a two bolt anchor. The extension above the anchors is a cool-looking 13d called Diesel.

name: Sour Diesel
description: Climb Diesel, but rather than finishing at the 10 anchor climb right to the rest ledge of What About Bob and finish up the left leaning dihedral of of the original What About Bob.  Seeing as how Diesel climbs WAY better than it looks, it has always been marred only by its short length.  The original What About Bob finish, originally rated 12d????, lay unrepeated for years after only two assents by Jim Ewing and Luke Parady.  The cryptically hard sequence left many a hard man shaking their head as they lowered off completely stymied.  Finally unlocked over ten years later by Chris "The Deulenator" Deulen, the Bob finish appropriately caps Diesel with a feel through the upper dihedral reminiscent of perhaps the sierras more than Shagg and makes it totally full-value and way more rad.  Even with the rest ledge it adds considerable difficulty to Diesel and greatly solidifies the 13d grade.

name: Standard Route
description: Fun, juggy crack up the slab.

name: Summer Smoke
description: Climb up through the right-trending flake crack to a big move to a jug. Sharp face holds lead to the chains.

name: Tightrope
description: Tightrope climbs the line of bolts just left of Ginseng. The crux, coming about two thirds of the way up, is quite a memorable one. Despite my efforts to find alternate beta, the move boils down to a huge dyno. With a very thin left crimp, you set up and throw and hit a sloper at full extension. Holding the outward swing is the most difficult part. It's just so easy to let go of that small crimp, but that's really the only thing holding you in.     If the climbing leading up to the crux was trivial, I'd call this an average route. Since the moves before the crux are still hard, maybe about 12a, and since the crux move is so spectacular, I call this a tough and very fulfilling 12d.

name: Two Shaved Heads
description: Two Shaved Heads is located on the far right side of the cliff, past Meltdown, on a separated section of rock. The routes here are slightly less pumpy than those on the main part of the cliff, partly because they're shorter and partly because they're less steep.     Unlike many other routes at Shagg, Two Shaved Heads offers vertical, technical climbing. It is also much harder than it looks. After the steep, relatively easy start, the climbing becomes delicate and and culminates in some hard moves at the top. Expect to use your fingers more than your biceps on this one.

name: Unitard
description: Bouldery! Climb up the white dike.

name: Unknown
description: Great climbing up slightly less than vertical rock to a short overhang with positive holds.

name: Unknown Name
description: A fun adventure and a great second pitch to Summer Smoke or Kick to the Teeth.  From the slab above Summer Smoke and Kick to the Teeth, follow the flake and fun face holds to lower angle rock and the anchors. Link with either of the bottom pitches for a 100 foot pitch!

name: Velvet Elvis
description: The weird, water-smoothed face at the far right end of Shagg.

name: What About Bob?
description: What About Bob? (WAB) was bolted by Bob Parrot in '96/'97 and climbs the steep white section of rock to the right of Short Shagg, beginning in the thin band of quartzite-mixed rock that shoots straight up from the bouldery start. Cryptic and acrobatic (as described by Chris Cook), this route is hard to on-sight for 5.12 climbers. Tense climbing with a few possible sucker holds (depending on your height beta) lead to good jugs and a traverse to the right.  Face climb to a big ledge, breath, and prepare for the boulder problem that follows the seam up left, then face climbs to the finish anchors.     This original left variation has only seen 3 ascents-Jim Ewing, Luke Parady, and myself (mumbles of holds breaking and magic "foot dyno" beta are frequently heard when referencing this finish). Per Jim Ewing, Luke Parady thought it climbed like a 13a/b, but was probably only 12d. From my personal experience, I would put this upper crux sequence around V9 (or 13c overall). It has thwarted the likes of, yes, Dave Graham, as well as Josh Wharton. Does this mean I'm better than Dave Graham and Josh Wharton? Probably.     Note: If you unlock the crux sequence, the theme from Star Wars plays.

name: What About Bobcat
description: WABC is the right variation to WAB after the ledge rest. Start out the same for WAB (the cheater way starts in the juggy side pulls to the left of the start and would probaly only merit a 12c rating accompanied by shaming from the locals).    This is the more common finish (bolted by Jim Ewing in '05/'06; Steve Dyer's nickname is apparently "bobcat") and moves into the start of the small dihedral and then exits right to another crux: moving back out to more face climbing with fun moves. (A knee bar is rumored to be used around here.) The chains are 2 bolts up.    WABC is probably the diamond in the rough of Shagg. The moves are exciting, fun, and nearly every section has 2 or 3 types of beta, all equally fun but suited to different styles. Right on par with Shagg It (though much different climbing). I'm surprised more people don't get on this thing, though with it's intimidating looking start and never-ending movement, it might not be hard to see why. That said, this route is freakin awesome! This will definitely be one I might find myself coming back to again and again. Top 3 best routes at Shagg in my opinion.

name: When the fat lady sings
description: Climb Fat pig but continue up the route past 1st set of anchors to the obvious finish at the top. If and or WHEN you whip before the anchors watch out for the tree................:).

name: Anti-Fat Bastard Cream
description: Climb up the slab to a small ledge. Thin face moves past the 2nd bolt to the roof. Pull the roof onto the overhang above and finish to the anchors. 4 bolts to anchors.

name: City Dweller
description: One of the easiest routes at Bald Bluff, this makes a good warmup for routes at the Lower Dike and the South Wall. Climbs flakes and jugs on gently overhung to vertical terrain to an awkward crux move at the 5th bolt. Rest at a stance then fire up the final headwall to anchors.

name: Fat Bastard
description: Climb up the black and white streaked face 2 bolts to the roof. Climb out the roof into a jug on the overhang above. Clip the third bolt and make some hard pulls to the anchors.

name: Tough Bastard
description: Burly climbing with some big pulls up through the steepest terrain near the middle of the wall. Stick clip first bolt. 4 bolts to anchors.

name: Unfinished Project
description: A partially bolted open project up the bulging overhang. Looks very difficult. 2 bolts up high to anchors.

name: City Link
description: This is a link-up of "Spikes & Twine" and "Welcome to Greenwood City". Climb the first 12 bolts of "Spikes" then move right into the last 2 bolts of "Welcome" avoiding the thin crux of "Spikes".

name: Covid Haircut
description: Fun climbing on a variety of interesting features with a very distinct thin crux a third of the way up. 9 bolts to anchors.

name: First Born
description: A thin bouldery start right off the ground brings you to a ledge and much easier climbing to the anchors. 5 bolts to anchors.

name: Lust for Life
description: Hard undercling moves leftwards gets you into a shallow, left facing corner. More tricky moves lead to a ledge and anchors. 6 bolts.

name: Millinocket Wedding
description: Climb out the center of the arch into some thin crimping. Grab a rest at a jug then head up into the big white patch for a second thin crux into slightly more moderate terrain to the top. Save a little something for the finishing moves which have a little punch!

name: Mr. Brown
description: Climbs the brown rock on thin holds past 10 bolts to anchors.

name: Mystery Meat
description: Climbs straight up the smooth white face. 6 bolts to anchors

name: Second Born
description: Fun crimping up thin edges from bottom to top. 5 bolts to anchors.

name: Spikes & Twine
description: An epic journey up the left end of the Dike Wall! Tricky climbing up to and through the overhang onto the face above. Fun moves through some basalt blocks leads to endless pulls through smaller and smaller holds to a heartbreaker finish through unfairly thing crimps. 14 bolts to anchors.

name: Super-Spreader
description: Another epic Dike Wall route envisioned and equipped by local legend Pokey Amory! Start up easy ledges for a few clips to get to the business. Multiple boulder problems with less-than-ideal rest stances get's you to the half-way mark at a juggy, undercling flake. From here the climb eases off a fair amount but plan on encountering a few more thin sections including the final moves to the anchors.

name: Welcome to Greenwood City
description: This is the premier route at Bald Bluff and should be on every New England climber's tick list. Fantastic climbing through wild square cut basalt blocks sticking out of the wall. As the blocks dwindle the route gets harder. Rest when you can because the top is thin and pumpy! 14 bolts to an anchor. There's also a two bolt rap station at the 6th clip for those foolish enough to bring a rope shorter than 60 meters or for those looking to just do the 5.9 section through the first 5 bolts. .

name: City Corner
description: Climbs the obvious right facing corner system.

name: Dominatrix
description: Fantastic climbing up clean rock up the right margin of the wall. Lots of exposure!

name: Nate Kimball Project
description: A difficult open project still waiting a free ascent.

name: Star Search
description: Big pulls and long moves. Hard moves right off the ledge lead to a tough mantle onto a small ledge. Climb out the small roof on some easier moves to a final big move to the anchors.

name: Submission
description: Start up "Dominatrix"  then finish up and left. A direct start that begins left of "Dominatrix" is still waiting to be freed (probably 5.13).

name: Blue November
description: Cool lip traverse. Start at low crimp rail and follow jugs, crimps and slopers up the left diagonaling lip of the boulder.

name: Rapture
description: Start in the cave on a great rail at chest height. Big move to sloper rail then up edges to lip and top out. Solid rock. Great holds!

name: Shattered Glass
description: On the same boulder as "Mantle Man" but you start on the right side with a crystal jug and an undercling pinch. Right hand up to sloper left hand out to rail and drop left foot out to water level rail, bring in right hand to sharp micro crimp directly above left hand rail, bump left hand out to square crystal crimp, heel hook pinch start to bump right down to the same rail below micro crimp, drop heel and switch to toe on rail at hips height, move right hand up to obvious side pull, begin standing on right toe and move left to to little tooth below right foots rail, bump right hand up to terrible crimp and bump again for a small but positive crimp about a foot from the lip, reach or jump for lip horn.

name: Sun Drop
description: Start low and move up and left along cool holds to a cool lip and a hard mantle.

name: Birthday pitch
description: The route is located on the large left portion of C Bluff and at the bottom the rock ramps. It is the start to C Monster, which ascends the full height of the bluff, mostly on slab. Extremely good laybacking and jamming make this the longest crack on the bluff so far.  P1: 110’ 5.8+ Start behind some trees and face climb straight up to the ledge at the base of the crack (There should probably be a bolt here). Layback though the wide crack to a good rest. Follow the excellent zig-zagging corner crack to it’s end. From here make a thin face move up to the rap anchor.  A 70m rope will just get you to the ground to the left of the route or continue on an adventure up C Monster.

name: C Legs
description: This sport route climbs the textured face to the right of the large overhang. The second pitch is very enjoyable sustained face climbing which lets up somewhat near the top. The third pitch is not too thin, but proves to be a challenge. The impressive face to the left looks to be hard (5.11/5.12) climbing. The route would typically end after the third pitch, but could easily continue onto the upper slab, completing the full assent.  P1: 80’ 5.8 Start a few feet to the right of the toe of the slab. Find the first bolt at the lip of the first overlap, after that, head for the right hand corner of the massive roof.     P2: 100’ 5.9+ Climb left on the lip of the large overhang and up to a small flake. Move up and left to mantel onto a ledge, then make thin and sustained moves up and right to the bottom of a small right facing corner. Thin moves give way to easier terrain near the bolt anchor.    P3: 90’ 5.11c Gently overhanging strenuous face climbing gives way to easier slab. The steep section seems to be fairly sequence dependent and rather pumpy. Useful features are hard to distinguish amidst all the knobs. Where’s all the chalk?! Rap from the bolt anchor or continue on much easier slab to the top.    P4: 130’? 5.6? Climb through a bulge and onto the upper slabs which can be followed to the top. A tree halfway to the top can be used to rappel. Has yet to be climbed. Looks easy.

name: C Monster
description: This is the first and tallest route at C Bluff. I have climbed the first pitch, but not the full length route. pitch 1, The Birthday pitch, is very enjoyable and will be posted independently. A full accent of C Monster would be pretty adventurous, involving lots of easy, run out face climbing. Check out a well written and lengthy trip report: neclimbs.com/SMF_2/index.ph…    This description was taken directly off the FA topo:    P 1: 5.9; Start - meadow area right of a big overhang. Climb up to a left facing corner/crack system, belay in bushes/overlap 150’    P 2: 5.7; Climb the overlap and up the face, passing rap slings on right, belay at a oak tree. 50’    P 3: 5.8+; move up at the ease in the overlap. face climb straight up then angle left to a tree beneath a steep crack. 60’    P 4: 5.9: Up the crack to a stance then angle left to a corner/crack system, follow this then move right onto the face and up, belay at the anchors. 160’    P 5: 5.7: Face climb up to a ledge then angle left up to a white streak, climb up to a tree system near the top of the wall. 160’

name: C Sick
description: From afar, this area has attractive looking rock on the upper portions. It turns out it is very smooth and slippery with tiny rounded sloping edges, and overlaps with hairpin cracks under them. The first pitch was alright, but the upper sections turned out to pretty tough and scary, so we trended left, ending up in the trees and not taking the proper direct line. A significant bolting effort could result in quite an impressive hard and thin route. C Sick is located on the right half of C Bluff. Approach by walking past C Word for five minutes, crossing directly in front of a large bear cave!    P1: 200ft 5.8 Climb up and left on easy slab for 50ft until you can head into the enjoyable left facing corner that leads to the top of the pillar. Unless you have 7” cams to belay on, face climb up a few feet and scratch around for pro, then make some sort of tenuous move onto a slippery bushy ledge where you can belay on a 0.1 C3 and small bush. Best pitch of the climb.    P2: 100ft 5.10+? We had high hopes for this rock, it’s very fine grained and has features that appeared to be similar to traditional granite. Head through a couple overlaps finding a couple small pieces of pro, trending left until you reach the safety of the trees. If you’re feeling brave, stay on the direct line. This rock would be an interesting hard slab route if it had a bunch of bolts.

name: C Word
description: Varied climbing, extreme exposure and good pro come together in this excellent climb. It is possible to rap from any of the anchors.    P1: 120’ 5.10a Climb over a bulge and into a small right facing corner where a #0.4 can be placed. Easily continue up the slab (2b’s) to the tree ledge. Climb the strenuous and enjoyable offwidth/chimney past 2 bolts (crux) where a slab leads to the bolt anchor.     Variation 5.9 Instead of heading up the offwidth/chimney, climb the left facing corner crack to join C Legs or continue up C Word. Awkward but interesting moves climb through the thin to wide and back to thin crack. Rope drag is an issue when joining back up with C Word.    P2: 100’ 5.11- Clip a bolt off the anchor and climb into the enjoyable left slanting flake. Follow the wildly exposed flake to the end of the foot ledge. Just above and out of reach is a crucial yet bomber #2 placement that protects the final crux moves. Large blocks lead to the bolt anchor. Do not follow the two bolts directly under the finer grained roof, they go nowhere.    P3: 70’ 5.8 An enjoyable slab traverse (2b’s) leads to the bolt anchor of C Legs. From here, either rap or continue onto the easy slab above.

name: The High C's
description: The route is located on the upper left of the bluff, approached from the very steep gully leading left off the rock ramps. A technical start, exposed middle section and a spectacular final pitch more than make up for the steep approach.  P1: 120’ 5.11a  Make strenuous moves off the ground and pull into the left facing corner (crux). Move right and follow easier climbing up the main corner to a stance and a gear anchor (#3, #1, #0.3).  P2: 70’ 5.10b Climb into the excellent overhung corner. Fun stemming and good pro lead to the lip where a small spruce was used for the final move. Continue for 15ft on dirty slab to a tree ledge (bring a sling).  Descend by walking left 100’ to where a short tree rap leads into the steep gully.

name: Block Party
description: First sport route in the Cirque. Located on the main wall (middle ravine), left (south) of Welcome to the Cirque. Five bolts and a double bolt anchor at the top. Steep, like the rest of the routes on the main wall, with not-obvious sequences that would make it a tough on-sight. Good fun.

name: Crimson Thread
description: The crux is about 3/4 to the top with a tough mantle. A good classic crack to off width climb with a few secrets.

name: Diamond in the Rough
description: Follows the shallow groove, straight up the center crack system on the diamond shaped face. Two bolts, good crack pro, and double bolt anchor at the top. Awesome exposure and view of the Carrabbasett Valley, on the climb and from the top.

name: First Kiss
description: Steep crack - fingers to hands to fist, with edges on the face to use.

name: Frenchman's Fury
description: Look for a left facing corner and climb the thinner finger crack inside the corner to a ledge and then up to another ledge and bolt to a crux move to the anchors

name: Judo Chop
description: Around the corner, left of First Kiss, the striking twin crack system on the arete. The first few moves at the base of the climb are much more difficult (hard 5.10) than the rest of the crack climbing above. The alternative, 'Padawan' start, coming in from the left and gaining the cracks above the hard boulder-problem start, makes for a more uniformly difficult and enjoyable 5.8 climb. All gear, plenty of it, with a double bolt anchor at the top.

name: New in Town
description: Excellent edges and jugs with reachy moves at times between them. I recommend using just a carabiner on the first bolt due to the crux being between bolt 1 and 2. 5.10- climbing above this. If you do it let me know what you think for a grade. My guess is 10+

name: Welcome to the Cirque
description: Beautiful, steep crack climbing. Crux is at the boulder problem start.

name: East Side Squeeze
description: An obvious offwidth/squeeze chimney on the east face of the boulder.

name: West Side Pinch
description: Follows a thin crack just to the left of the West Side Squeeze.

name: West Side Squeeze
description: The obvious offwidth/squeeze chimney on the west side of the boulder.

name: Cranberry Hand Crack
description: An iconic splitter crack. Climb the roughly hand-sized crack to a resting ledge 2/3 of the way up. From there, make a few finger crack moves and grab the lip.  Mantle your way up onto the summit of the rock.You can make an anchor at the top by placing stoppers and small cams into the continuation of the crack, which goes all the way across the summit. With a long sling (that hangs over the edge) you can make a good top-rope anchor, and lower off of it.

name: The Four Year War
description: Hard old school arete...

name: Northeast Overhang
description: There were two rusty pitons (one of which got pulled out when I was cleaning the gear), indicating that old school hardmen have probably climbed it before. I found the gear a bit tricky to place, and led it with pre-placed gear. I'm tentatively calling it Northeast Overhang 5.10+. If anyone is aware of a previous free ascent please let me know. youtube.com/watch?v=LpKwMK9…

name: Spud Webb
description: Really easy, really short. If you can do a pull up you can climb this.

name: Home Sick
description: On the east side of the Notch I free soloed the slabs beginning on the right or southern end of them. I followed the diagonal bands of least resistance. The quality of the rock improved after the first slab. There were three distinct slabs. The top slab is the steepest and whitest and best. I remember very sticky rock for the shoes at the top I was thankful for that sure footed foot work to the top. It's an excellent place. I Maximized the distance climbed by diagonalizing the slabs. The vertical height gained is about 600 to 700 feet. I didn't do the last wall to the north capped by a roof.

name: Prangster Dike
description: Free soloing the Eyebrow, about half way up beyond eyesight the moderate (5-6) solid dike becomes a construction project of ripping loose rock off until it will hold body weight. I made the mistake of continuing up it as it became a one way sloping foothold trip without any decent handholds through hell. At this area I came to staring at an old rusted rotted hanger and bolt. Clearly I understood why some other climber had put that bolt in there before going on ahead. It's ridiculous after the bolt, continue removing  crumbling rock out of the dike before stepping up on it. The dike narrows and becomes almost too wide to bridge the chimney. It's a predicament like the posture of Bambi when he fell on the ice. Continue in this manner vertically for I don't remember how many feat(possibly 100+). No footholds, no rest until it stops at the summit of the cliff. How I got up was grace or sheer luck and off I don't remember. I do remember it was desperately bad! That unknown climber and I basically experienced the same intriguing situations. The only difference between us was that he was futilely roped in and belayed up (the bolt is so low to fall at the top a climber will deck it) or he/she retreated from the bolt. Really no way to rate the climb accurately except I'd rate it, avoid it. That is the best rating for this climkb unfortunately.

name: Crystalline Fracture
description: In-between Noah's Ark and the large headwall, look for an obvious finger crack which moves up and right for about 25 feet.  Follow the crack up and over a small roof (5.7).  Once you gain the slab above, work your way up and slightly left to the large tree at the base of a gully and set your anchor.      The name Crystalline Fracture is given because during the first ascent, a protruding piece of quartz slightly bigger than a golf ball was used as a foothold, but after weighting it, broke off causing the climber to lose his footing and bang his shin hard into the rock.  Fortunately, he did not take a fall because the finger crack sports a nice grip.

name: Noah's Ark
description: Pitch 1 (50 Feet):  Start below the left hand side of the huge roof left of the head wall.  Follow the crack up a right facing corner up to the base of the huge roof.     Pitch 2 (80 Feet):  Traverse the arch at the base of the roof 50 feet right, then follow the right facing corner up another 30 feet to the large tree.  This route is one of the more obvious king lines when traversing the base of the cliff.  At the top of the first pitch, we found a solitary rusty iron piton marking the only evidence of any history of technical climbing on the ledges.  After talking to a middle aged local who had lived in the area his whole life and used to hang out around the ledges as a kid, he said that he has never known of any climbing activity on the ledges marking our suspicion that the pin could be a landmark of the 30's or 40's.  Having not discovered any other signs of climbing activity, we are unable to tell if the nailer of the pin traversed the arch right as we did, walked the walkway left to access the upper left part of the wall, or merely bailed.  This historical landmark adds a nice flavor and mystery to the Great Ledges as well as to the history of traditional climbing in New England.

name: Gorilla Traverse
description: Start in the small cave on Jockeys Cap and traverse left until climbing eases. I have not climbed this but I've heard this is one of if not the longest/hardest traverse in New England.

name: Cleavage
description: Sit start with left on jug flake on face, right on jug in crack. Move straight up, roughly paralleling the crack.

name: Jaws
description: This line follows the left edge of the triangular roof on the right end of the boulder, traversing right to the roof's point (where the downhill face meets the uphill face). The holds are comfortable and the moves enjoyable and consistent, which more than make up for the fact that it's a lowball traverse.

name: Just Right
description: A fun eliminate. Start sitting just right of the easy flake route on the southern face on two slopey but good holds. Move up to nasty sloper pockets at 5-6' before hitting a pair of positive edges that lead to better holds above. A v1 variation uses the flake and skips the sloper moves, instead moving from the flake to the edges.

name: Peary Flake
description: Sit start right of the obvious flake on two good slopers. Pull on and move left to the flake. Follow the obvious path of good holds to the lip and figure out the final moves to the top.

name: Standard Overhang
description: Start at the bottom of a right leaning flake.  Climb this to more jugs up and right.  Jugs the whole way to a crux mantle (the top out was covered in ice when I climbed this, so it may be more straight forward than I thought)

name: Ships Prow
description: Sit start the steep prow on beautiful Maine schist.

name: Spiritual Traverse
description: Sit start from the flake in the cave on the left end of the boulder, move up and work your way across the boulder, finishing past “Ships Prow”.

name: Crystal Face
description: Obvious and fun route

name: "Peary Face" Left & Right
description: These are the two climbs # 5 and #6 on the sketch/topo.    Locate the anchors on the low-angle slab and rap 30 feet to the lower anchor. Lead or top rope the climbs.  Both are about 5.6-5.7

name: "Peary Gates" Left & Right
description: These are the climbs # 3 and #4 on the sketch topo.     Approach from the top on the low angle slab. Locate the rap anchor and rap down to the lower Rap anchor 40-45 ft below.     Lead or Top Rope the two climbs.  The climb on the left is a bit more difficult (5.8- ?) than the one on the right (5.7)

name: Barge Variation
description: This is the climb that starts at the very "toe" of the cliff.  #2 of the sketch/topo    P1 - Scramble up to an arete and crack, climb through this and exit right. Protect for the followers, and then continue on the very easy slab to the double bolt anchor of "Peary Gates"  120 ft 5.5 - 5.6

name: Great White
description: Start just to the right of Mako Roof, climb straight up through the roofs to an anchor. 4 bolts

name: Hammerhead
description: The obvious line of big horizontals under the right side of the roof capping the southern face's right end. Be prepared to go big!

name: Mako Roof
description: Mako roof makes its way up though some steep blocky features before making a throw for a horizontal beneath a large roof.  A very pumpy hand traverse leads to a somewhat desperate clip and a V3+ boulder problem to establish on the large flake.  Clip the 3rd bolt and go up about 6-10 feet of much lower angle rock and clip the anchor.  An extension could easily be added to this route as the steep slab continues up another 20 meters of so.  While there aren't any showstopper moves on this, the boulder problem is pretty powerful and it comes right at the end of a very pumpy traverse and the long throw to the horizontal.  If you have the traverse and clip dialed this may feel soft in the grade, but the onsight may feel stiff.  The rock quality is superb with good friction but not sharp.

name: The Puff Fish
description: Start on the Mako Roof, but after clipping the natural thread and first bolt go directly out the horizontal roof to a lip encounter boulder problem crux.

name: Standard Crack
description: This the first, very obvious hand crack on the left hand side of the cliff.

name: Sycamore
description: Boulder through the bulges, then move left to the last bolt of Great White. Finish at the anchors of that route.

name: Top Rope Area
description: This is the area of easy climbs to the left of the Standard Crack Route (and to the right of where the trail goes onto the slab)

name: The Breath of Life
description: Climb the slopy traverse to the left of Fuga.  Lowball.

name: Fuga
description: At the far right end of the cliff line this amazing but short problem awaits... Orginally done by Dave Sharratt from the obvious crimpers and later done from the lower flake to complete the full line by Morgan Patterson. The crux is the first move to the crimps and then the throw to stick the the sloping edge. Great movement!

name: left of left
description: Big face small tree  left of tree

name: Frostsaber
description: Start under the arete and go left/up and ninja the face using some very small crimps. This has probably been done before but it deserves a name.

name: King's Cub
description: At the edge of the upper bouldering field just below the drop off into the valley there sits an amazing boulder made of schist and granite. On the SW side climb the overhanging arete, starting under the bulge on slopers and amazing crimpers.

name: Roaring Lion
description: Climb the slightly over hanging face, starting on double undercling crimpers. Fire for a decent hold then to the top. Short but strenuous.

name: Climb or Die
description: Climb the slab by (5-6) face holds to the ceiling complex. At this complex ceiling are two ceilings one bigger and one smaller. The smaller ceiling is a step onto it's roof. Utilize a thumb under cling pocket dynamically into becoming an index finger lay back by finger/thumb doing a pinching jam. Steep no other hold to get stabilized legs. Then reach to crimp holds better ascending. I moved to the right to escape the larger last ceiling left. Onto a tree ramp that goes to the top in a round about way. This has likely been climbed or top roped because I found slings on a tree at the ramp. The climb has no trad protection and would have had to been climbed like I climbed it without protection. I got stuck doing this crux because of a sudden rain storm. In seconds the only place dry was under these the ceilings. Only one place to go for me was get up it. Complicated manipulation of this only hold for the right arm. Do or die situation soloing sometimes. I kept my thoughtfulness to movement together. Panic is falling instead climbing ahead is being out of it. So much felt in so little time. I felt out of it caught by a rain storm. The climb has decent ceilings. The highest ceiling could be climbable. The slab is clean grey rock with many sloping hand and foot holds.

name: The Slide
description: This is the obvious diagonal ramp system that splits the cliff in two. Mostly tree-protected steep hiking/scrambling with a few exposed moments with serious consequences. The Slide is used to access the top of the cliff face and also provides access to some of the climbing on the Left Wall.

name: 3 Climbs Left of "The Trunk"
description: There are at least 3 climbs on the wall left of "The Trunk's" arete: (L to R)    Two Trees Crack (5.9 trad)   Spillway (5.10b, sport, 7 bolts)    Runnel  (5.8 Trad)

name: Bubblecuffer
description: A superb short climb.     This awesome climb is the right most bolted line at the Family wall, working it's way up a slight overhang then topping out at some trees.

name: Chocolate Moose
description: From left, third bolted climb. Climb a delicate slab (3 bolts) passing to the right of the pine tree edge (bolt) and continuing up to a small overhang. Pull over the overhang (bolt) and climb the face above (2 bolts) to the top.

name: Flake Route
description: START - About 30-40 ft from where the approach trail meets the cliff, Below the obvious left-facing corner/flake that is about 20 ft up. [photo]    P1 - Climb up to the corner/flake, step left at the top (bolt seems to have replaced the old pin) and up to the large pine tree ledge. Move up the slab on the right (bolt) to the right-leaning crack. Up this (crux maybe 5.7+?, bolt, optional nut placements) to the top.  Belay off trees.  100 ft  5.7 / 5.7+

name: Four Routes to the Right of Slab
description: There are four routes located to the right of Bubblecuffer.  The usual approach is to walk right of Bubblecuffer about 30-40 ft, then cut back left-and-up to a dirt ledge.  1) Justin's Ascent 5.9 climbs the face to an anchor.  The climb is left of the large, wide, dirty corner crack (This climb MAY(?) actually start on the far right of the main slab and then traverse onto the face.) 2) Coyote Crack 5.7 -  the large, wide, dirty crack in the corner  3) Bullwinkle 5.8 - Climbs a corner in the left wall of the Arete to an overhang (2 Bolts), then finishes on the arete.  4) Schools Out  5.2 - Climb the arete past 2 bolts to the old tree anchor.  [NOTE: This climb currently (2018) seems to be mis-named as Bullwinkle.

name: Moose Du Jour
description: Start a few feet right of the large blocks of "The Trunk" and climb up to a right-leaning flake.  Up the flake, step left at its top. Make interesting foot moves left (bolt) and up to a ledge.  Move right on the obvious crack (piton, nut or TCU a foot beyond) then up at the end (May be the crux for shorter climbers) and left to a good ledge.      Perplexing moves past 2 bolts (crux...5.9+?) lead to the anchors.  80-90 ft  5.9 / 5.9+? Final move may also be crux for shorter climbers.

name: Moose's Leap
description: START- 30-40 ft right of The Flake, just before where the base starts to rise into a gully/corner. There are two climbs that start here: "Mica Slab" (5.10d) which moves left; and Moose's Leap which moves right on a line of horizontal jugs.     P1 - Climb up 15 ft to the horizontals, move right around the shallow bulge ( shorter climbers may find this the crux??) and then follow the line of bolts upwards. (total of 7 B's)      I, personally, found the crux to be up where a dike-like, horizontal intrusion made for a great handhold(s); but others found an easier way to do this and felt it was "5.7" ! I thought the sequence I used was 5.9+ / 5.10a.    100 ft,  5.9  7 B's

name: Mr. Moose's Wild Ride
description: This route was named after a Moose's bones were found at the base of it. At times the run outs may make you feel like you're about to join the moose.    There are only 3 bolts the whole way, and the rare spot for a very creative trad gear placement, making the climbing of this route a hair raising adventure for those that dislike runouts.

name: School's Out
description: An extremely easy and moderate outing. At the extreme right end of the Family Wall there is an obvious low angle slab that will take you to the top. Awhile ago someone slapped some bolts in to give an extra sense of security.     Fun to blast up to the top, with a good view, though not especially recommended.

name: The Trunk
description: Furthest left on the "front wall" of Family Crag. Scramble up large blocks, pass a 4" diameter birch tree good spot to belay)  and then climb the cracks and flakes just right of the arete, to the top. 80-90 ft, 5.5-5.6 Anchors for "Moose Du Jour" are to your right.

name: Captain Dinghy
description: Wicked pissah route. Good steep rock with jugs right where you want them. The crux seems to be at 3/4 height.   Start on the top of a pointed block next to the clean grey face and make an easy first clip. Head straight up for a few bolts then trend right toward a foot wide ramp/flake with a beautiful finger crack protected by 2 bolts. At right end of ramp head straight up passing bulges on jugs to a 2 bolt anchor with chains.

name: Lone Pine
description: Step off the small horn, clipping the first bolt and making a large move to a good jug. Continue up the bolt line, clipping 6 total bolts. Step left into a right running ramp and as the difficulty eases off, continue up, placing small gear (.3-.4, tricams useful) and continue up the face, ending at a short, slightly overhanging handcrack to a tree anchor. Rap cord replaced 8/2020. 70m needed if rapping off.

name: Science Project
description: Fun well protected climbing on clean steep rock. Moderate start with 1st bolt at about 15', crux at 8th bolt (a little swing if you blow it). Cool quartz crystals (which make good holds thank you) nearing the anchors.

name: Blast Furnace
description: Sit start with hardly any feet and small crimps and move straight up gently overhanging face on small holds.

name: The Civilian
description: Sit start on a flat ledge and move up to a sloper and then up the arête.

name: Search Warrant
description: Sit start as for the problem Blast Furnace but instead of moving straight up move right to the arête and then up.

name: Case Study
description: Sit start on crimps and a high foot. Move up to a sloper and top out.

name: Honorable Discharge
description: Sit start the steepness with marginal feet and small holds. The key is a really low right side pull and a left heel. Move up and top out. An easier V3- version starts further right using obvious good flat holds.

name: Badass
description: Sit start roughly in the center of the 30 foot long wall and move up and right to a crux at about the ten foot level and make a slopey top out avoiding the small tree. Pumpy and cool.

name: Elbow Grease
description: Low sit start on the steep bulge. A heel can be useful.

name: Another Day In Paradise ?
description: Sit-start on a bomber side pull, hit a sweet pocket, jam your foot in the side pull and go for the top!  For full grade value use only the holds to the right of the split in the boulder.

name: Arete Problem ?
description: Nice clean moderate arete with a technical crux at the beginning.  Start down to the right on the arete feature, and work up and left until good smears can be had on the arete itself.  Try not to fall on the topout.

name: Cross Cut
description: About 20 ft to the left of the arete boulder is a boulder which has a clean triangular shaped slightly overhainging face.  Sitstart the bottom right side of the face, and use the featured lip of the face to gain the top of the boulder.

name: Moosehead on Tap
description: Sit start on two great but painful finger pockets.  Getting your weight above your feet is the crux.  Top out on a cool triangular hold and small flake/side pull.  An excellent problem for warmup laps.

name: Pumpkin Head
description: A boulder problem characterized by one of the best underclings that I have ever utilized.  Bump the right hand up from a sloping edge to intermediate holds, then match on a small jug and pull up for the topout.   Sit start.

name: Super Sloper
description: Start on a excellent left facing side pull then throw for a sloping hold above lip, or use intermediate holds to gain lip.  Work your feet up and use another sloper to top out.

name: Detached flake/pillar
description: 5.9 climbing on either side of the flake(sharp). my guess is follow the weakness or cracks off to the right after toping out the flake...

name: Magalloway
description: A full length sport climb on top of a full length trad climb. Climb steep blocks to a right facing layback crack. Exit the crack to bolts trending left through excellent quartz face climbing. A long and varied pitch.

name: Pang
description: A great mixed line! scramble up cracks to a ledge. Gear protects up to the first bolt. Layback and balance up cracks and grooves to a techy sequence at the last bolt.

name: Static Free
description: Technical, small right facing corner. Boulder up to first bolt, mantel onto a ledge, friction climb up to the second clip. Find the stance to place a blue and black alien nest before rocking out left to the third bolt. Reachy moves to a finger crack (optional .5), crank over and onto the ledge above with good holds heading up and left to a two bolt anchor.

name: Wide crack
description: good looking wide crack right of detached flake/pillar.

name: Bemis
description: Climb the clean looking arete past 7 bolts.  A hold on the top-out recently broke and significantly increases the difficulty of the last move.  The end can be bypassed by moving far right to the finish of Winter is Coming.

name: Ghost
description: Climb under a roof to the obvious, straight, hand crack.  Originally rated 5.9+ it is probably harder by today's standards.  Although relatively short, there are no options for rest, so the climb is strenuous.  However, it zippers up very well.

name: Winter is Coming
description: Climb the finger crack system just right of Bemis.    Zippers up well with small cams and nuts.  Orginially rated 5.8.  The grade, however, is form the old days and the climb is probably closer to 5.9+ by modern standards.

name: Bakers Passage
description: Three pitch sport climb Which feels more like a trad climb. (whatever, does that even mean?)Straight up the guts of the cliff, following the quartz vein for two pitches. Great belays!The third pitch being the crux in an open corner with granite trickery (good luck shorties). Sling long at the top of the corner (sixth bolt) before ledge traversing left fifteen feet. Climb the exposed prow to the highest point of the cliff. My suggestion is the leader clips the chains and gets lowered down past the belayer to the rappel station below. MUST have a 70 meter rope!On the second rappel to the ground, stay to the right over the slabs.Which means pushing off before losing contact with the rock midway through the lower off.

name: Contortionism
description: Unexplainable! Think twister (the game)

name: Conundrum
description: Crowning the top of the central wall is a short but airy white slab that hangs 150ft above the deck, split by a thin seam. What the pitch lacks in length, it makes up for in thin, technical slab climbing in a kick ass location... Plus the excitement of doing it on lead. The gear is there, just be sure to place it well!

name: Entrance Crack
description: Climb the striking hand/fist crack under a dihedral to reach the belay ledge.  There are bolts for anchor/rap at the belay.  The crux is the finish, moving under the bulky dihedral with small under-clings and lay-backs, using friction on the smooth face to gain sloppers at the lip of the ledge.  A really fun climb bottom to top!  Protects very well.

name: Kennebago
description: Make bouldery moves to gain slab face with a diagonal, horizontal seam.  Six bolts and small cams.  Tops out at same ledge as Plumbago.

name: Plumbago
description: Climb the featured buttress, right of a vertical quartz vein, trending right past three bolts to belay ledge.  Get ready for an exciting first clip (or bring a stick clip.)  Gear is okay but gets worse as the climb progresses.  Route is steeper than it looks from the ground and despite its blocky appearance is pumpier than expected as well.  There are two small roofs to climb past on the route, the first is just below the first bolt (and first option for pro) about 15 feet up.  Holds tend to be not as positive as expected and a bit slopey in places.  Options for gear decrease as the climb progresses making for an exciting finish.  There are bolts for anchoring at the top of pillar.

name: Punch It
description: An awesome variation to “Stem It”! After a small tree was extracted and a crusty layer of lichen removed, a splitter fingertip crack was uncovered up the left corner of the Stem It feature. Start at the base of stem it, but instead of climbing up the mossy, fern filled right corner, start up the obvious, clean splitter to your left. Balancey opening moves lead to fierce, thin finger locks. The crux starts where the finger crack seams out for a couple feet. If you are tall, pull hard and reach up to the awesome locks above. If you are not tall.... you are just gunna have to be a little more creative and/or rugged. Stop for gear if you are warming up on 12s, consider gunning for the big ledge if you aren't. The gear is great! Finish on stem it. Wicked fun climb bobby.

name: Stem It
description: Climb the double corner system with some cracks and wild stems.  A climb reminiscent of the chimney's at Devil's Tower, WY.  Definitely a fully body experience.  Very dirty at the moment and needs considerable cleaning.

name: The Tenth Degree
description: The Tenth Degree is this crag's signature line.  Although it sees very little traffic, the Tenth Degree is easily one of Maine's best, multi-pitch routes of it's size.  With more publicity and traffic to help clean it up the route will, no doubt, become a destination line for New England climbers.         The Tenth Degree is the obvious, four pitch crack/corner system that runs straight up the cliff's center to it's highest point.  Pitches two and three are the routes real gems.  Although it is likely that no individual move on either pitch is harder than 5.9, the sustained and burly character of both pitches puts them each in the 5.10 realm.  This is one of those climbs that the leader, who will be placing gear under stress, lacking solid stances, will probably find to be a grade harder than the second, who will get the luxury of humming along, enjoying the fine movements on TR.       Pitch One (5.8):  Technically, the route starts right at the base, where the Wavy Wall and Main Wall meet to make a 90 degree corner.  However, the first pitch is almost always wet, overgrown, and blocky.  You can bypass pitch one by doing any route that gets you to the top of the Wavy Wall and then do a short traverse into pitch two.  A good, moderate (but slabby and scary) option to get around pitch one is Wavelength.    If you climb the original pitch one then build a trad anchor on top of the block below the big, corner crack.  If you bypass pitch one via accessing the top of the Wavy Wall, there are three, old pins at the far left corner.           Pitch Two (5.10a):  Climb the blocks to access the off-width corner.  You can stem, using both sides of the buttress for the first four or five moves before the left side vanishes away and the routes turns into a lay-back.  Once you mantle up to a shelf above the corner take a good rest, finish up and left about 20 more feet, over a block to a nice belay shelf and a set of bolted anchors.  If you bring two #3's and two #4's the lay-back corner stitches-up well.  If not, be ready to jog your 4.      Pitch Three (5.10a):  Continue up the obvious corner right off the belay shelf.  The first bolt is a bit far off the deck but the corner will take a #2 about 10 feet up that will protect you while you access the first bolt.  Clipping stances are strenuous and the right wall is lacking good feet.  A #4 protects the mantle move above the pin.  Look up and right, behind the small bush, as you attempt the mantle or you'll wonder how the hell getting onto the slabby shelf is possible.  Once on the slabby shelf traverse left about ten feet, past two bolts, to a new set of bolted anchors.      Pitch Four (5.10c/d):  Pitch Four has a couple options.  The 5.10d options starts right at the anchors; climb the obvious, left trending finger crack into the blocky roof that is about 12 feet off the shelf.  You can bypass this option, making life a little easier, by starting left of the anchors and climbing a dirty ramp that takes you to the top of the blocky roof and is protected by an old bolt.  Either way, above the blocky roof climb on quartz and granite square cut holds until you can access a bolt below the second roof with a v-notch.  Up and over the v-notch roof, and over another block, to a slab and the summit anchors.     Route can be descended in two raps with a 70m rope.  Three to four raps with a 60m rope.   A WORD OF CAUTION:  The top of pitch four, about 20 feet from the anchors, goes over a blocky roof with a sharp edge that could present some real, potential, rope-integrity issues for the second.  I highly suggest mitigating this risk by going into this climb with a fatter rope that has a nice, hardy sheath or by having the leader extend their personal anchor system down to the edge in order to pad it for the belay.  If you do not have a nice, fat, rope or the leader does not have the technical skills to extend down and protect the edge, then I highly suggest calling it quits at the top of pitch three and rappel from there.

name: Wave Length
description: A mix of slab and face climbing on the long, low-angle, blunt arete that makes up the top edge of the wavy wall where it borders the start of the friction wall. Protects well on mixed gear. Belay from the trees at the top of the ledge. Dries quickly after a rain storm.

name: Wavy Gravy
description: Balancy climbing on very interesting rock. Harder than it looks but very well protected. Climb past 3 bolts to anchor. The long runout between the second and third bolts protects well with a .5 cam.

name: Big Dipper
description: Climb the arete, inside the alcove, past three bolts to a horizontal crack.

name: Brown Crack
description: Fingers and hand jambs.  Crack is often wet.

name: Chimney Sweep
description: Blocky start leads to a narrow chimney with a crack in the back, climb the chimney for 30 feet and exit up and left.

name: The Craggle
description: Climb the arete to a crack system.

name: Hey Hey, My My
description: Start in the short, dirty, spider-infested chimney just right of the Big Dipper. Climb the chimney to gain a right trending cracks. Follow cracks to a blocky finish. This climb can easily be top roped off trees.

name: Iron Born
description: Fingers and hands that joins the Brown Crack.

name: On the Tweak Again
description: A great sport climb on the far, left arete of the Military Wall.

name: Singalong
description: An excellent, well protected crack.  Fingers and hands.

name: Afternoon Nap
description: Located on slab on the right side of the Shady Wall.   Start high, move up crack, move left (friction), crack becomes corner, zig zag to the top.

name: Charlieville
description: Climb the overhanging wall/corner to thin, steep lay back crack.  One bolt near the top.

name: The Growth of the Soil
description: Make bouldery moves under small roof to gain flake that joins obvious hand crack.  It's a big start, to access the first holds it may be necessary to step up on a cairn at the base.  The climb is short but strenuous, despite its appearance of being low-angle from the ground, the route does not let up until your reach a shelf at the top of the crack.

name: Illegal Alien
description: Start on a vertical crack to the left of a horizontal crack, make balancy and slightly committing moves to the horizontal crack and place a cam, then move up clipping two pitons. Continue to a small roof, move up along a thin crack on the right end of the roof and then traverse to another vertical crack on somewhat thin crimps. Continue up on good edges, clip 1 piton, save some juice for a slight runout to the finishing jugs.

name: Illegal Alien
description: A blind alien placement (yellow or green size) in the horizontal at the start

name: Dickweed
description: Editor's NOTE- When Tumbledown was broken into sub-areas  I had to guess as to the location of this climb. It's a total guess, but the description seems to closely match Dog Leg Corner 5.7 ** on Dorsal Fin, so I put it there. R Hall Admin. Maine    "Begin beneath 20ft outside corner. The crux is getting onto it's edge. The edge leads a climber up to a long (5-5) slab."

name: The Finger Peeler
description: Bolted route just to the left of Orange Peel Wall. Not the best rock quality (a bit dirty also, seems rarely climbed). Work your way through a sequence of small roofs with nice and sometimes cryptic movements. Unfortunately I broke off a jug near the 4th bolt while working on the route, but it shouldn't change the grade of the climb.

name: Orange Peel Wall
description: Start on juggy holds in an orange dike that quickly turns into sloping, flaring cracks, with lots of good side pulls for lay back moves. The crux (just below the roof) is very difficult to protect (on a lead attempt I whipped from the crux, ripped out two cams and almost decked). If you get through the crux, good jugs and knee bar rest await at the roof, followed by an easy top out.

name: The Red Letter
