description: Really fun, easy climbing.  I thought the starting crack was probably the crux, but there's no real show-stopper move on the climb.  Once you come over the bulge and the angle eases off, it's probably no harder than 5.3/5.4 to the anchor.

name: Dickheads
description: Beautiful sustained finger crack up the west side of the central amphitheater crags. Slight draw back is in the fall, leaves accumulate on some of it's footholds. Climber may need to do some excavating with a nut pick to get leaves out of the way for stopper placements. If the climb had traffic it wouldn't be like this.

name: Fork N'Hell
description: Start in the middle of the Amphitheater; there are two crack systems (on either side of a groove) that will take gear.  The left variation is marginally more difficult and slippery (from moss).  Climb to a stance/ledge just below where two upper cracks split in different directions.  Follow the right crack that has an undercling move (or two), and finish on a slab covered with pine needles.

name: No Mistake
description: The Handren guide has this sharing the first 50 feet with Thin Air.  If you want to keep the difficulty more consistent, there is now a line of bolts slightly left of Thin Air that meet up with the second part of this route.  The bolts are mostly standard bolts and hangers, but the first bolt has an interesting homemade hanger.  It seemed perfectly fine, though.So, either start at the bolt line slightly left of Thin Air (maybe 5.9?) or at the Thin Air starting crack (this start has no bolts, bring gear).  When you reach the left arching crack, use the scoops to move up and right of the Thin Air line, clipping a couple of bolts as you go.  Now, trend left onto and up the arete.  I would consider this the crux.  Finish by making a beeline for the Thin Air anchor.   *note: the bolts to the left of the Thin Air start are not in the photos in the Handren guide.  I would guess they were added after to give No Mistake it's own start.  If anyone knows the details, feel free to add.

name: Thin Air
description: Climb straight up a nice crack to the pine tree (optional belay).  From there, follow an arching leftward crack.  For me, the crux was transitioning from the top of the crack to the face and crack climbing of the headwall.  Pleasant face and crack climbing to a bolted anchor.If you have a 60m rope, you will not be able to be lowered back to the ground.  We used a 70m and barely made it with stretch.  There is an optional belay/rappel station set on the tree directly above the starting crack to get down with a 60.  Knot the ends of your rope and be safe.NOTE-There is a COMMENT in the AREA ( 2nd Tier) for this route that the top anchor bolts are seriously lose. and suggest using a tree for belay and walking to Wander Wall’s anchor. RHall Admin.

name: Wander Wall
description: Begin about 15' right of Thin Air at the base of another clean streak. Follow discontinuous cracks through bulges up and slightly left, finishing on a line a bit right of No Mistake's faint upper arete.A 70m should barely make it down with stretch (knot the ends!) but is likely insufficient to lower without cleaning your gear. With a 60 you'll need to use the tree anchor about 30' up Thin Air (a little left of the rap line).

name: Red Acted
description: 15' up go right (3" gear). Angle right up blocky crack to ledge with pine tree at 30'. Climb up behind the tree and trend right to gain a crack at a tiny triangle roof visible from the ledge. Follow the crack that soaks up nuts for 60' to where it fades. Angle up and right to the tree anchor shared with Broken Sling.

name: Shylocks
description: Balancy and slabby moves tick-tack up a faint crack, eventually leading to a challenging sequence  fifteen feet off the deck and your first opportunity for substantial gear.  As the route progresses, another short series of fingery moves gets to easier climbing and the sloping top-out.    Though short, this route is sustained and somewhat cryptic.  Bring nerves of steel--you'll need 'em!

name: Bear Den
description: Start at the cave and move onto the arete.  run it out to the two bolt rap anchor.  Further continue up to a wall on the right.  put in a backed up cam or two at the base of the wall and send directly to easier terrain.  not for the faint of heart but good

name: Bear Hug
description: The beginning of the climb you’ll see a pine tree about 20 feet up the initial 20 feet will be a scramble using passive protection on the slab aiming for a under cling Once reaching the under clean you will be able to back up #.75 with a #.2 moving out left with your feet high under cling the ramp and reach out with your left hand to a good hold  you can place a #1 cam move up the crack system you can place #.1 cam before making a delicate move to another roof  at the small roof clip a bolt and figure out the Boulder move 5.10B then clip the next bolt and make a heady finish to the slings at a bonsai tree

name: Bear season
description: Start at the base of a large oak move up a slab to gain a good crack some grass grows on a ledge but it is not wet move into the crack and follow the large fist jam to the overlap.  The thin crack above Takes you to another overlap and into a deep jam you must make the overlap with a high left foot 5.8 and two crimps on a slab to reach the mid station anchor the next pitch stays in the corner to the right and protection is placed in the crack  eventually veer toward the large pine tree in the middle of the cliff you can belay from the tree and use the rappel anchor for dolomite duet nearby

name: Bear Stare
description: 30 feet down from the Bear Den start is a big wall to a big over lap look for bolts.  make hard face moves protecting a finger jam into the overlap to (3)bolts and step left around the overlap onto the face above.  follow the crack system trending up and right to the mid anchor station above Bear Season.  or escape left to anchors for Dolomite Duet.

name: Dolomite Duet
description: Begin the two pitch climb at a cave and move right onto the face making moves on horizontal cracks until you can place gear in the hand cracks moving up to the anchors about 40 feet the next pitch begins on a flake to the first of five bolts If you climb the left side of the bolts it is much harder at 5.10 if you climb the right side the grade stays 5.7 above you can use a variety of gear and bolts to reach the anchor on a ledge

name: rock paper plastic
description: There is a really good selection of boulder routes I cleaned a couple hundred feet up the trail to Bear Cub cliff providing a great warm up to the early morning.

name: Center Face
description: Climbs like a woody problem. Start on an OK crimp and worse sidepull below it. Move out left to a better crimp and fire up to the slopey rail above. Match and top out via the weakness at the top of the boulder.A sit start on the juggy rail below and to the left of the start holds looks doable but would add multiple V grades.

name: Left Arete
description: Decent arete climb up the edge of the overhanging face of the boulder. Start on the slopey holds around the corner, climb up the arete and top out. Top may be mossy.

name: Railroad
description: Start at the right end of the prominent rail which runs along most of the boulder, and follow it right until it ends at the weakness in the rock.

name: The Anvil
description: This striking overhanging arete on the NE corner of the rock is the true king line of the boulder. Interesting holds, varied movement, and a little spice at the top add up to a great climb at the grade. Start sitting with your left hand on a good rail and right on a crimp on the arete. Pinch and slap your way up the blunt edge with the help of crimps on the face until you hit a good jug slot below the nose of the overhanging prow. Make your way up and left, climbing out of the overhang and onto the headwall. Top out at the end of the arete.

name: Left Crack
description: Splitter left-leaning finger crack, with good feet and hands sometimes available. Felt like a 5.10 finger crack when using finger locks the whole way. This climb is also lead as a short trad route, as there is a nasty rock in the landing zone for a lot of the climbing.

name: Northwest Arete
description: Great easy climbing up a perfectly sculpted schist arete. Stand start low and layback the arete to the top.

name: Right Crack
description: Good vertical handcrack. There is a rock in the way of the landing for much of the route so it is also lead as a trad route. May have a mossy topout.

name: TDMFP
description: A good test of balance and finger strength, climbing on small holds up the vertical face. Start standing with your left hand on a crimp and right hand on a good sidepull at the bottom of the incipient crack. Make your way up to the horizontal crack near the top of the boulder, then follow it right and top out at the top of the arete.

name: A.M.C. Route
description: This climb is on the wide west side, outside ramp ridge, next to the central depression, and is away from the rock slides that have radically changed the appearance of the right side, the red wall ledges. I posted this route, and I haven't done it. I believed I had, until photos were posted. The A.M.C is a classic route, and far better than what I climbed, the left ridge, far left of the red section.

name: A.M.C. Route Variation
description: A really nice route at an extraordinary scenic location. Three long pitches of mostly face climbing along cracks and flakes.  P1. Climb left crack, veering right through a weakness with a vertical crack. Continue along the face, passing flakes and some bushes, veering slightly right all the way to a two bolt anchor on a nice tree ledge. 170' 5.6  Optionally climb the committing right crack to the same weakness. This was originally put as the main option, but using the left crack is more natural for the grade and route. 170' 5.7R  P2. Continue straight up the exciting face along more cracks and flakes to another two bolt anchor, just below a big tree filled ledge. 140' 5.6+ PG13  Scramble up 20' to tree ledge and belay here for the next pitch.  P3. Climb the crack filled face and then follow just right of the exposed arete, passing a big ledge and continue up all the way to a nice ledge with a tree belay. 150' 5.4  From here you can scramble to the top of the west summit and enjoy the views!! A trail leads to the Loop Tr and back out.  Note: This cliff can get windy and pay attention to loose rocks.

name: Central Groove
description: I wandered up to the central eastern section depression. At a junction, I veered left, way below the ceiling, of the recent rock slide. Entered the groove, and 100 feet up, to the ridge. I stayed on the outside of ridge to the woods. Then went west to find the trail. It is difficult to describe how, I climbed the Great Ledges, I was there once.  Oddly I did a difficult boulder problem in the talus field, that I have the most recollection of difficulty, than on the entire ascent. I do remember I didn't want to repeat it without a rope.

name: Lakeview Arete
description: Joe reports nice climbing on good rock with trad pro where you need it.2 pitches, rap with a single 70m see photo [ Disclaimer- I haven’t climbed this route, I put it in at the request of Joe Cormier. R Hall ]

name: North Peak Western Slab
description: Move right under ceiling until there is a break in the ceiling. Go through break at (5-5) and climb the easier slab right or left. I did the slab both sides. the climbing was slightly different. Don't recall trad pro pockets but I wasn't looking for it. Clean and beautiful rock climbing and over 100ft of easy slab.

name: Western Edge of East Peak.
description: Begin and stay on the western edge all the way to the summit. Climbing cracks, face holds, mantles and lay backs. Lots of fun climbing on a broken up buttress.

name: Bad Strong
description: Did this route back in the early 2000's... It climbs an arete of a block down low in the boulder field. Anyone got any more info?

name: Genie Baboo
description: Twitchell pond classic, Start left hand undercling and right hand on the low right jug seam just beyond the arete.

name: Genie Baboo Lip Traverse
description: From the amazing undercling left of Genie Baboo, follow a left leaning arete/lip to the very top of the boulder. A small seam tracks this arete and peters out 2/3rds of the way up. Figure something out and then make a crux reach to a jug! Good boulder!V5- might be a generous grade but you tell me.

name: Margin Walker
description: Start matched on the obvious lip-pinch-hold with right heel hook. Progress through the hard rail of sloopers (similar to Numb Thumb, but harder)

name: Project
description: Start matched on low left jug and work up the right leaning arete.

name: Project 2
description: The crux is perching on the low underclings and working upper the overhanging belly.

name: Slab
description: Finding the holds when the slab see slow traffic is the crux.

name: Swamp Butt
description: Start sitting on block to the left of Swamp Thing. Start right hand side pull and left hand on low corner, and follow a line of sloopers to jugs with a reachy finish.

name: Swamp Thing
description: Start low left matched in the seam, stacking hands (alternate beta using right hand 3' over). Crux is the first two moves to a friendly just often dirty top out right with a mantle on seam. Some may choose to climb reachier moves as a direct top out which has been cleaned summer 2011.

name: Toss the Muffin
description: Start on obvious rail at chest height, smear feet and fire up right to a nice gaston. Continue to a fun top out straight up.

name: V2 Arete
description: Start low sitting on the arete. Climb with left hand on arete and right hand on face holds.

name: Xhosa
description: Start sitting with in the middle of the face, left hand good crimp, right hand smaller crimp. Climb with left hand on arete and right hand on various face crimps to a big right hand move to a slopping pinch. Easy topout left exit. (optional slopper start left goes at about the same grade)

name: Just keep swimming
description: Sit start, with a slopey-sidepull and two finger pocket. Move up along the corner of the slab (first two moves can be quite sharp). Jam for a crack and get feet up to go for a good jug and easy topout.

name: Ain't Nothin' but a Tree Thang
description: Start out on good holds with slabby feet. Work up easy moves into the obvious hand crack. Continue over two small 'trees', top out up and left. Basic crack climbing skills make this a fairly easy but fun route. Can be done as a top rope or high-ball boulder.To the right of Sea Legs, and Slabcrack

name: Behind the old spike
description: Start on the obvious shelf and work your way up and right to a jug. See photo.  ** make sure you take a good look at holds on this wall before climbing as there are many that might blow off on you.

name: Bonsai
description: The climb leads directly up the ladder of drilled monos.  A fall leads directly to the hospital.

name: Box Traverse
description: A short but fun problem with great holds. Start with right hand sidepull and left hand on the edge with good feet, then climb to the top by bumping the right hand followed by swinging the left to the crimp above. Nice easy move to the nice edge on top. Either climb for a short V0 or continue by traversing to a far decent hold for a little extra challenge. A high right foot makes it easy to get a right hand over, followed by a high left foot to match with the left hand. Bump the right hand over around the corner to the top without swinging and look for a nice right foot along the corner. Mantle and top out.

name: Eaten Alive
description: The crux is getting out of the cave.   Sit start for the full tick....try not to be Eaten Alive!

name: Edging
description: A short but awesome climb! Starts with a left hand on the low crimpy rail, a right on the nice jutting edge, a left in the low crack, and a right heel up on the right ledge. Quick left hand move to the next crimp above then match. Bring the left foot up a little to a solid spot and shoot for the  top with whatever hand feels comfortable. Pull up with good feet and top out.

name: fancy toes
description: Ascend the right trending seam. Sit start to the right of the pine tree. Right hand on the obvious hold. left hand low in the seam. Good luck finding the feet that work for you. Short, powerful. awkward. fun.

name: Lady Slippers
description: Start left of the crack. Undercling the left face, delicate foot traverse to lyback. Get to the top.  **Don't use the tree**

name: Magic Bean
description: Starts right of the crack.   Easy slab climbing to a foot rail and then the real challenge begins.  Look for the magic bean!

name: Murder Rocks
description: Quality sequence with a committing top out. Start in the center on a lyback, hit the jug above and move left on to crimpy sidepulls, then straight up to top out. Super fun!  Located off of the green trail deeper in the park. This hidden climb is easy to miss.  The window of climbable days is also small. There needs to be about 2-3 days of dry weather for the landing to be bearable. Water pools below climb on wet days.

name: The Peace Stem
description: This climb is harder than it looks. Slippery slab climbing with some potential to stem the left facing rock.   Thins out up top. For extra challenge only use the slab... just don't fall. The landing zone isn't great.  V1 if  using both rock faces V2+ if only using slab

name: The Pinnacle
description: Rock quality is the crux right now. Some flakey rock will sluff off as more climb this beautiful solitary boulder.   Pure V-easy fun

name: Red Stripe
description: Named after the bottle of Red Stripe found at the base of the problem.  Short, 3-move problem.  Start on the lower stable flake, move up and get a heel hook to top out.  I would check the integrity of the flake before committing.

name: Rock Slug
description: Cool start. Foot on furthest rock. Hand on low outcrop.

name: Sound the Alarm
description: Start up the north face arete of the Pinnacle.   Balance moves and some fun liebacking to the top.

name: Spinal Flake
description: Creepy Flake makes it fun.

name: Stand and deliver
description: Sit start the obvious holds. Stand on the flake and fire for the top.

name: Starfish
description: A fun overlooked problem. Sit start the obvious holds. The crux is topping out with marginal feet. A fall from the top would be unfortunate.

name: Tetanus
description: For the full difficulty do not use the diagonal crack on the left.  Using drilled monos and the arete only crank this otherwise straight forward line to a challenging paddle problem.

name: Two in the Stink (project)
description: Start on juggy side pull to the left and wide pinch to the right. Transition to line of drilled monos to the left, then use small crimps to a slopey top out.PG13 because of a small boulder located in the fall line when you get further to the left.Didn't get to finish due to rain, and I'm not local,  but would love to see it go.

name: Unamed
description: start low on the left edge and move up with a couple hard moves.

name: Unamed
description: Just climb it

name: Very Unnecessary
description: Start at the bottom of rock wall. Traverse uphill and finish back on the ground.

name: High Heels
description: Start high on the good slopers, and work up and to the left to top out with the ball.

name: I'm Lichen It
description: Climbing the left arete. A good warm up with good holds.

name: Mosquito Mob
description: Very Short Problem that is only doable in the winter when the marsh below it is frozen. Start on the good underlings, and grab the right arete then heel hook the left and huck for the left hand pinch, and then finish out up and on the slab.

name: Mozzie Slab
description: Easy slab that climbs on the left side of Mosquito Mob up the arete and good crimps.

name: Blunt
description: Climbs the blunt arete to the right and up above the hueco cave. Start with hands spanned across the arete and bump and slap your way up.

name: Blunt Traverse
description: Start the same as for Strong Jonhs Blunt but instead of finishing on Blunt keep traversing across the arete to the left eventually gaining good holds to the right of Skelletor. A tricky right hand cross move gets you around the arete.

name: Skelletor
description: Start way back in the cave the same as for Skull Cap. Climb out the right side of the roof through some tricky layback moves.

name: Skull Cap
description: Start as far back as you want in the small cave/roof and climb out close to the lip and trend out left a little. Climb out of the roof on really cool two and three finger pockets. Really good. Perfect for the grade.

name: Strong Johns Blunt
description: Sit start on the uphill side of the boulder on bad slopers with feet way underneath the boulder. Slap bad slopers to the left across the arete and join Blunt. Joining Blunt is the crux. Finish on Blunt.

name: Desperation
description: This problem climbs a short face to the left of Superman. A large horzontal crack splits the face. Start on the left side of the crack with bad underlclings and bad feet. Make one hard move to a good hold above and top it out.

name: John's Arete
description: Climbs the right arete of the Superman Boulder via one difficult move. Pull onto the arete and work your way up. The hard move is the second one. After that there are some really good holds.

name: Pulse
description: Sit start at an attractive, juggy ledge with a hand-heel match just to the right of Shorty. Make a tough reach to another great jug then scrape up to the top.

name: Superman
description: Start on a juggy arete and traverse it to the right. After you keep going right you will come to a small seam. Figure out how to get through the seam (crux) by heelhooking the arete, bumping, crossing, and maybe controlling a swing depending on your beta. There are many ways to do this section. After you get through the seam there are jugs up and right and then jugs up and left after that. Finish with an easy topout. This is a really awesome problem that is worth going to do if you are close by with nothing else to do.

name: Superman Direct (Project)
description: The direct start to Superman. Sit start below the large overhanging wall at a low shelf. Work up the arete and into the seam of Superman.

name: Breakers
description: Begin on a large undercling hold to the right of The Wave. Pull up to the layback crack above, get a high foot and mantle strait up.

name: Power Traverse
description: Begin crouching at two good holds on the left of the overhanging face. Traverse right across the opening holds of The Wave. Stay below the lip by doing a difficult gaston move into the layback crack/flake of Breakers (crux). Finish up on Breakers.

name: Salty
description: A hard sloping traverse that is really friction dependent. Start low on the arete on the far right side of the boulder. Traverse the arete to the left using really bad slippery slopers. Gain marginal holds farther left on the arete and top out to the right of Breakers.

name: The Wave
description: Begin at good crimps in the middle of the dark face. Pull up to good slopers above the overhang and finish with a tricky mantle. Really good.

name: Crabapple Breakdown Project
description: Overhanging project that follows a very slopey lip to the sketchiest top out since the war of 1812. very sharp slopers and haggard crimps. Still a project but possibly a v5-7 depending on the beta. The Top out is incredibly sketchy and is probably the crux.

name: Grown Ocean
description: Not actually on the Cornerstone boulder, but on the boulder that's behind the route "Rugosa/Yunker". Climb up the clean-ish crack ann arete on the left corner of the slab opposite the Cornerstone boulder. Sit start isn't too hard and makes for a better route.

name: Heaven
description: Heaven climbs the very obvious and aesthetic southwest corner of the Cornerstone. After a crimpy and sharp start, the climbing eases up considerably with a tall, slightly balancy, but very fun finish. This was the very first problem put up here, requiring quite a lot of cleaning. It was done in a pre-pad era so it was TR-ed first, then soloed. With modern pads, a ground-up ascent is pretty reasonable

name: The Loaf
description: The crux is reaching the glued pocket and finishing the problem.

name: Purgatory
description: Start siting under roof, left hand side pull and right hand crimp. The crux is getting over the buldge and getting all the weight onto your feet.

name: Rugosa
description: Rugosa tackles the arete just left of the Loaf, starting low and moving up on very rough slopers and crimps.

name: Sub Zero
description: The crux is at the top when the holds thin out. You might find yourself one crystal in each hand, sub zero temps help.

name: Against the Grain
description: ATG climbs the clean section on the back of the Lodestone, starting with a small flake and heading up into the moss and ferns. Despite the appearance the climbing is good

name: Aretile Dysfunction
description: IMPORTANT! This route is incredibly obvious and has more than likely been done before (looking at you P. Beal)So if this has been done, notify me and I will change this details. Thanks!   Starting on the obvious flake undercling with the left hand and another good undercling about hip height around the arete, pull up on good feet and slap your way up the arete until you can make a lunge for a good crimp up high. After a bit of a flora heavy top out, take a moment to enjoy the view from the top before scrambling back down to high five your crew.

name: Diamond Bollocks
description: Risky venture as you gain higher hands on smaller holds.

name: Clear the Deck
description: This is a fun problem heading up to the obvious shelf via a flake

name: Lower Lower Arete Problem
description: Start on ok slopers and work up the arete until you can reach out left to the obvious jugs. Top out as for Clear the Deck.

name: Mantle Problem
description: Climb up on short backside on obvious holds, mantle over lip

name: Santa's Little Helper
description: Start with left hand & foot on underside of boulder (obvious chalk), right on sidepull.  Move left to big hold on corner, the up and right to sharp sidepull, then to the top on bad holds.

name: Bart
description: Same beginning as Lisa, at corner jug continue left on sharp holds to Marge, then Homer.  Top out same as Homer

name: Homer
description: Sit start at obvious holds on left-most side of boulder.  Move up and left on big gym-size holds

name: Lisa
description: Start on undercling, move left on decent hands to jug at corner, then up

name: Marge
description: Sit start about 5' right of Homer.  Head straight up.  On top out there's a nice hold high and left on top

name: Problem A
description: Sit start with hands on large right facing side-pull.   Move up passed a right hand sloper and a small left crimp to gain holds at the break.    Continue direct to finish.

name: Vulcan
description: Start matched hand in vertical low left corner. Move up right through sloper and eventually right hand Vulcan grip and left hand slooper, continue straight up.

name: Vulcan left
description: Start hands matched in low right corner and climb left, making a reach up left to a shelf and top out with a nice right side pull and whale mantel. (avoid seperate boulder to the left)

name: Blade Runner
description: start to the right as far as you can go before the drop into the water, sit start & work your way around the arrete along the little roof and around the corner where you pull to a mantle top out..a pumpy route that has an awesome finger jam. The crux lies on the roof as you have to fall into an over head matched crimp

name: Borderline
description: This route is found south of the lighthouse at the property line of the park.(note the fence post at the top in the pictures) It’s not a super hard wall to Free Climb but the pitch and height definitely get the blood flowing good!null

name: Flake Out
description: Sit Start is mandatory for this given its short length.  This short but satisfying route has 3-4 moves that follows the flake on a boulder with a slight over hang. The crux is the second move, getting setup on the flake that stands out on the boulder to the right of Web Crawler.    Sticking to just this boulder, the crack is a satisfying mix of face climbing and lay back.

name: piece 0-cake
description: fun little boulder just around the corner from blade runner.low start in the middle most crack. let you figure it out from there. lots of fun crash pad recomend. the tide shouldn't be a problem low tide recommend.

name: Web Crawler
description: This climb starts at the edge, overlooking the water, and in a small crevass.  It has some consequence if you fell, given that you would tumble out onto a terrible fall onto sharp rocks.    The reason this is even notable, is that it is so much fun, and a great selection of various holds and cracks, and a sustained climb of about 10-14 feet.

name: Little Wing
description: This problem is long, very funy, hossy, involves a heel hook or two, and is located on the Spoonman boulder. Start at right side of the lowest part of the boulder on the little, flat shelf where a coffe mug would rest perfectly. Climb left out and under the small roof to a huge flat ledge and then begin the crux sequence. top out on the obvious block.

name: Cat Pine Crack
description: Sit start with hand on the jugs and bad feet.  Work your way up the jugs and crack topping out on the slab.  Hand jams make it much easier.  There is a much harder super low start.

name: Cat Pine Dyno
description: Start with a sit start low and work up to small crimps.  Then explode upward dynoing to the jug.

name: Belly Button Arete
description: Sit start with dismal feet and your hand on a jug and head up the nice holds of the arete to top out.  Avoid the block to the side for the feet (using that or stand start makes it v0).

name: The Coffin
description: Slap your way out the prow on this compression problem.

name: Groop Prooject
description: Stand start on a wide sloping hold at the lip, then traverse right into the crack to top out. Stay above the lip on the good rock and avoid stepping underneath as these holds are crumbly (and the low feet reduce the difficulty & quality of movement). Use high heel hooks instead.

name: Warm Up Slab
description: There area  number of variations up the easy slab on the far back of the Coffin boulder that make nice quick warm ups to get the blood flowing. If you turn around there are much better, much higher slab/vert easy problems that can feel a little spicy for warm ups.

name: Biker Slingshot
description: Starts on a semi-incut crack, follow the decent crimps straight up and finally top out left.

name: Daddy Longlegs
description: Traverse right on the massive jug with platform feet and then follow up right using the same topout as biker slingshot. Easy cruising with a mildly difficult topout.

name: House Party
description: Sit start on a sloping left hand side pull and a sharp very slightly in cut right hand. Slap big to the lip and then top out directly above. The rock that is separated by dirt is not on for feet.

name: Blood on the Leaves
description: Start sitting, RH on sidepull flake, LH on good edge. Climb straight up on technical compression moves to an easy topout.Block/outcropping that is detached from the wall on the left is off (makes more sense in person).

name: The Completely Sweet Finger Crack
description: Start as for Lost in the World but break immediately right up a small finger crack.Needs a little more cleaning, will likely be easier if you move out further to grab the arete on the right.

name: Lost in the World
description: Sit start on outcropping and climb up easy crack.

name: No Church in the Wild
description: Start as for So Appalled but move right, traversing on small feat and good holds, toping out on a jug crack.Small, detached block off for feet. Exiting straight up after the first long move to the seam is probably a grade easier.

name: Slightly Appalled
description: Climb the right side of the arete using the vertical crack on the right

name: So Appalled
description: Stand start with RH undercling and LH on whatever keeps you on the wall, block is on for feet. Move straight up to slopey bulge, and make a hard pop to a crimp. Sneak under the brush after a somewhat tenuous topout.

name: Unnamed V1
description: Start on RH triangular crimp and a LH edge nearby. Climb straight up to a slightly dirty topout.

name: Nucular
description: Anyone know the FA or route name?    Short route with some easy crack and face climbing   Crux could be transitioning from ledge to the face or last move to top out

name: Another Day
description: Sit start the flake at the left end of the wall, keep left of the crack. Top out rightwards.

name: Disappearing in the Wood
description: Classic of the crag. Sit start on the jugs, then take a fiendish right hand crimp, left foot heel hook; hold the tension to reach a flake.

name: Maggie of the Cave
description: Sit start with feet at the back of the cave and climb straight up to another tricky top. A left variation goes into the top out of Slow Mover.

name: Oyster Crimp
description: Sit Start at a the base of a crack toward the left end of the wall at an oyster shell-like crimp, and head right on interesting sidepulls. Left variation goes left of the crack, V4.

name: Pasta
description: The left hand crack, directly below the tree. Sit start on the blocky intrusion, and top out as for Slow Mover

name: Poetry and Porridge
description: Sit Start as for Disappearing In The Wood, but move left on small crimps to an eventual jug.

name: Rage, Rage
description: Right to Left traverse. Sit Start at the cave, traverse left to a rest then go low for some upside down moves. Hit the wobbly flake on "Another Day" and top out.

name: Slow Mover
description: The right hand crack in the centre of the wall. Sit start at  the crack. Easiest is to go right to a good crimp, then back left.

name: Stick A Flake In Me
description: The flake to the right of the cave at the right end of the wall. Tricky top-out. Sit start with feet at the back of the Cave is around V3.

name: Suburban Evening
description: Sit start at a couple of poor crimps left of the cave, top out as for Slow Mover. Difficulty may depend on the thickness of your crash pad.

name: Write You
description: Sit start on a thin crimp near the left end of the wall. Use a right heel hook to gain improving crimps, then lunge for the top.

name: Cut-back
description: Sit start. Work your way up the corner side pull feature and top out.

name: Death Wave
description: A short overhanging face up a sidepull to some pockets with an easy top out.

name: Grommet
description: Sit start. Work your way up the blocky jugs to top out.

name: Walling Up
description: Sit start on sidepulls, pinch, crimp and top out.

name: Silverfin
description: Sit start with good hand holds and ok feet and make a few moves on jugs up the perfect arete.

name: Head For Higher Ground
description: Start under the overhanging face and climb along the obvious flake. Follow the flake until you reach the vertical seam, follow the seam up and mantle. Route was named for dam sirens going off during the first ascent. Flake has reportedly broken off.

name: Maybus
description: Maybus climbs the arete on the backside of the boulder which faces the bank of the river. Low but challenging.

name: Moxie Madness
description: Stand start on the hanging arete on the south side of the boulder. Fire up the arete with marginal foot holds.

name: Static Shock
description: This problem starts to the right of the Head For Higher Ground finish on the slopy edge and pulls a hard mantle move over the lip and topout. 1 move wonder.

name: Warmups
description: Located on the southern side of the boulder are one or two short warm ups.

name: A Dramatic Situation
description: Super fun!!  Classic anywhere, the best line at Pemaquid.    I attempted to enter this as a 5.10 boulder problem, MP wouldn't let me.   Hard to designate on the V-scale as it feels like a 5.10 solo.      Situational climbing at it's finest!  Park  at the restaurant and walk left along the ocean 1/4 mile (10 min), the rock will gain height.  A Dramatic Situation follows a flake/ horizontal rightward for 10' until it is possible to mantle up.  The rock cuts away as you traverse to the right, truly exciting at high tide!!  Climbers not solid at the grade shouldn't attempt this problem.    Thought about  naming this Tarter Sauce, which is what you'd be if you fell.

name: Loose Lips
description: Very nice roof with cool features. crux is turning the lip.

name: Ode to Europe
description: Sit start on a left side of a striking white boulder, just up the coast from loose lips.

name: Sinking Ships
description: Start low, make big move to lip. Once you pull over the first lip you are done.

name: Baby Aurora's Baby Arete
description: The tiny, attractive arete

name: The Barrel
description: Sit Start on a block at the back of the ledge and climb via a good incut crimp, then a quartz tooth at the top.

name: Big Groove
description: The open groove with a crux at the top.

name: Feel Cheerful
description: Right line on the overhanging face. Sit start with a heel hook, then follow holds leftwards below the ferns to top out as for Martha Stewart's Sofa Monolith.

name: The Guillotine
description: Sit start, then climb direct to top out via the hanging boulder.

name: Martha Stewart's Sofa Monolith
description: Left line on the overhanging face, just off the trail. Sit start on crimps and launch to the lip.

name: Moss Icing
description: The overlapping layers of granite and moss.

name: Noah's Arete
description: The next short wall to the right. Start on the left, and slink round to the right.

name: Overlook Wall
description: The best lump of granite at Tracy Shore. The lines all merge into each other, so it's best to make up your own.

name: To Scotland
description: Blunt arete to the right of the ferns. Move right to groove to top out.

name: Various Aretes
description: Round to the right there is a series of aretes protruding from the moss.

name: Wall with ferns
description: Short wall with ferns

name: The Garden
description: Starts off straight forward with a crack you can sink some fingers into, but then requires moving left as the ground falls away making it a highball. Ends moving up into some serious lichen and moss.

name: Jacob's Ladder
description: An easy juggy ladder up to the top of the hill. Looks like a log with steps cut into it, set into a crack.

name: Supaman
description: On a nice very slightly overhanging oval face, some stuff to pinch leads to cool top out.

name: Variations on a Theme
description: A left facing corner that's slightly overhanging cracks and flakes with a lot of jugs. It all starts the same but as you get higher you have a few different choices for ending, with the choices getting harder from left to right. Really fun, but watch out for loose rock.

name: Cat Scratch Fever
description: Walk around the corner from the landing at Dyce's head and take in the improbable overhang of rock. Appreciate the sandstone-esque features of pancakes and chicken heads. Then reach up and break off a piece of the choss.    This route starts from a sit start and works out the massive crack that splits the roof, then ascends it for the unsettling top out.    The rock is sharp, and brittle and only accessible at low tide.

name: Elephant Boulder
description: This is a large egg shaped boulder out in the sand at low tide in the Backshore area of Castine.  From the road you walk to your right along the beach at low tide, its the only time you can access the boulder.  I used to boulder here back in 78'-82' and the boulder has some decent problems on large crystal type holds.  Something to check out if you are looking for some bouldering.  My memory is its the only boulder out there on the beach so its location is obvious.

name: Project 2 (the easy one)
description: A mildly overhanging wall of terrible crumbling rock, you follow the small arete up the white rock streak, trending left for challenging face climbing, begin with a sit start.    watch your fall zone for the sharp boulder pointed at your back.

name: Doin' Great Sweaty
description: Easy to get to, and easy to climb. This route is characterized by big jugs and huge ledges for feet. Should be an easy climb for beginners. The start can be made harder or easier by a couple feet left or right, the overhang gets more significant the further left you walk. The crux is the last move before the anchor, a big reach up and right to a flake projecting from the formation on the climber's right.

name: Rope Drag
description: If you take the overhanging bit at the beginning, this is probably a 5.7.If you take the staircase to the southern side of this route, it is a 5.4.The overhang is the crux by far, everything else is quite easy. The route is typified by the wall, with good protection using a range of small to medium cams and/or nuts. I only used cams.

name: Seams Easy
description: Sit Start with right hand in jug and left hand at same level. Make one move up and left then straight up following the seam.

name: Seems Right
description: Sit Start matched in jug, make a move up and right to rails then continue straight up.

name: Africa
description: Sit start right of Lowbie Lightning

name: Breaking Right
description: Stand start arête left of Half Way Prince, lat="44.58503" lon="-69.886152"

name: Buzzkill
description: Sit around the corner left from Powerhead, finish same as Powerhead.

name: CTTB
description: Sit start at left edge of cave lip with hand in big crack, traverse right to same topout as SCTTB

name: Fierce Feline
description: overhanging arete on the backside of the mountain. it had a flat mantle top out in  no fall zone.

name: Halfway Prince
description: Sit start center of overhanging face on layback. Straight up to break.

name: Jester
description: Start under right side of the overhang and work up.

name: Lowbie Lightning
description: Sit start with high hands, move through small edge and up.

name: Old Iron Flake
description: Start on the rust colored flake leaning against the Under Prince Boulder.  Climb the sharp edge as high as you can, then mantel over.

name: Powerhead
description: Sit Start on right side of face with left hand in the undercling, follow arete to topout

name: SCTTB
description: Sit start in back of cave, follow crack system to lip then move right to mantle out.

name: Seams Easier
description: Left side of the prince and up one level. Sit Start edges and follow to highest point for topout.

name: Serenading Bird
description: Sit start on right side of overhanging face with left in undercling and right hand high, follow seam left until you can mantle and reach left facing hold.

name: Splitz
description: Sit start in middle of three boulder stacked on top of each other, below the split of the two higher boulder. straight up.

name: Timber Pig Slide
description: Start in the bottom of hole on back side of prince with both hands on the stalactite. Make it to exit without dabbing, then mantle out.

name: TimTom
description: roof problem that started matching on undercling flake. reached out a roof to a sloper. get a toe hook and match on the lip.and mantle up. also had kind of a sketchy top out

name: the Arete boulder
description: Nice egg shaped boulder that needs to be cleaned.

name: The Finger Crack
description: The finger crack on the left of the outcrop on the Sanders Hill loop trail.

name: The Hand Crack
description: Splitter hand crack - highball boulder problem that needs to be cleaned and climbed.

name: The Mantle Boulder
description: Another nice boulder problem near the Outcrop.  Nice overhanging mantle onto mossy sloper.

name: Right side
description: Right side of the Outcrop

name: The Snapper
description: The Snapper Arete - stand on the Snapper's mouth and reach for the top.

name: Free the Proletariate
description: "Political Economy regards the proletarian ... like a horse, he must receive enough to enable him to work. It does not consider him, during the time when he is not working, as a human being. It leaves this to criminal law, doctors, religion, statistical tables, politics, and the beadle."   -Marx, Wages of Labour (1844)

name: Running Through the Six
description: Granite window sills, brick side pulls, visible from public walkways for maximum confusion of the average Joe. Keep feet on one of the two granite block horizontal buttresses. Best if linked "With My Woes" by finessing around the corner.

name: Thickly Winking
description: Start is the lower windowsill, going left to grab the next brick edge. Stand up on a high right foot to top out on the high window ledge.

name: What Happened to Shawn Kingston?
description: Lowball sit start, tsssaah, high foot, lay back, hit the jug, peak in the window, victory whipper

name: With My Woes
description: Starting from the corner/the finish of "Running Through the Six," "With My Woes" continues towards climbers right. Make a delicate move from the corner to the next sill using a mono pocket (tssssssaah) at head hight. The majority of the route offers a great view into the lecture of the day in Hedge 104. When you reach the bike rack, make a move similar to the start with more spice and less mono pocket.

name: Ride the Lightning
description: Climb from the flat roof up the downward facing slats and then mantle over the lip. Either rap or down climb to escape.     As soon as you stand up off the ground, you're visible, so make it quick!

name: "On Target"
description: This route is on the left side of the building if you are outside looking towards the front.  Wall kick/jump start up to the metal beam laying across some pillars and then proceed to the intermediate roof.  From here, wall kick to the top, or improvise your way to the top using some partner techniques.  DOWNCLIMB.

name: Super Wal-Mart
description: The first move is the crux.  This route is slightly different than most in the area due to it's somewhat challenging jump start.  There are cameras literally directly to the side of the top of climb, who knows who, or if anyone is watching them.  Wall kick up to the black pipe, easy climbing after the first couple moves.  Downclimb your way back to the Earth after enjoying watching people come and go from the front of the store.  Don't get spotted!!!

name: Thomas Hill Standpipe
description: Climb 360 degrees around the building on the granite foundation.  More of an endurance boulder problem then anything technically difficult.

name: Bell's IGA
description: Go to the back of the IGA building.  Look for the large metal staircase.  Once you're on top of the stairs, use the hinges/doorknob and railing to ascend the additional 6 ' to the actual roof.  Easy, and short.      NOTE:  It would be possible to go from the backside of the railing and jump to a cat-grab on the wall next to the stairs.  This has not been done yet.

name: Hannafords
description: Best if done at night.  Downclimb the route to get down.  Start in front of the young men's christian association.  Pick a flag pole and climb it.  Run right and jump for an angled steel beam.  Use this beam to reach either of the two edges above the beams and then mantel.  Beware of pipes laying approx. five inches above the ground on the roof.  Travers across the roof towards the roof for Hannafords.

name: Alopecia
description: On the SE Corner of the Coal Chute boulder follow the path of least resistance up. Sloping holds. Cleaned as a descent route, but provided a moderate challenge due to wet rock and freshly cleaned lichen. The route is typically used as the designated downclimb for this boulder.

name: Bosley's - Open?
description: Follow the NW Corner / Arete to the top. Still needs cleaning

name: MPB (Male Pattern Baldness) - Open
description: Still needs some cleaning. Super wet when I tried. Hard steep moves off the ground to thin flake holds lead to a positive high jug. Pull the jug with a heel hook and top out on sloping ground. Tricky feet

name: Trichotillomania - Open?
description: Very thin moves on suspect flakey holds steep and sustained all the way to the topout. Descend via Alopecia

name: Afternoon Delight
description: Start on a flat ledge and move up an obvious right leaning crack. Jam and lyback around a roof (crux). Continue to an obvious dike edit.

name: Captain Hook
description: SS, start on obvious features above the low overhang.  Work up and right on a series of rails to top-out.

name: The Dangle of Doom
description: Start left, use the lip of the roof to traverse right, mantle top-out.

name: Dynot
description: Meant to be a dyno problem until more thorough cleaning revealed face features.  Start on the rail and move straight up to a shelf and top-out.

name: The Long Trail
description: Start way left on a low roof.  Traverse right, heel hooking and hand matching to reach an obvious hand crack around the corner.  Use hand crack to top-out.

name: The Mallard Sweater Controversy
description: Start on undercut rail, move left matching feet until you reach the rail.  Use LH on arete and RH on left facing dishes to top out around corner, same top out as White Belt.

name: Photo Opportunity
description: Traverse the lip of the dog bone looking boulder lodged between two walls.

name: Stop!  You're Under Arete!
description: Sit start all the way left.  Climb the right and upward trending arete to top out.

name: Take it on the Nose
description: Start with RH on deep, horizontal crack at shoulder level and LH on nose.  Move left using features on slab-face or heel hook around left edge.Big reach to a dish around left of the nose, mantle on to bridge of the nose for the top-out.

name: The Tale of the Lost Mountaineer
description: Start in the corner of the overhang. Move right on rail, heel hooking to gain crimps on face.  Continue to move right and up to top out.

name: White Belt
description: SS around corner, left of "The Mallard Sweater Controversy."  Climb obvious features to the top-out.

name: Barkimedes
description: Runs up the left side of the blocks and fins.    It's easy, chunky, and aesthetic. Very obvious to find.

name: The Coffin
description: Hard. Big reaches, tough body positions.    Start inside with a sit start, work your way out the long way, and pull the roof.

name: High Fly Drive By
description: An upward slanting crack that moves left.    Delicate footwork marks the top out. Make sure you have plenty of pads.

name: Why I oughta (open project)
description: On the climber's right downslope side of the massive boulder in the middle of the scree field, you'll find this fun arete problem.     Begins with a sit start underneath the boulder, then you have to clamber out and up.     2 cruxes, the start then the top out. Easy climbing between.     Super fun. Quality.

name: Zac Attack
description: Super fun, but with a tricky landing zone.    Sit start, and pull out. Getting up the bottom of the face is the crux.     Top out is sort of a highball, but easy.

name: Alternative Magnetics
description: Cool little mini compressive roof. Start under the roof on a good right sloper edge and and decent left hand edge.

name: Firp Fight
description: Big flake in the middle of the wall. Good feet and hands to 20', bouldering lay back to mantle top out with a great view. A good stable tree at the top to rap from.

name: The "Diamond Area"
description: There are a few climbs in this "Area" which may serve to entertain on days when climbing to the higher elevations is questionable due to weather.     See photos and sketch diagrams for routes.

name: American Beauty
description: 1. Start at the base of the big corner and climb finger and hand cracks on the right wall to a small overhang. Belay on a sloping stance just above. 5.7-, 120'.    2. Continue up the corner a short way to an obvious rightward finger traverse into a clean, vertical crack. Follow this (about 80' of 4-5" crack) to a belay alcove. 5.7, 130'.    3. Climb the broken ridge, mostly easy but with a couple of short 5.7 sections, until it's obvious to unrope and scramble up to the Knife Edge. 5.7-, 150'.

name: The Armadillo
description: The Armadillo has just about everything you could hope for in an alpine climb: Chimney climbing, face climbing, crack climbing, ridge climbing, big time exposure, solitude on the route mixed with gawking, awed filled hikers at the top.This route climbs at least 6 pitches of the huge pyramid and ridge in the middle of the south basin to the rim of the mountain, 10 minutes from Baxter Peak.   Expect to get an early start and plan for a long day. The rangers will inspect your gear and require you to bring a #4 camalot, or equivalent cam. You'll need to fill out an itinerary form and leave the camp by 8 am.  The approach is long, and somewhat sketchy. Rock hop around the right side of Chimney pond until you come to the stream bed on the south side (back.) Follow the stream bed (which will have a lot of water after rain) south to the headwall of the basin, at the waterfall which makes up the start of the Ciley Barber route in winter. Skirt the waterfall on the left (in the trees without a rope or via some easy but technical climbing through the rock band.) Cross the stream at another headwall and follow loose wet slabs and vegetation up and to the right until you can access a narrow vegetated ledge which will lead left to the start of the climb. There is a chock stone blocking convenient access on this ledge, which can easily be passed, however it is very exposed and roping up before this point is safe and convenient. Build an anchor below and to the right of the small flake with a pin. Plan for at least 2 hours on the approach but it may take you 3.  Pitch 1, the chimney: From the vegetated ledge clip an old pin on your left and boulder up to the next ledge system, move left to the base of the huge detached flake. Stem, jam and wedge you way up the chimney behind the flake to the second comfortable ledge, about 2/3 of the way up the big flake. (5.5)  Pitch 2, the face: Climb on the fat arete of the flake for about 20 feet (protection can easily be found in the hand crack on the right.) Move left just below an old pin (when you run out of comfortable feet) onto the face of the flake for some very exposed face climbing to the top of the flake. (5.7 PG)  Pitch 3, the bad ass crack: Climb straight up the splitter crack. It starts as big hands and is easily protected with a #3 cam (keep sliding it up with you if you only have one.) Quickly pass a chock stone (red TCU) and climb up to the Bong. Dump the #3 as the crack turns into fist and more and start to protect with a #4 cam (again, slide it up with you if you only have one.) 30 feet or so above the bong the crack widens to 6 inches for a few feet. Soon the climbing eases up and protection can be had with a #9 and #10 nut as well as a #2 cam a little higher. At the top of the crack belay with gear in the 1.5 in range behind a solid flake at a comfortable ledge. Be careful of the loose rock at the top of this pitch. (5.7) WooHoo!  Pitch 4, the corners: From here the quality of climbing changes character. Access a ledge 15 feet above the crack and make progress through a few short dihedrals to the left separated easy climbing and rest ledges. Belay just below the crest of the ridge, or the spine of the Armadillo. Again, be careful of the loose rock. (5.5)  Pitches 5 and 6, the ridge: Climb the ridge to the top, which is basically 4th class hiking with a few 5th class moves. Be careful as most of the rocks are pretty loose. Many people simulclimb the last two pitches.  From the junction of the Armadillo with the knife edge trail you can hike to the summit (Baxter Peak) if you go right (northwest) and then down the Cathedral or Saddle trail. The Saddle trail is much nicer to hike down with your rack and rope in your pack. You can also go left and cross the knife edge and Pamola four/Chimney Peak and then down the Dudley trail.

name: Baron's Direct
description: With a pretty short and simple approach, manageable loose rock and short simple crux sections Baron's Direct offers a good  intro to Katahdin climbing. The climbing is quick with good belay ledges. As always route finding was  somewhat of an issue, but when in doubt just climb the better quality looking rock. The route can be done in far fewer pitches  with some easy soloing or simul climbing applied on the upper ridge.   Located just left of Pamola 4 Baron's Direct follows the major buttress eventually connecting to the ridge line.    Pitch 1-3   Head up the path of least resistance through the slabs on pretty easy rock. We eventually passed two pitons before trending right to the krummholz. 5.3-5.5    Bush wack and wade through the krummholz for a few hundred feet to gain the meat of the route.    Pitches 4-5   Pitch 4 starts on the center of the buttress following a right facing corner for 90' eventually ending on a ledge. Keep heading up the most prominent crack  system passing a mangy piton under a somewhat precarious block    then up a short wide crack  to another great ledge. 120' 5.7      Pitch 6   Aim for the center crack climbing a short lay back section ending on another good belay ledge. 100' 5.7    Pitch 7    The money pitch. Climb up the  right on a short horizontal crack before heading straight up. Look ahead and jam up the splitter crack. Belay from a good ledge just above. 150' 5.7    Continue up the ridge for another 500' through mostly 4th class terrain and short sections of 5.4.

name: The Chimney
description: 1 pitch of about 5.6 R (You REALLY don't want to get hirt up here!) getting past THE chockstone, with several "pitches" of class 3/4 that leads directly to the notch between Pamola Peak and Chimney Peak. I climbed this way back in 1966 or 1967, but hesitated to put it in to Mountainproject because telephoto pictures I took from near Baxter Peak (across the basin) in 2015 just didn't look right. I had remembered traversing directly below the huge first chockstone (like maybe I even had to duck in places) and making one or three "sketchy" 5.5 (old school) moves to get around its left side. The 2015photo(s) I took looked like there was nothing under the chockstone.Both observations have been confirmed by a recent report on the climb by Robert O'Brian who reported in an e-mail :"I climbed it as a high school student (’72) and remember it the same as you… now we climbed about 60-70 feet down hill from the chockstone itself… I think something washed out the gully. " His description of the 2019 climb is as follows: A very short technical climb (perhaps 80 ft) with a fair distance bushwack approach and regular short (10-50 ft) class 4 going around chockstones 2-4. We also had to 4th class the small 20 ft headwall beneath the first chockstone. Conditions were wet, but the rock was good and not slimy. The crux is on left side of the 1st chockstone, and had a 20 foot vertical bit that is very well protected (including fixed nut) up to 15 feet, but poorly thereafter (5.6R at the top of the crack, before the angle eases off). You can stem (hard) or wide hand/foot crack (easier) the first 20 feet. The remainder is a long, gradual rising horizontal crack system with vegetation and loose choss (beware to belayer) which meets with the upper left side of the chockstone itself. This upper crack protects poorly and offers both the leader and second a ground fall. 5.6 seems right. 4th class is inappropriate (5.6 solo is still 5.6). Based on the beta from many websites and BSP, it seems like the route is rarely climbed in summer.

name: Flatiron
description: Approach same way as the Armadillo, then breakout right to the first grassy tier, take the traverse to the large slab that forms a cave.    P1: Head up diagonally left through finger crack and off width section, belay whenever convenient.   P2: Jam up awesome hand/fist/finger crack and pull small over lap. Belay wherever convenient then head up to ridge.

name: Memorial Buttress
description: This route climbs the semi-independent buttress left of the Armadillo (left of the ice climb The Primitives), joining the Armadillo very near the top. It's a bit scrappy but has one breathtaking pitch.    1. Follow not-very-obvious cracks, mostly trending a bit right. (5.6)    2. More indistinct cracks and grooves lead up to the base of a short, steep headwall. (5.5) It might be possible to combine the first two pitches. In 1982, old manila slings were found here.    3. Instead of climbing the short headwall, crane your neck out right and find the horizontal hand crack traversing out over the void on perfect rock. Follow this crack until it ends and you can pull up into an offwidth-chimney; belay in a niche a short distance above. (5.7)    4. The rest of the climb is mostly low fifth class up the ridge crest, but unlike most of the other ridge finishes in the South Basin, it has numerous short, exposed technical cruxes where a rope will be much appreciated. Unrope where this ridge meets the main Armadillo ridge.

name: Pamola 5.0
description: We think we might have climbed a new route on Pamola, although it seems everything at Chimney Pond was climbed by the AMC in the 1920's, or Boy Scouts in the fifties, or Ben Townsend.  We were aiming for Pamola IV but ended up on a different route, and there was no evidence that it had been climbed before.    The cruxes include climbing past two 40 foot chockstones in the Chimney, and the route itself has a few easy fifth class moves and a fair amount of shrubbery.  It was a fun route in spite of loose rock, and follows an interesting spine of rock, like a crumbling vertical Knife Edge.    The PG-13 parts included the Chimney rubble crawl, and avoiding massive amounts of precarious loose rock all the way up...a lot of the climb should not be touched or it will fall.  There are some new rock scars but the risk was tolerable if you are accustomed to climbing loose rock.

name: Pamola IV Ridge
description: I stand corrected on the route. P3 that was listed below is actually the traiditional route for P4. The real PIII is further to the climbers left. I changed the PIII to P4 and PIV to P4rv(right variation) Thanks for the info Ben.    Over the course of 4 days in August 2012 me and two friends climbed on Katahdins South Basin and sent Pamolla IV(P4) ridge as pair with one rope on our last good day of weather. We took a shot Pamola IV right variation (P4rv) as a party of 3 with 2 ropes and retreated in a rainstorm by rappelling into the chimney and then rappelling past the chock stones. We got a good view of P4rv from P4. P4rv was less steep but had way more loose rock. Enough so that you'd be foolish not to stay roped up even on the 4rth class stuff. The chimney is to the right of P4rv and was grungey and loose. P4 had its share of loose rock but held plenty of solid protection placements. Areas to set belay stations were abundant. Scale/height can be deceiving so plan on an early start. We started from chimney pond at 8am and walked back into camp at nightfall.

name: Radio Nowhere
description: Climb the most prominent ridge between the Armadillo and the Flatiron. Route begins on the wet slabs up and climbers right from the start of the armadillo, hugging the right side of the canyon until you can begin ascending the ridge.    The crux pitch follows the ridgeline over terrifying hollow rock. It can be climbed at 5.5, but expect to make harder moves to avoid loose rock. Don't bother placing gear, it won't hold you. Airy, exposed, vegatated.

name: The Wind in the Willows
description: This route follows the long finger and hand crack left of the left side of the Armadillo, which eventually becomes the fist crack above the Armadillo flake. Though mentioned in the Armadillo comments as a variation, it really deserves to be described as a separate route.    1. Climb the wide crack in the corner on the left side of the Armadillo flake to a ledge. (5.8)    2. Traverse left into the obvious crack system (fingers at first, gradually getting wider). Follow the crack to an airy stance at the top of the Armadillo flake. (5.9) At this point you have joined the normal Armadillo route.    3. Climb the Armadillo fist crack to a comfortable stance. (5.7)    4. Follow corners and cracks on the left, moving up right to gain the ridge crest. (5.7)    4th and easy 5th for about 400' to a big ledge where it's comfortable to unrope.

name: The Wrong Chimney
description: Located to the right of THE Chimney, the "Wrong Chimney" provides access to the excellent class 4 / easy class 5 rib between the two chimneys. [NOTE: MtnPrjct member Ryan Gibbs suggests it is highly probable that this is the same gully/chimney as "False Chimney" in Rock Wilcox's winter ice climbing guide. ]    Scramble up into this chimney and climb it for about 200-300 feet, looking for an exit wall on the left as the central gully becomes steeper and more narrow, eventually the gully actual ends at a gravelly/poor-rock "headwall". [ I think we moved out on P5, but I have no recollection of pitch length, we would have been using a 40m (137 ft) or 150 ft rope.]  The exit wall was the crux ( 5.4 -5.5 ?)     Above the exit wall, the rib (keep a bit to the right, see photo of upper section) provides for pleasant and enjoyable Class 4 / easy Class 5 climbing to the ridge just south of Chimney Peak.     I also think that on another day we climbed THE Chimney, and moved right onto the rib that ends exactly on Chimney Peak.

name: Bear Butt
description: Sit start, move left to the good crimp, mild dyno to the good ledge, easy top-out.

name: Brooks Brothers Riot
description: Begin left, traverse across right on good holds and bad feet. Go up to the horn and either top out on the mossy side or bail out on the tree, making the v2-3 difference.

name: Entrance Crack
description: Follow the obvious left leaning wide crack that finishes in the center of the south face of split rock.

name: Split Personaliry
description: On the northwest corner of the Boulder is a crack that starts as tips and progresses up to offwidth. Jam away

name: Gassed Up
description: Mostly overhanging holds on this route require some fun maneuvering to get past the first move.

name: Sidle Up
description: Follow the arete on the left side of the face.

name: Walk Up
description: Far right side of slab as you're looking at it.
